{"title_page": "Mathieu Fleury", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = [[File:Mathieu Fleury 005 cropped version.jpg|160px|Mathieu Fleury in 2014]]\n| name = Mathieu Fleury\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|09|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]]\n| office = [[Ottawa City Council]]lor\n| term_start = December 1, 2010\n| term_end =  \n| predecessor = [[Georges B\u00e9dard]]\n| successor = Incumbent\n| party =  \n| religion =  \n| constituency = [[Rideau-Vanier Ward]] \n| majority = \n| spouse = Lai Hoang\n}}\n\n'''Mathieu Fleury''' (born September 26, 1985 in [[Ottawa}}, [[Ontario]]) is the [[Ottawa City Council]]lor of [[Rideau-Vanier Ward]]. He won the ward in the [[2010 Ottawa municipal election]], defeating the incumbent [[Georges B\u00e9dard]] in a narrow contest. He was reelected in the [[2014 Ottawa municipal election]].[https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/rideau-vanier-vote]\n\nFleury was born in Ottawa and raised in the [[Sandy Hill, Ottawa|Sandy Hill]] and [[Lower Town|Lowertown]] neighbourhoods. He attended [[\u00c9cole \u00e9l\u00e9mentaire publique Francojeunesse|Francojeunesse]] and [[\u00c9cole secondaire catholique Franco-Cit\u00e9|Franco-Cit\u00e9 School]] in Ottawa. He also has a [[Master of Science]] in [[Kinesiology|human kinetics]] with a concentration in [[Sport management|sports management]] and an Honours [[Bachelor of Science]] with a specialization in human kinetics from the [[University of Ottawa]].[https://ottawacitizen.com/sports/Survey+Mathieu+Fleury+Rideau+Vanier/3597705/story.html]\n\nFleury has a diverse background in sports, having interned for the [[Minister of Sport and Persons with Disabilities|Minister of State (Sport)]], volunteered at the 2010 Olympics for the [[Canadian Olympic Committee]], served as equipment manager for the [[Canada women's national baseball team|Canadian women's baseball team]] at the [[2008 Women's Baseball World Cup]], and served for ten years as a lifeguard supervisor for the city.[https://ottawacitizen.com/news/Mathieu+Fleury/3306281/story.html] He has also volunteered for various other sport organizations.\n\nFluery has made political donations to several Liberal politicians in the past, including [[Madeleine Meilleur]], [[Mona Fortier]] and [[Nathalie Des Rosiers]].<ref>https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/ottawa-votes-what-you-need-to-know-about-the-candidates-in-rideau-vanier</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2016 Ottawa sinkhole]]<ref>http://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/sinkhole-means-slump-for-nearby-ottawa-businesses-1.2951407</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110404114050/http://www.mathieufleury.ca/en/about Biography]\n\n{{Ottawa City Council}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fleury, Mathieu}}\n[[Category:Franco-Ontarian people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ottawa city councillors]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = [[File:Mathieu Fleury 005 cropped version.jpg|160px|Mathieu Fleury in 2014]]\n| name = Mathieu Fleury\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|09|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]]\n| office = [[Ottawa City Council]]lor\n| term_start = December 1, 2010\n| term_end =  \n| predecessor = [[Georges B\u00e9dard]]\n| successor = Incumbent\n| party =  \n| religion =  \n| constituency = [[Rideau-Vanier Ward]] \n| majority = \n| spouse = Lai Hoang\n}}\n\n'''Mathieu Fleury''' (born September 26, 1985 in [[Ottawa|Ottawa, Ontario]]) is the [[Ottawa City Council]]lor of [[Rideau-Vanier Ward]]. He won the ward in the [[2010 Ottawa municipal election]], defeating the incumbent [[Georges B\u00e9dard]] in a narrow contest. He was reelected in the [[2014 Ottawa municipal election]].[https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/rideau-vanier-vote]\n\nFleury was born in Ottawa and raised in the [[Sandy Hill, Ottawa|Sandy Hill]] and [[Lower Town|Lowertown]] neighbourhoods. He attended [[\u00c9cole \u00e9l\u00e9mentaire publique Francojeunesse|Francojeunesse]] and [[\u00c9cole secondaire catholique Franco-Cit\u00e9|Franco-Cit\u00e9 School]] in Ottawa. He also has a [[Master of Science]] in [[Kinesiology|human kinetics]] with a concentration in [[Sport management|sports management]] and an Honours [[Bachelor of Science]] with a specialization in human kinetics from the [[University of Ottawa]].[https://ottawacitizen.com/sports/Survey+Mathieu+Fleury+Rideau+Vanier/3597705/story.html]\n\nFleury has a diverse background in sports, having interned for the [[Minister of Sport and Persons with Disabilities|Minister of State (Sport)]], volunteered at the 2010 Olympics for the [[Canadian Olympic Committee]], served as equipment manager for the [[Canada women's national baseball team|Canadian women's baseball team]] at the [[2008 Women's Baseball World Cup]], and served for ten years as a lifeguard supervisor for the city.[https://ottawacitizen.com/news/Mathieu+Fleury/3306281/story.html] He has also volunteered for various other sport organizations.\n\nFluery has made political donations to several Liberal politicians in the past, including [[Madeleine Meilleur]], [[Mona Fortier]] and [[Nathalie Des Rosiers]].<ref>https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/ottawa-votes-what-you-need-to-know-about-the-candidates-in-rideau-vanier</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2016 Ottawa sinkhole]]<ref>http://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/sinkhole-means-slump-for-nearby-ottawa-businesses-1.2951407</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110404114050/http://www.mathieufleury.ca/en/about Biography]\n\n{{Ottawa City Council}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fleury, Mathieu}}\n[[Category:Franco-Ontarian people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ottawa city councillors]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathieu_Fleury"}
{"title_page": "Mossley (ward)", "text_new": "{{about||the town|Mossley}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name          = Mossley (Tameside)\n| settlement_type        = [[Electoral ward]]\n| image_skyline           = Mossley (Tameside Council Ward).png\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = Mossley within Tameside\n| image_shield            = Coat of arms of Tameside Metropolitan Borough Council.png\n| shield_alt              = \n| etymology               = \n| nickname                = \n| motto                   = Industry and Integrity\n| coordinates            = {{coord|53.5164|-2.0316|region:GB-HCK_type:adm3rd|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type       = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name       = [[United Kingdom]]\n| subdivision_type1      = [[Countries of the United Kingdom|Constituent country]]\n| subdivision_name1      = [[England]]\n| subdivision_type2      = [[Regions of England|Region]]\n| subdivision_name2      = [[North West England]]\n| subdivision_type3      = [[Ceremonial counties of England|County]]\n| subdivision_name3      = [[Greater Manchester]]\n| subdivision_type4      = [[Metropolitan borough]]\n| subdivision_name4      = [[Tameside]]\n| established_title      = Created\n| established_date       = 2004\n| named_for              = [[Stalybridge]] and [[Hyde, Greater Manchester|Hyde]]\n| government_footnotes    = {{space}} UK Parliament constituency: [[Stalybridge and Hyde (UK Parliament constituency)|Stalybridge and Hyde]]\n| government_type         = [[Unicameral]]\n| governing_body          = [[Tameside Metropolitan Borough Council]]\n| leader_party            = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| leader_title            = Leader of the Council\n| leader_name             = Brenda Warrington\n| leader_title1           = Councillor\n| leader_name1            = Stephen Homer ([[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]])\n| leader_title2           = Councillor\n| leader_name2            = Tafheen Sharif ([[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]])\n| leader_title3           = Councillor\n| leader_name3            = Jack Homer ([[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]])\n| area_total_sq_mi       = \n| population_total       = \n| footnotes              = \n| website                 = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''Mossley''' is an [[ward (politics)|electoral ward]] of [[Tameside]], [[England]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Your Councillors by Ward |url=http://tameside.moderngov.co.uk/mgMemberIndex.aspx?FN=WARD&VW=LIST&PIC=0 | website = tameside.moderngov.co.uk | publisher = [[Tameside Metropolitan Borough Council]] | access-date = 5 January 2018}}</ref> It is represented in [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Westminster]] by [[Jonathan Reynolds]] Labour Co-operative [[Member of parliament#United Kingdom|MP]] for [[Stalybridge and Hyde (UK Parliament constituency)|Stalybridge and Hyde]].<ref>{{cite web | title= Jonathan Reynolds MP | url = http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/jonathan-reynolds/4119 | website = parliament.uk | publisher = [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]] | accessdate=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Councillors ==\nThe ward is represented by three councillors: Stephen Homer (Lab),<ref>{{cite web | title = Councillor Stephen Homer | url = http://tameside.moderngov.co.uk/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=1014 | website = tameside.moderngov.co.uk | publisher = [[Tameside Metropolitan Borough Council]] | access-date = 14 May 2018}}</ref> Tafheen Sharif (Lab),<ref>{{cite web | title = Councillor Tafheen Sharif | url = http://tameside.moderngov.co.uk/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=425 | website = tameside.moderngov.co.uk | publisher = [[Tameside Metropolitan Borough Council]] | access-date = 5 January 2018}}</ref> and Jack Homer (Lab).<ref>{{cite web | title = Councillor Jack Homer | url = http://tameside.moderngov.co.uk/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=424 | website = tameside.moderngov.co.uk | publisher = [[Tameside Metropolitan Borough Council]] | access-date = 5 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitab