al chord ({{harvnb|Burkholder, Grout, and Palisca 2009|838, 885}}; {{harvnb|Simms|1986|loc=65\u201366}}).{{failed verification|date=November 2012|reason=Doesn't mention \"neotonal\", \"neotonality\", \"neotonalities\", \"new tonality\", or \"new tonalities\"}}\n\n==References==\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Burkholder, Grout, and Palisca|2009}}|reference=Burkholder, J.  Peter, Donald Jay Grout, and Claude V. Palisca. 2009. ''A History of Western Music'', eighth edition. New York: W. W. Norton & Company. {{ISBN|9780393931259}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Salzman|1974}}|reference=Salzman, Eric. 1974. ''Twentieth-Century Music: An Introduction'', second edition. Prentice-Hall History of Music Series. Englewood Cliffs, NJ: Prentice-Hall. {{ISBN|9780139350153}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Silberman|2006}}|reference=Silberman, Peter Scott. 2006. \"Neighbor Spaces: A Theory of Harmonic Embellishment for Twentieth-Century Neotonal Music\". PhD diss. Rochester: University of Rochester, Eastman School of Music.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Simms|1986}}|reference=Simms, Bryan R. 1986. ''Music of the Twentieth Century: Style and Structure''. New York: Schirmer Books. {{ISBN|0-02-872580-8}}.}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Berger|1963}}|reference=Berger, Arthur. 1963. \"Problems of Pitch Organization in Stravinsky\". ''Perspectives of New Music'' 2, no. 2 (Spring-Summer): 11\u201343.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Dragone|[2003]}}|reference=[Dragone, Luann]. [2003]. [https://web.archive.org/web/20121029012008/http://www.omnidisc.com/Talma/Compositions.html Introduction] Louise Talma Society website (archive from 29 October 2012, accessed 22 April 2015).}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Hermann|1987}}|reference=Hermann, Richard. 1987. \"Thoughts on Voice-Leading and Set Theory in 'Neo-Tonal' Works: The 'Hymne' from Stravinsky's ''S\u00e9r\u00e9nade en la''\". ''Theory and Practice'' 12:27\u201353.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Kinne|2000}}|reference=Kinne, Michael. 2000. ''Die Pr\u00e4fixe  post-, pr\u00e4- und neo-: Beitr\u00e4ge zur Lehn-Wortbildung''. Forschungen des Instituts f\u00fcr deutsche Sprache: Studien zur deutschen Sprache 18. T\u00fcbingen: Gunter Narr Verlag. {{ISBN|3823351486}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Rihm|1986}}|reference=[[Wolfgang Rihm|Rihm, Wolfgang]]. 1986. \"Neo-Tonalit\u00e4t?\" ''MusikTexte: Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Neue Musik'', no. 14:14\u201317.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Straus|2000}}|reference=Straus, Joseph N. 2000. ''Introduction to Post-Tonal Theory'', second edition. Upper Saddle River: Prentice-Hall. {{ISBN|0-13-014331-6}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Wile|1995}}|reference=Wile, Kip. 1995. \"Collection in Neocentric Music: A Study in Theory and Analysis of the Music of Debussy, Stravinsky, Scriabin, Bart\u00f3k, and Ravel\". Ph.D. dissertation. Chicago: University of Chicago.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Williams|1997}}|reference=Williams, J. Kent. 1997. ''Theories and Analyses of Twentieth-Century Music''. Fort Worth: Harcourt Brace and Company. {{ISBN|015500316X}}.}}\n\n{{Tonality}}\n{{Modernism (music)|state=autocollapse}}\n\n[[Category:Modernism (music)]]\n[[Category:Tonality]]\n", "name_user": "Grimes2", "label": "safe", "comment": "format", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neotonality"}
{"title_page": "Edward L. Feightner", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|United States Navy admiral}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|birth_name            = Edward Lewis Feightner\n|birth_date            = {{birth date |1919|10|14}}\n|birth_place           = [[Lima, Ohio|Lima]], [[Ohio]], U.S.\n|death_date            = {{death date and age|2020|4|1|1919|10|14}}\n|death_place           =[[Coeur d'Alene, Idaho|Coeur d'Alene]], [[Idaho]], U.S.\n|placeofburial         = \n|placeofburial_label   = Place of burial\n|image                 = RADM Edward Feightner 19700715.jpeg\n|caption               = Feightner in 1970\n|nickname              =Whitey\n|allegiance            ={{Flag|United States of America}}\n|branch                = [[File:United States Department of the Navy Seal.svg|25px]] [[United States Navy]]\n|serviceyears= 1941&ndash;1974 (33 years)\n|rank=[[File:US-O8 insignia.svg|30px]] [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear admiral]]\n|current position=\n|commands= {{USS|Okinawa|LPH-3}} <br/> {{USS|Chikaskia|AO-54}} <br/> Air Group 10 <br/> [[VFA-11|VF-11]]\n|battles=[[World War II]] <br/> [[Cold War]]\n|awards= [[Legion of Merit]] (2) <br/> [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] (4) <br/> [[Air Medal]] (12) <br/> [[Navy Commendation Medal]] <br/> [[Congressional Gold Medal]]\n|relations=\n|laterwork= Aerospace Industry\n}}\n[[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] '''Edward Lewis Feightner''' (October 14, 1919 \u2013 April 1, 2020) was a [[United States Navy]] officer who fought in a number of significant battles in the [[World War II]] [[Asiatic-Pacific Theater|Pacific Theater of Operations]]. During two combat tours, he shot down nine enemy aircraft to become a [[flying ace]].\n\nHe was an early member of the [[Blue Angels]] flight demonstration squadron and flew the lead \"solo\" position. His work as a [[test pilot]] included aircraft, electronic systems, and operational tactics such as developing techniques for delivering nuclear weapons from small fighter aircraft. He commanded increasingly larger air units including [[VFA-11|VF-11]] and Carrier Air Group Ten as well as training organizations that helped the Navy transition from propeller to jet aircraft. He commanded two Navy ships, served as the head of Navy Fighter Design, and was a key contributor to fighter studies that resulted in the development of jet aircraft that {{as of|2015|lc=y}} are still in active service.\n\nFeightner was the only pilot to land the dash-1 variant of the [[Vought F7U Cutlass]] aboard a carrier. He led VF-11 to become the first Atlantic fleet unit in which every pilot received the coveted \"E\" award in a single exercise. After retiring from the Navy, Feightner promoted aviation and shared his experiences with others.\n\n==Early life==\nFeightner was born on October 14, 1919 in [[Lima, Ohio]], a small town in the northwest part of the state, to Amos Evan and Mary Story (Roths) Feightner.{{sfnp|Wooldridge|1993|p=78}}<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=stpsnwT7jFoC&pg=PA510&dq=%22Amos+Evan+and+Mary+Story+(Roths)+Feightner%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiBv8Th7M7oAhULheAKHd7BA9sQ6AEwAHoECAIQAQ]</ref> He attended [[Findlay College]] in Findlay, Ohio{{sfnp|Astor|2005|p=3}} and learned to fly in the [[Civilian Pilot Training Program]] (CPTP). The CPTP was a flight training program sponsored by the United States government to increase the number of civilian pilots and thereby create a pool of trained aviators from which the military could draw.<ref name=USN_Oral_History_Transcript_p2>{{cite book |last = Eanett |year=2005 |title=Interview Transcript |page=2}}</ref> By 1940, Feightner received his [[private pilot license]].{{sfnp|Astor|2005|p=3}} He graduated from Findlay College in 1941.{{sfnp|Wooldridge|1993|p=78}}\n\n==World War II service==\nWith war approaching and because of his strong desire to fly, Feightner attempted to sign up with the [[United States Army Air Corps]]. But he faced an eight-month delay before acceptance since the Army flight program could not cope with the large influx of people. When Feightner found that the Navy would accept him immediately, he made up his mind to pursue naval aviation.<ref name=USN_Oral_History_Transcript_p3>{{cite book |last = Eanett |year=2005 |title=Interview Transcript |page=3}}</ref> On June 16, 1941, Feightner enlisted in the [[United States Navy Reserve]] and entered the [[Aviation Cadet Training Program (USN)|Naval Aviation Cadet Training Program]]. He completed flight training at [[Naval Air Station Corpus Christi]], Texas on April 3, 1942 thereby earning his [[Commission (document)|commission]] as an [[Ensign (rank)#United States|ensign]] and designation as a [[United States Naval Aviator|naval aviator]].{{sfnp|Wooldridge|1993|p=78}}<ref name=USN_Oral_History_Summary>{{cite book |last= Eanett |year=2005 |title = Interview Summary}}</ref> He finished advanced carrier training at [[Naval Air Station Norfolk]] and received orders to [[VF-5]] aboard {{USS|Yorktown|CV-5}}.{{sfnp|Astor|2005|p=128}} ''Yorktown'', however, was sunk by the Japanese at the [[Battle of Midway]] before Feightner could arrive.{{sfnp|Tillman|1995|p=15}} Feightner was reassigned to [[VF-3]] at [[Naval Air Station Pu'unene]] on Maui, Hawaii. VF-3's commanding officer was [[Edward O'Hare|Edward \"Butch\" O'Hare]] who had recently returned from a combat tour in the Pacific as the Navy's first fighter ace.<ref name=USN_Oral_History_Transcript_p3/> O'Hare gave Feightner the nickname \"Whitey\" for his inability to [[Sun tanning|tan]] despite hours in the sun during the squadron's many [[spearfishing]] trips.{{sfnp|Veronico|2005|p=46}}\n\n===VF-10 Grim Reapers===\n[[File:F4F-3 new pitot tube of later model.jpg|left|thumb|Grumman F4F-3 Wildcat from early 1942]]\nIn October 1942, Feightner was assigned to [[VF-10]], the ''Grim Reapers'', aboard {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6}} flying the [[Grumman F4F Wildcat]].<ref name=USN_Oral_History_Transcript_p3/> The [[commanding officer]] of VF-10 was [[James H. Flatley]] whom Feightner described as \"a true leader [who] epitomizes what you think of as a squadron commander.\"{{sfnp|Astor|2005|p=43}} ''Enterprise'' left Pearl Harbor on October 16, 1942 for the South Pacific as part of [[Task Force]] King.{{sfnp|Astor|2005|p=127}} Less than ten days later, Feightner performed his first night carrier landing after the search and attack group for which he provided cover became lost and did not return to the carrier until after dark.{{sfnp|Astor|2005|p=129}} On October 26, 1942, during the [[Battle of the Santa Cruz Islands]], Feightner shot down his first enemy aircraft&mdash;an [[Aichi D3A]] [[dive bomber]] that was attacking ''Enterprise.''{{sfnp|Astor|2005|p=134}}{{sfnp|Lundstrom|2005|p=413}} He was also credited with a probable kill of another aircraft.{{sfnp|Astor|2005|p=134}} Feightner was awarded an [[Air Medal]] and gold [[award star]] for his actions that day.<ref name=USN_Oral_History_Summary/>\n\n{{Quote box\n|align=right\n|width=210px\n|quote=\"You're a fighting fool, aren't you!\"\n|source=J. Flately, VF-10 CO to Feightner after shooting down three planes in one day{{sfnp|Ewing|2002|p=168}}\n|}}\n[[File:RennellBattleMap2.jpg|thumb|right|Japanese aerial attack (dotted red line) on ''Chicago'' (yellow dot) on the morning of January 30. Black arrows are U.S. carrier fighter aircraft.]]\nAfter several weeks of repair, ''Enterprise'' sortied to oppose an [[Military of Japan|Imperial Japanese]] battle fleet that was threatening the [[Solomon Islands]].{{sfnp|Ewing|2002|p=147}} The Japanese [[convoy]] included eleven transports with over seven thousand soldiers headed down the \"Slot\" to Guadalcanal to retake [[Henderson Field (Guadalcanal)|Henderson Field]].{{sfnp|Ewing|2002|pp=151&ndash;3}} On November 14, 1942, Feightner protected U.S. dive bombers and [[Strafing|strafed]] enemy vessels during the strikes that destroyed seven of the troop carriers&mdash;a significant event in the [[Naval Battle of Guadalcanal]].{{sfnp|Ewing|2002|pp=151&ndash;3}}{{sfnp|Astor|2005|p=150}} After the attacks, VF-10 remained at Henderson Field on Guadalcanal to reinforce the [[1st Marine Division (United States)|1st Marine Division]] and deal with the Japanese ships and troops from the remaining transports that had intentionally beached themselves.{{sfnp|Astor|2005|p=151}}{{sfnp|Ewing|2002|pp=155&ndash;6}} Conditions on the island were primitive and dangerous for pilots of the [[Cactus Air Force]]. Many of the servicemen came down with [[malaria]]. Japanese soldiers hid in trees and waited to ambush the Americans. Sleep was disrupted by night bombardment.{{sfnp|Astor|2005|p=152}} Fortunately, Feightner had to endure the hazardous conditions on Guadalcanal less than a week, as VF-10 left their old aircraft at Henderson Field and returned to ''Enterprise'' on November 25, 1942, where they received new F4Fs.{{sfnp|Astor|2005|p=155}}{{sfnp|Ewing|2002|p=156}}\n\nOn January 30, 1943, the second day of the [[Battle of Rennell Island]], Feightner shot down three [[Mitsubishi G4M]] \"Betty\" torpedo bombers in a single engagement.{{sfnp|Ewing|2002|p=168}}{{sfnp|Tillman|1995|p=54}} In this engagement, a force of twelve Bettys approaching ''Enterprise'' were intercepted by VF-10 aircraft.{{sfnp|Astor|2005|p=155}} The Bettys turned away from ''Enterprise'' and went after {{USS|Chicago|CA-29}}, a heavy cruiser that had been disabled the night before. VF-10 destroyed six of the Bettys before they could reach the cruiser, but the remaining aircraft released their torpedoes with devastating effect&mdash;''Chicago'' sank within minutes. Two more of the Bettys were dispatched by the pursuing VF-10 Wildcats as they passed the ring of destroyers that had been protecting the cruiser. Flatley shot down another and the remaining three fell to his wingman, Feightner, who had been delayed due to a balky engine but arrived at just the right time.{{sfnp|Ewing|2002|pp=165&ndash;8}}{{sfnp|Astor|2005|p=158}} Feightner was awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] and an air medal for downing three aircraft on that day and ended his first combat tour with four confirmed kills.{{sfnp|Ewing|2002|pp=165&ndash;8}}\n\n===VF-8===\n[[File:Hellcats F6F-3, May 1943.jpg|thumb|right|Grumman F6F-3 Hellcats in tricolor camouflage, May 1943]]\nIn May 1943, Feightner received orders to [[VF-8 (1943\u201345)|VF-8]] flying the [[Grumman F6F Hellcat]] at [[Naval Auxiliary Air Station Pungo]]&mdash;a satellite airfield near [[Naval Station Norfolk]].{{sfnp|Linder|2005|p=191}} This second squadron to be designated VF-8 was established on June 1, 1943 and led by Lt Cdr William M. Collins Jr. who would himself become a nine-victory ace.{{sfnp|Tillman|1996|p=8}}<ref name=Lineage>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Lineage for Fighter Squadrons |url = http://www.history.navy.mil/download/vf-lin.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140610181147/http://www.history.navy.mil/download/vf-lin.pdf |archivedate=June 10, 2014 |publisher = Naval History & Heritage Command |location = Washington, D. C. |accessdate = August 20, 2015}}</ref> Fighting Eight was initially assigned to the new carrier {{USS|Intrepid|CV-11}} that had been launched just weeks prior.<ref name=CVW8_GS>{{cite web |title = Carrier Air Wing Eight (CVW 8) |url = http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/agency/navy/cvw8.htm |publisher = GlobalSecurity.org |location = Alexandria, Virginia |accessdate = October 15, 2011}}</ref><ref name=Intrepid_GS>{{cite web |title = CV 11 Intrepid |url = http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/agency/navy/cv-11.htm |publisher = GlobalSecurity.org |location = Alexandria, Virginia |accessdate = October 15, 2011}}</ref> During ''Intrepid''{{'}}s [[sea trial]]s in the fall of 1943, Feightner performed initial takeoffs, landings, and catapult shots flying the F6F.{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|pp=47\u20138}}\n\nIn March 1944, [[Carrier Air Wing Eight]] began operations from {{USS|Bunker Hill|CV-17}}.{{sfnp|Tillman|2000|p=64}} Part of the [[Fast Carrier Task Force]] TF 58 commanded by Vice Admiral [[Marc A. Mitscher]], ''Bunker Hill'' participated in a series of attacks against Japanese positions in the Pacific Theater of Operations.{{sfnp|Tillman|2000|p=52}} VF-8 saw their first combat during a two-day strike on [[Palau]].{{sfnp|Tillman|2000|p=64}} On the first day of the raid, March 30, 1944, Feightner became an ace when he shot down a [[Mitsubishi A6M Zero|Mitsubishi A6M]] \"Zeke\" over the island of [[Peleliu]].{{sfnp|Hammel|1998|p=335}} The Palau battle also marked the first combat use of the 'Berger' Gradient Pressure Suit&mdash;an air inflatable [[G-suit]] that allowed a pilot to maneuver his aircraft more aggressively without [[G-LOC|blacking out]]. The \"Z-suit\" proved so successful that all but three of the VF-8 pilots chose to wear the equipment.{{sfnp|Tillman|2000|p=64}}\n\n[[File:Fighter plane contrails in the sky.jpg|thumb|left|225px|Fighter aircraft [[contrail]]s mark the sky over Task Force 58 on June 19, 1944]]\nAs TF 58 followed the U.S. strategy of [[Leapfrogging (strategy)|leapfrogging]] toward Japan, Feightner participated in strikes at the [[Yap]] [[coral atoll]] of [[Woleai]] helping to isolate the Japanese garrison there.<ref name=USN_Oral_History_Summary/> At the end of April, the task force returned to [[Chuuk Lagoon|Truk]] in the [[Caroline Islands]].{{sfnp|Tillman|1996|p=21}} Once a major Japanese stronghold, Truk had been badly damaged during [[Operation Hailstone]] earlier that year, but the Japanese had since reinforced the island with aircraft from [[Rabaul]].{{sfnp|Tillman|1996|p=20}} On April 29, 1944, Feightner shot down a Zeke over Truk, raising his total to six aircraft destroyed.{{sfnp|Tillman|1996|p=21}}\n\nIn June 1944, the U.S. initiated the [[Mariana and Palau Islands campaign]]. Feightner flew during the [[Battle of the Philippine Sea]] that was better known to American pilots as the 'Great Marianas Turkey Shoot' due to the overwhelming losses inflicted upon the naval air forces of Japan.{{sfnp|Tillman|1996|p=22}} He fought in a series of actions over the next few months including the [[Battle of Saipan]], the [[Battle of Guam (1944)|Battle of Guam]], strikes on [[Okinawa]], and the [[Battle of Tinian]].{{sfnp|Tillman|2005|p=1222}}\n\nAs U.S. forces pushed toward the [[Philippines]], the fast carriers of Task Force 38 (TF 38) moved to subdue Japanese air power on the island of [[Taiwan|Formosa]]&mdash;known today as Taiwan.{{sfnp|Tillman|1996|p=49}} During the [[Aerial Battle of Taiwan\u2013Okinawa]], VF-8 destroyed thirty aircraft near Taien Airfield. Flying in this battle on October 12, 1944, Feightner shot down three Zekes (although at least one source{{sfnp|Stanaway|2006|p=19}} states the aircraft were \"Oscars\") bringing his total to nine aircraft destroyed.{{sfnp|Tillman|1996|p=50}} Feightner continued to fly missions with VF-8 until ''Bunker Hill'' returned to the United States for an overhaul in November 1944.<ref name=Bunker_Hill>{{cite web |title = USS Bunker Hill (CV-17) |url = http://www.history.navy.mil/photos/sh-usn/usnsh-b/cv17.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014162655/http://www.history.navy.mil/photos/sh-usn/usnsh-b/cv17.htm |archivedate=October 14, 2012 |publisher = United States Navy |location = Washington, D. C. |date = September 24, 2001 |accessdate = August 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Fighter Instructor===\nUpon returning to the United States in November 1944, Feightner was assigned as a fighter instructor with [[VF-98]] at [[Los Alamitos Army Airfield|NAS Los Alamitos]] in [[Orange County, California|Orange County]], [[California]], and later at [[Jacqueline Cochran Regional Airport|Naval Air Facility (NAF) Thermal]] in [[Thermal, California]]. Near the end of World War II in 1945, Feightner was assigned as gunnery officer to [[VF-21]] at [[Naval Air Station North Island|NAS San Diego]] in California.<ref name=USN_Oral_History_Summary/>\n\n===Victory credits===\nThe following table summarizes Feightner's aerial victories and provides the date, number of aircraft destroyed, types of aircraft destroyed, and the battle at which the victory occurred. In total, he was assessed with 9 destroyed and 4 probables.<ref name=USN_Oral_History_Transcript_p3/> However, another source claims two probable kills for Feightner.{{sfnp|Tillman|1995|p=92}}\n[[File:Edward Feightner Nine Victories 1944.jpg|thumb|Lt. Feightner with nine victories]]\n<!--[[File:F6F-3 over California 1943.jpg|thumb|U.S. Navy Grumman F6F-3 Hellcat]] -->\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Date\n! No\n! Type\n! Battle/Location\n! Aircraft flown\n! Unit\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |October 26, 1942\n|align=\"center\" |1\n|align=\"center\" |[[Aichi D3A|D3A]] \"Val\"\n|align=\"center\" |[[Battle of the Santa Cruz Islands]]\n|align=\"center\" |[[Grumman F4F Wildcat|F4F Wildcat]]\n|align=\"center\" |[[VF-101|VF-10]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |January 30, 1943\n|align=\"center\" |3\n|align=\"center\" |[[Mitsubishi G4M|G4M]] \"Betty\"\n|align=\"center\" |[[Battle of Rennell Island]]\n|align=\"center\" |F4F Wildcat\n|align=\"center\" |VF-10\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |March 30, 1944\n|align=\"center\" |1\n|align=\"center\" |[[Mitsubishi A6M Zero|A6M]] \"Zeke\"\n|align=\"center\" |Raid on [[Peleliu]]\n|align=\"center\" |[[Grumman F6F Hellcat|F6F Hellcat]]\n|align=\"center\" |[[VF-8 (1943\u201345)|VF-8]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |April 29, 1944\n|align=\"center\" |1\n|align=\"center\" |A6M \"Zeke\"\n|align=\"center\" |Raid on [[Chuuk State|Truk]]\n|align=\"center\" |[[Grumman F6F Hellcat|F6F Hellcat]]\n|align=\"center\" |VF-8\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |October 12, 1944\n|align=\"center\" |3\n|align=\"center\" |A6M \"Zeke\"\n|align=\"center\" |[[Aerial Battle of Taiwan\u2013Okinawa]]\n|align=\"center\" |[[Grumman F6F Hellcat|F6F Hellcat]]\n|align=\"center\" |VF-8\n|-\n|\n|align=\"center\" |9\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n==Post-war service==\n\n===Flight test===\n<!--[[File:F7U-1 CVB-41 launch2 1941.jpg|right|thumb|Feightner flying an F7U-1 off USS Midway in 1951]] -->\nAfter serving for several years in staff assignments, Feightner received orders to attend the [[United States Naval Test Pilot School|U.S. Navy Test Pilot School]] at [[Naval Air Station Patuxent River|NAS Patuxent River]] in Maryland.{{sfnp|Veronico|2005|p=46}} He graduated in July 1949 with the school's second class and served with the Flight Test Division at the Naval Air Test Center where he flew a variety of aircraft including helicopters and the Navy's largest transport, the [[Lockheed R6V Constitution]]. Feightner also tested the [[Grumman F8F Bearcat]], the [[Vought F4U Corsair]], and the [[Grumman F7F Tigercat]].<ref name=USN_Oral_History_Transcript_p12>{{cite book |last = Eanett |year=2005 |title=Interview Transcript |page=12}}</ref> When Colonel [[Charles Lindbergh]] came to evaluate the Tigercat, Feightner, as F7F project pilot, provided the pre-flight instruction.<ref name=USN_Oral_History_Transcript_pp_14_15>{{cite book |last = Eanett |year=2005 |title=Interview Transcript |pages=14&ndash;15}}</ref>\n\n[[File:F7U-1 CVB-41 landing 1951.jpg|left|thumb|Feightner landing F7U-1, No. 415, on the USS Midway in 1951]]\nFeightner was assigned as the Navy's project pilot for the [[Vought F7U Cutlass]], a carrier-based jet [[fighter-bomber]] with [[swept wing]]s and an unusual [[Tailless aircraft|tailless]] design.{{sfnp|Powell|2008|p=37}} From July 23 to August 14, 1951, he performed carrier suitability tests of the Cutlass on board the {{USS|Midway|CV-41|6}}.{{sfnp|Gardner|2010|p=72}} Feightner survived a number of near-fatal incidents in the Cutlass. During a test using the NAS Patuxent River air field catapult, an engine exploded and caught fire on takeoff. Unable to eject at such a low altitude, Feightner made use of a low spot in the river bank to turn the aircraft and return safely to the field where firefighters extinguished the burning engine.{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|p=82}} On July 23, 1951, he performed the first (and only) carrier takeoff and landing of the dash-1 variant on the aircraft carrier USS ''Midway''.{{sfnp|Powell|2008|p=37}} Landing the Cutlass was hazardous due to the extreme nose-up attitude that restricted visibility forward and below. Feightner was unable to see the flight deck and relied on the [[Landing Signal Officer]] (LSO) to provide the indication to reduce engine power. Despite assistance from the LSO, Feightner landed short of the desired position and nearly [[ramp strike|struck the ramp]].{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|p=83}} Although the fleet received the improved F7U-3, the Cutlass did not live up to its potential and remained in service less than four years.{{sfnp|Grossnick|1995|p=481}}\n\n===Blue Angels===\nIn January 1952, Feightner received orders to the U.S. Navy's flight demonstration squadron&mdash;the Blue Angels. The squadron had been directed to add the Cutlass to their performance although neither Feightner nor Blue Angels commander [[Roy Marlin Voris|\"Butch\" Voris]] believed the aircraft was ready for formation flying.{{sfnp|Wilcox|2006|p=239}} The F7U was the Navy's first operational aircraft fitted with a hydraulic [[flight control system]] and reliability was still poor.{{sfnp|Veronico|2005|p=46}} In the event of failure, the mechanical backup system required eleven seconds before control was restored.{{sfnp|Veronico|2005|p=47}} The solution was to fly the F7Us separately from the rest of the team thereby creating the diamond and solo roles that remain to the present day. Feightner recruited former Blue Angel Lt. Harding C. \"Mac\" Macknight to fly the second Cutlass.{{sfnp|Wilcox|2006|p=239}}\n\n[[File:F7U-1 Blue Angels 1952.jpg|right|thumb|Blue Angels F7U-1 Cutlass in 1952]]\nAt the start of the 1952 show season, fuel control problems grounded the team's [[Grumman F9F Panther]]s leaving the Cutlasses to put on the primary demonstration between March and June.{{sfnp|Veronico|2005|p=50}} During a show at [[Saufley Field]] in Florida, Feightner experienced a total loss of hydraulics on a full afterburner takeoff and steep climb. While trying to gain enough altitude for ejection he was able to stay with the aircraft until the back up control system engaged. He clipped trees on the end of the runway, causing the left engine to flame out. With hydraulic fluid streaming back in a bright flame, he made a hard turn and got the plane back on the runway, much to the excitement of the crowd.{{sfnp|Veronico|2005|p=49}} Feightner and Macknight performed maneuvers that showed off the best attributes of the F7U. The two solos would approach each other from opposite ends of the runway and, after passing each other, would roll the aircraft, deploy [[Air brake (aircraft)|speed brakes]], and light [[afterburner]]s. In Feightner's opinion, \"There just is not an airplane like it anywhere.\"{{sfnp|Veronico|2005|p=51}}\n\nMaintenance issues and additional near-fatal accidents put an end to Blue Angel Cutlass performances.{{sfnp|Veronico|2005|p=52}} While traveling to an airshow at [[Naval Air Station Glenview]] in [[Chicago, Illinois]], both F7Us experienced in-flight emergencies. One of Feightner's engines failed shortly after takeoff, but before he could land, Macknight's right engine caught fire and the left engine quit soon after. Although Feightner called for him to eject, Macknight stayed with the burning aircraft and landed at Glenview.{{sfnp|Veronico|2005|p=53}} With the runway closed, Feightner was redirected to make his landing at Chicago's former Orchard Airpark, which had been expanded and renamed [[O'Hare International Airport|O'Hare Airport]] after Feightner's former VF-3 commander. The runway had just been completed and was covered with peach baskets to prevent aircraft from landing until it was opened. Feightner was told to ignore the baskets and land on the new runway. As a result, Feightner's F7U became the first aircraft to land on the new runway for Chicago's O'Hare International Airport.{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|p=86}} After yet another in-flight emergency resulted in a forced landing at [[Naval Air Station Memphis]], the F7Us were given to the station's training center.{{sfnp|Veronico|2005|p=56}}\n\n===Return to testing===\nIn September 1952, Feightner returned to flight test as the development officer for Air Development Squadron Three ([[VX-3 (Squadron)|VX-3]]).<ref name=USN_Oral_History_Transcript_p6/> VX-3 was located at [[Atlantic City Air National Guard Base|NAS Atlantic City]], [[New Jersey]], and was responsible for testing fighter aircraft, systems, and munitions.{{sfnp|Lurie|2004|p=48}} In this new role, he tested aircraft systems (rather than the airplanes themselves) and determined what tactics would most effectively utilize those systems.<ref name=USN_Oral_History_Transcript_p6>{{cite book |last = Eanett |title=Interview Transcript |year=2005 |page=6}}</ref>\n\nOn December 3, 1953, Feightner participated in the first public demonstration of the [[Aircraft catapult#Steam catapult|steam catapult]] chosen  to launch heavy jet aircraft from the short decks of aircraft carriers. Flying a propeller-driven [[Douglas A-1 Skyraider|AD Skyraider]] at the [[Naval Air Material Center]] in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], Feightner described the steam-powered launch as \"much better for the pilot\" due to the relatively gentle start that eliminated the shock of other catapult techniques.<ref name=NAN_Feb_54>{{cite journal |last= |first=|date=February 1954 |title=From David to Brown |journal=Naval Aviation News |volume= |issue= |pages=1&ndash;2 |publisher=United States Navy |location=Washington, D.C. |doi= |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/nan/backissues/1950s/1954/feb54.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141201231458/http://www.history.navy.mil/nan/backissues/1950s/1954/feb54.pdf |archivedate=December 1, 2014 |accessdate=August 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFeightner contributed to the development of weapon delivery tactics for the [[McDonnell F2H Banshee]].{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|p=98}} The F2H-2B was modified for the attack role and had strengthened wings and pylons to accommodate a heavy weapon such as the  [[Mark 7 nuclear bomb|Mark 7]] or [[Mark 8 nuclear bomb]].{{sfnp|Francillon|1990|p=81}} The F2H-2B testing on which Feightner worked included the longest non-stop, round trip flight from a carrier&mdash;more than 2,800 miles. He also participated in an 18-hour, low-level, non-stop, round-trip flight from a carrier with weapon delivery in a Douglas AD-3 Skyraider.{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|p=98}}\n\n==Aviation commands==\n\n===VF-11 Red Rippers===\n[[File:VF11 Rippers Aerial Bombing 1956.png|left|thumb|VF-11 pilots receive \"E\" award for aerial bombing. Feightner is kneeling at left]]\nIn January 1955, Feightner assumed command of VF-11 also known as ''The Red Rippers.''{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|p=103}} Flying the McDonnell F2H-4 Banshee, he led VF-11 to top honors in [[toss bombing]] during the annual fleet competition in 1956. All fourteen VF-11 pilots received the Navy's [[Battle Effectiveness Award]] for precision accuracy with this unusual and difficult technique used to deliver nuclear weapons. With this award, VF-11 became the first Atlantic fleet unit to have all of its pilots receive an \"E\" in the same exercise.<ref name=Jax_News_1956>{{cite news |title='Red Rippers' Establish Aerial Bombing Mark |author= |url=http://ufdc.ufl.edu/UF00028307/00566 |newspaper=Jax Air News |date=June 14, 1956 |location=Jacksonville, Florida |publisher=United States Navy |accessdate=October 30, 2011}}</ref><ref name=NAN_Aug_56>{{cite journal |last= |first=|date=August 1956 |title=Red Rippers Fighting 11 Top Bombers |journal=Naval Aviation News |volume= |issue= |page=14 |publisher=United States Navy |location=Washington, D.C. |doi= |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/nan/backissues/1950s/1956/aug56.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060419100420/http://www.history.navy.mil/nan/backissues/1950s/1956/aug56.pdf |archivedate=April 19, 2006 |accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1956, VF-11 embarked as part of Carrier Air Group Ten on the {{USS|Coral Sea|CV-43}} and deployed to the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]]. Just two months into the cruise, the [[Suez Crisis]] provided tense moments for all personnel as the carrier prepared for battle and to evacuate American citizens that might be caught in the conflict.<ref name=DAFS_43>{{cite web |title = USS Coral Sea |url = http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/c13/coral_sea.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013201824/http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/c13/coral_sea.htm |archivedate=October 13, 2013 |accessdate = August 18, 2015 |publisher=Naval Historical Center |location = Washington, D.C.}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1957, Feightner was assigned as officer in charge of the Jet Transitional Training Unit (JTTU) at [[Naval Air Station Olathe]] in [[Gardner, Kansas]].{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|p=108}} Established on April 4, 1955, the mission of the JTTU was to train pilots of propeller-driven aircraft to operate jets and to provide refresher training for aviators transferring from shore to sea duty.{{sfnp|Grossnick|1997|p=206}}\n\n===Carrier Air Group Ten===\nFeightner received orders in February 1959 to relieve the air wing commander of Carrier Air Group Ten (CVG-10) on the {{USS|Forrestal|CV-59}} that was deployed in the Mediterranean.{{sfnp|Tegler|2006|p=60}} He continued to serve as CAG-10 when the air wing embarked on the {{USS|Essex|CV-9}} the following month and returned to the \"Med\" for another tour.{{sfnp|Grossnick|1995|p=525}} From February to July 1960, Feightner served on the staff of Carrier Air Group Four (CVG-4) where he helped write some of the first Naval Air Training and Operating Procedures Standardization ([[NATOPS]]) manuals with the goal of reducing the Navy's aircraft accident rate.{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|pp=124\u20135}} In July 1960, he reported to the [[Naval War College]] in [[Newport, Rhode Island]] to study areas such as  [[military tactics]] and [[wargaming]]. Feightner graduated in 1961.{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|p=126}}\n\n===Fighter Design===\nIn July 1961, Feightner was assigned as the project officer for the [[McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II|F4H-1 Phantom II]] and later the Tactical Fighter Experimental (TFX) that evolved into the [[General Dynamics F-111 Aardvark|F-111 Aardvark]] at the [[Bureau of Naval Weapons]] in Washington, D.C. A year later, he was selected as the head of Navy Fighter Design where he participated in the development of the [[Vought F-8 Crusader|F-8 Crusader]], [[North American FJ-4 Fury|FJ-4 Fury]], and the [[Northrop Grumman E-2 Hawkeye|E-2 Hawkeye]]. The Hawkeye, {{Asof|2015|lc=yes}}, remains in active service with the U.S. Navy.{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|p=130}} From August 1963 to November 1964, Feightner served as [[operations officer]] to the Commander of Carrier Division Two aboard the USS ''Enterprise''.{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|p=134}}\n\n==Senior leader==\n[[File:USS Chikaskia Change of Command 1964.jpg|right|thumb|USS ''Chikaskia'' change of command in 1964]]\nFrom 1964 to 1967, Feightner served as captain of two U.S. Navy ships&mdash;the [[Replenishment oiler|fleet oiler]] {{USS|Chikaskia|AO-54}} and the [[amphibious assault ship]] {{USS|Okinawa|LPH-3}}. ''Chikaskia'' deployed to the Mediterranean to provide [[underway replenishment]] to the fleet and in the process set a refueling record for the shortest time to begin pumping fuel\u201474 seconds.{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|p=145}} After learning the techniques of amphibious operations at the [[Naval Amphibious Base Little Creek|Naval Amphibious Warfare School]] at [[Little Creek, Virginia]], Feightner commanded ''Okinawa'' during a tour of the Caribbean in 1966.{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|p=147}}  During Feightner's tour as captain, ''Okinawa'' received the Flatley Award for Aviation Safety.{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|p=148}} At the conclusion of this deployment in 1967, he brought ''Okinawa'' to [[Naval Base San Diego]], where she became part of the U.S. Pacific Fleet.<ref name=DANFS_Okinawa>{{cite web | title = Okinawa |url = http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/o2/okinawa.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130303025306/http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/o2/okinawa.htm |archivedate=March 3, 2013 |publisher=United States Navy |work=Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships |location=Washington, D.C. |accessdate=August 20, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nin 1967, Feightner was assigned to the office of the Deputy Chief of Naval Operations (CNO) for Air in [[the Pentagon]] under [[Noel Gayler]].{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|p=150}}  In this role, Feightner was responsible for supervising and coordinating the efforts of CNO air warfare program officers. Between 1969 and 1970, he also served as the director of Naval Aviation Weapons Systems Analysis Group.<ref name=USN_Oral_History_Summary/> In June 1970, Feightner was promoted from captain to the two-star rank of [[Rear admiral (United States)|rear admiral]].<ref name=Jax_News_1970>{{cite news |title=Thirty Captains Selected for Two-Star Promotions |author= |url=http://ufdc.ufl.edu/UF00028307/01042/11j |newspaper=Jax Air News |date=June 4, 1970 |location=Jacksonville, Florida |publisher=Holt Publishing Company |accessdate=November 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1970, Feightner served his final tour with the [[Naval Air Systems Command]] (NAVAIR) where he participated in several fighter studies that resulted in the development of the [[Grumman F-14 Tomcat]] and [[McDonnell Douglas F/A-18 Hornet]].{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|pp=152\u20133}} He also served as assistant commander for Logistics/Fleet Support responsible for incorporating test program modifications into production aircraft, ensuring the fleet obtained maximum effectiveness of air assets, and supporting the aircraft throughout their operational life.<ref name=NAN_July_71>{{cite journal |last=Benjamin |first=Dick  |date=July 1971 |title=The Hardware Store |journal=Naval Aviation News |volume= |issue= |pages=16&ndash;17 |publisher=United States Navy |location=Washington, D.C. |doi= |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/nan/backissues/1970s/1971/jul71.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120131085643/http://www.history.navy.mil/nan/backissues/1970s/1971/jul71.pdf |archivedate=January 31, 2012 |accessdate=August 21, 2015}}</ref> On May 20, 1972, former VF-11 skipper Feightner delivered introductory remarks at the Red Rippers change of command ceremony commemorating 45 years as the Navy's oldest continuous fighter squadron.<ref name=VF11_Hist_72>{{cite web |last=Taylor |first=J.E.| title = VF-11 Command History Report | url = http://www.history.navy.mil/content/dam/nhhc/research/archives/command-operation-reports/aviation-squadron-command-operation-reports/vfa/vfa-11/pdf/1972.pdf |date = December 17, 1973 | accessdate = August 18, 2015 |publisher=United States Navy |location = Washington, D. C.}}</ref> After 33 years of service, Feightner retired from active duty on June 30, 1974.{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|p=166}}\n\n==Later years==\nFeightner remained active in aviation after his retirement from the Navy. He shared his flight experiences at many events including:\n* ''A Conversation with Whitey Feightner''&mdash;A speech at the [[National Air and Space Museum]] where Feightner shared the experiences of his Navy career. The event was held on November 16, 2007 and was one of the [[Donald D. Engen]] Lecture and Flight Jacket Night lectures held that year at the museum.<ref name=NASM_Conversation>{{cite web | title = A Conversation with Whitey Feightner |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080304085929/http://www.nasm.si.edu/events/eventDetail.cfm?eventID=678 |archive-date = March 4, 2008 |url = http://www.nasm.si.edu/events/eventDetail.cfm?eventID=678 |access-date = May 26, 2019 |publisher=National Air and Space Museum |location = Washington, D.C.}}</ref>\n* ''Memoirs from an Aviator's Logbook''&mdash;A speech at the National Air and Space Museum where Feightner recounted his experiences as a fighter pilot, an early Blue Angel, and a Navy test pilot. The event was held on May 24, 2011 and was the Charles A. Lindbergh Memorial lecture held that year at the museum.<ref name=NASM_Memoirs>{{cite web | title = Memoirs from an Aviator's Logbook | url =  https://airandspace.si.edu/events/memoirs-aviator's-logbook| access-date = May 26, 2019 |publisher=National Air and Space Museum |location = Washington, D.C.}}</ref>\n* ''100 years of U.S. Naval Aviation''&mdash;A discussion where Feightner and fellow panelists RADM George M. \"Skip\" Furlong, Jr., Mr. Hill Goodspeed, Capt. [[Robert L. Gibson|Robert \"Hoot' Gibson]], Capt. Kenneth Wallace, and RADM Patrick McGrath discussed the past, present, and future of naval aviation. The panel was part of the [[National Aviation Hall of Fame]]'s presentation of the 2011 [[Milton Caniff]] \"Spirit of Flight\" Award to the Blue Angels on July 15, 2011. The Milton Caniff \"Spirit of Flight\" award recognizes exceptional contributions to the advancement of flight.<ref name=NAHF>{{cite web | title = National Aviation Hall of Fame Prepares to Fete Blue Angels and 100th Anniversary of Naval Aviation |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425232601/http://www.tailhook.org/PDF/Press%20Release-22%20JUN%202011.pdf |archivedate=April 25, 2012| url = http://www.tailhook.org/PDF/Press%20Release-22%20JUN%202011.pdf |date = June 22, 2011 | accessdate = August 22, 2015 |publisher=National Aviation Hall of Fame |location = Dayton, Ohio}}</ref>\n*''70th anniversary of Victory in Europe (V-E) Day''\u2014Feightner participated in the [[United States Capitol]] flyover on May 8, 2015 celebrating the 70th anniversary of the [[Allies of World War II]] [[Victory in Europe Day]] flying as a passenger in one of the vintage aircraft.<ref name=NASM_Mersky_Interview>{{cite web |last=Tedeschi |first=Diane | title = The Tale of Whitey Feightner |url = http://www.airspacemag.com/as-interview/tale-whitey-feightner-180955989/ | accessdate = August 27, 2015 |publisher=National Air and Space Museum |location = Washington, D.C.}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to attending seminars, Feightner helped lead groups including the American Fighter Aces Association and the Golden Eagles.{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|p=161}} The Golden Eagles are also known as the Early and Pioneer Naval Aviators Association\u2014a group founded in 1956 to provide a living memorial to early naval aviators.<ref name=EPNAA_USN>{{cite web |last= |first=| title = Golden Eagles Chronolog |url = http://www.history.navy.mil/research/archives/research-guides-and-finding-aids/early-and-pioneer-naval-aviators-association-golden-eagles-chronolog.html |date = September 6, 2002  |accessdate=August 22, 2015 |publisher=Naval History and Heritage Command, Archives Branch |location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref>\n\nin 2017, Feightner was one of five veterans presented with a handmade quilt created by volunteers of the North Idaho chapter of the Quilts of Valor organization. The quilts were presented in honor of each veteran's service to their country.<ref name=Heilman>{{cite web |last=Heilman |first=Devin | title = Quilts for the Courageous |url = http://www.cdapress.com/article/20170218/ARTICLE/170219725 |date = February 18, 2017  |accessdate=February 19, 2017 |publisher= Coeur d'Alene Press |location=Coeur d'Alene, Idaho}}</ref>\n\nFeightner died on April 1, 2020 in [[Coeur d'Alene, Idaho]], where he had lived since 2016 with his nephew and family at age 100. He will be buried in [[Arlington National Cemetery]].<ref name=\"Yates 2020\">{{cite web |last= |first= | title = Edward Lewis Feightner Obituary | url = https://www.yatesfuneralhomes.com/obituaries/Edward-Lewis-Feightner?obId=12593486 |date =  |access-date = April 3, 2020 |website=Yates Funeral Home |location = Hayden Lake, Idaho}}</ref><ref name=\"Goldstein 2020\">{{cite news |last=Goldstein |first=Richard | title = Edward Feightner, Test Pilot and World War II Ace, Dies at 100| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/04/us/edward-feightner-dead.html |newspaper=New York Times |date = April 4, 2020 |access-date = April 4, 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"Krumel 2020\">{{cite news |last=Krumel |first=Jim | title = WWII ace Feightner dies |url = https://www.limaohio.com/news/405367/wwii-ace-feightner-dies |newspaper=The Lima News |date = April 4, 2020 |access-date = April 4, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Awards and Decorations==\nFeightner was awarded the following decorations for his military service.{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|p=161}}{{sfnp|Wooldridge|1993|p=79}}\n<center>\n{|\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[File:Naval Aviator Badge.jpg|250px]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"|{{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=award-star|ribbon=Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|width=106}} {{Ribbon devices|number=3|type=award-star|ribbon=Distinguished Flying Cross ribbon.svg |width=106}}\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=11|type=award-star|ribbon=Air Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Navy and Marine Corps Commendation ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Combat Action Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=3|type=service-star|ribbon=United States Navy Presidential Unit Citation ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=China Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=American Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=American Campaign Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=11|type=service-star|other_device=|ribbon=Asiatic-Pacific Campaign ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=World War II Victory Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Army of Occupation ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=Phliber rib.png|width=106}}\n|-\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n!Badge\n|colspan=\"12\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[United States Naval Aviator]]\n|-\n!1st Row\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"|[[Legion of Merit]] with one gold [[award star]]\n|colspan=\"5\" align=\"center\"|[[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] <br/> with three gold stars\n|-\n!2nd Row\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|[[Air Medal]] with two silver and one gold star\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|[[Commendation Medal|Navy and Marine Corps Commendation Medal]]\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|[[Combat Action Ribbon]]\n|-\n!3rd Row\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|[[Presidential Unit Citation (US)|Navy Presidential Unit Citation]] with three [[service star]]s\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|[[China Service Medal]]\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|[[American Defense Service Medal]]\n|-\n!4th Row\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|[[American Campaign Medal]]\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|[[Asiatic-Pacific Campaign Medal]] with eleven [[Service star|campaign stars]] \n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|[[World War II Victory Medal (United States)|World War II Victory Medal]]\n|-\n!5th Row\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|[[Navy Occupation Service Medal]]\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|[[National Defense Service Medal]] with one bronze star\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|[[Philippine Liberation Medal]] with one bronze star\n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n===Distinguished Flying Cross (first of four)===\n<blockquote>While in a combat patrol over the USS ''Chicago'' 30 January 1943 east of Rennell Island they intercepted a force of twelve Japanese torpedo bombers which were preparing to raid the cruiser. In the ensuing engagement ... Lieutenant (jg) Feightner downed three.<ref>{{cite journal |last= |first= |date=November 1943 |title=Distinguished Flying Cross |url=http://www.navy.mil/ah_online/archpdf/ah194311.pdf |journal=Bureau of Naval Personnel Information Bulletin |number=320 |page=65 |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=United States Navy |access-date=August 27, 2015|ref=harv}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Other honors===\nOn October 7, 1998, Feightner was inducted into the Carrier Aviation Test Pilot Hall of Fame.{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|p=161}} He is also an Honorary Fellow of the [[Society of Experimental Test Pilots]].<ref name=SETP>{{cite web |title = SETP Honorary Fellows |url = http://www.setp.org/setp-personnel/honorary-fellows.html |publisher = Society of Experimental Test Pilots |location = Lancaster, California |accessdate = October 8, 2011}}</ref> For his work on the International Midway Memorial Foundation, Feightner was made an honorary member of the [[United States Naval Academy]] (USNA) class of 1942.{{sfnp|Mersky|2014|p=157}} The class of '42 had approximately 75 members at the Battle of Midway and remains involved in commemorating the action.<ref>{{cite news |last= Raun |first=Vicki |date=September 2, 2005 |title=USNA Class Of '42 Remembers The Battle Of Midway |url=http://www.coronadonewsca.com/news/usna-class-of-remembers-the-battle-of-midway/article_350bebd5-49ac-5562-87dd-334d4fedd578.html |newspaper=Coronado Eagle and Journal |location=Coronado, California |access-date=August 27, 2015 }}</ref> In 2013, Feightner was honored as a distinguished [[alumnus]] of the University of Findlay. <ref name=Hankinson>{{cite web |last=Hankinson |first=Charlene |title = World War II Flying Ace Rear Admiral Edward L. Feightner ('41) Honored  |url = http://newsroom.findlay.edu/world-war-ii-flying-ace-rear-admiral-edward-l-feightner-41-honored/ |publisher = The University of Findlay |location = Findlay, Ohio |date=June 1, 2013 |accessdate = December 25, 2014}}</ref><ref name=Findlay_2013>{{cite web |last=Patterson |first=Brianna |title = The University of Findlay Honors Alumni During Homecoming  |url = https://newsroom.findlay.edu/the-university-of-findlay-honors-alumni-during-homecoming-2/ |date=September 13, 2013 |publisher = The University of Findlay |location = Findlay, Ohio |access-date = May 26, 2019}}</ref> On May 20, 2015, [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives]] [[John Boehner]] presented the [[Congressional Gold Medal]] to Feightner and 37 other fighter aces.<ref name=Reed>{{cite news |last=Reed |first=Alan |date=June 4, 2015 |title=Feightner, original Blue Angel, honored |url=http://mountvernonnews.com/story/2015/06/04/feightner-original-blue-angel-honored/ |newspaper=Mount Vernon News |location=Mount Vernon, Ohio |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150604220451/http://mountvernonnews.com/story/2015/06/04/feightner-original-blue-angel-honored/ |archive-date=June 4, 2015 |access-date=July 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|World War II}}\n* [[Awards and decorations of the United States military]]\n* [[List of inactive United States Navy aircraft squadrons]]\n* [[List of United States Navy aircraft squadrons]]\n* [[List of United States Navy aircraft wings]]\n* [[List of World War II aces from the United States]]\n* [[World War II Allied names for Japanese aircraft]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book |last=Astor |first=Gerald |title=Wings of Gold: The U.S. Naval Air Campaign in World War II |authorlink= |year=2005 |edition=Kindle |publisher=Presidio Press |location=New York, New York |isbn=0-345-47252-7 |url=https://archive.org/details/wingsofgoldusnav00gera |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite web|title=Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships |url=https://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs.html/ |accessdate=January 5, 2017 |publisher=Navy Department, Naval History & Heritage Command |location=Washington, D.C. }}\n*{{cite web\n |first       = J. D.\n |last        = Eanett\n |title       = Interview with Admiral Edward Feightner (Summary)\n |url         = http://www.vmi.edu/archives.aspx?id=9617\n |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120404023756/http://www.vmi.edu/archives.aspx?id=9617\n |archivedate = April 4, 2012\n |work        = Cold War Oral History Project\n |date      = October 17, 2005\n |publisher   = Virginia Military Institute\n |location    = Lexington, Virginia\n |accessdate  = August 28, 2015\n}}\n*{{cite web\n |first       = J. D.\n |last        = Eanett\n |title       = Interview with Admiral Edward Feightner (Transcript)\n |url         = http://www.vmi.edu/uploadedFiles/Archives/Adams_Center/FeightnerEL/FeightnerEL_interview.pdf\n |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120404023821/http://www.vmi.edu/uploadedFiles/Archives/Adams_Center/FeightnerEL/FeightnerEL_interview.pdf\n |archivedate = April 4, 2012\n |work        = Cold War Oral History Project\n |date      = October 17, 2005\n |publisher   = Virginia Military Institute\n |location    = Lexington, Virginia\n |accessdate  = August 28, 2015\n}}\n*{{cite book |last = Ewing |first=Steve |title=Reaper Leader: The Life of Jimmy Flatley |year = 2002 |authorlink= |publisher=Naval Institute Press |location=Annapolis, Maryland |url= |isbn= 1-55750-205-6}}\n*{{cite book |last = Francillon |first=Ren\u00e9 J. |title=McDonnell Douglas Aircraft Since 1920 |year = 1990 |authorlink= |publisher=Naval Institute Press |location=Annapolis, Maryland |url= |isbn= 1-55750-550-0}}\n*{{cite book |last=Gardner |first=Tom |title=Vought F7U Cutlass: A Developmental History |authorlink= |year=2010 |edition=Illustrated |publisher= Schiffer Publishing Limited |location=Atglen, Pennsylvania |isbn=978-0-7643-3232-6 |url=}}\n*{{cite book |last=Ginter |first= Steve |title=Chance Vought F7U Cutlass |authorlink= |year=1982 |edition=Illustrated |series=Naval Fighters Number Six |publisher= Steve Ginter |location=Simi Valley, California |isbn=0-942612-06-X |url=}}\n*{{cite book |last=Grossnick |first=Roy A. |title=Dictionary of American Naval Aviation Squadrons |volume=I |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/branches/dictvol1.htm |publisher=United States Navy |location=Washington, D.C. |isbn=0-945274-29-7 |year=1995 |accessdate=October 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915085909/http://www.history.navy.mil/branches/dictvol1.htm |archivedate=September 15, 2008 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Grossnick |first=Roy A. |title=Part 8, The New Navy, 1954&ndash;1959 |work=United States Naval Aviation 1910-1995 |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/avh-1910/PART08.PDF |year=1997 |accessdate=November 6, 2011 |publisher=Naval Historical Center |location=Washington, D. C. |isbn=0-945274-34-3 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110507140407/http://www.history.navy.mil/avh-1910/PART08.PDF |archivedate=May 7, 2011 }}\n*{{cite book |last = Hammel |first=Eric |title=Air War Pacific: Chronology |year = 1998 |authorlink=Eric M. Hammel |publisher=Pacifica Military History |location=Pacifica, California |url= |isbn=1-890988-10-3}}\n*{{cite book |last = Linder |first = Bruce |title=Tidewater's Navy: An Illustrated History |year = 2005 |authorlink= |publisher=Naval Institute Press |location=Annapolis, Maryland |isbn=1-59114-465-5}}\n*{{cite book |last = Lundstrom |first=John B. |title=First Team And the Guadalcanal Campaign: Naval Fighter Combat from August to November 1942 |year = 2005 |authorlink= |publisher=Naval Institute Press |location=Annapolis, Maryland |isbn= 1-59114-472-8}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Lurie |editor1-first=Maxine N. |editor2-last= Mappen |editor2-first= Marc |title=Encyclopedia of New Jersey |authorlink= |year=2004 |publisher= Rutgers University Press |location=Piscataway, New Jersey |isbn= 0-8135-3325-2 |page=48 |url=}}\n*{{cite book |last = Mersky |first=Peter B. |title=Whitey: The Story of Rear Admiral E. L. Feightner |year = 2014 |authorlink= |publisher=Naval Institute Press |location=Annapolis, Maryland |url= |isbn=978-1-61251-791-9}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Powell |first=R. R. \"Boom\" |authorlink= |date=August 2008 |volume=13 |issue=4 |title=Cutlass Tales: Quirks of the Ensign Eater |journal=Flight Journal |publisher=Air Age Media |location=Wilton, Connecticut |url= |accessdate=}}\n*{{cite book |last = Stanaway |first= John |title=Nakajima Ki.43 \"Hayabusa\": Allied Code Name \"Oscar\" |year = 2006 |authorlink= |publisher=Merriam Press |location=Bennington, Vermont |edition=2nd |url= |isbn= 1-57638-141-2}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Tegler |first=Jan |authorlink= |date=April 2006 |title=34 Hours With Old Shakey |journal=Flight Journal |volume= |issue= |publisher=Air Age Media |location=Wilton, Connecticut |format= }}\n*{{cite book |last=Tillman |first= Barrett |title=Wildcat: The F4F in World War II  |authorlink=Barrett Tillman |year=1983 |edition=2nd |publisher= Naval Institute Press |location=Annapolis, Maryland |isbn=0-87021-789-5 |url=}}\n*{{cite book |last=Tillman |first= Barrett |title=Wildcat Aces of World War 2 (Aircraft of the Aces) |authorlink=Barrett Tillman |year=1995 |publisher= Osprey Publishing |location=Oxford, England |isbn=1-85532-486-5 |url=}}\n*{{cite book |last=Tillman |first= Barrett |title=Hellcat Aces of World War 2 |authorlink=Barrett Tillman |year=1996 |publisher= Osprey Publishing |location=Oxford, England |isbn=1-85532-596-9 |url=}}\n*{{cite book |last=Tillman |first= Barrett |title=Hellcat: The F6F in World War II |authorlink=Barrett Tillman |year=2000 |edition=2nd |publisher= Naval Institute Press |location=Annapolis, Maryland |isbn= 1-55750-991-3 |url=}}\n*{{cite book |last=Tillman |first= Barrett |title=Clash of The Carriers: The True Story of the Marianas Turkey Shoot of World War II |authorlink=Barrett Tillman |year=2005 |edition=Google eBook |publisher= NAL Caliber (Penguin Books) |location=New York City, New York |isbn=978-0-451-21956-5 |url=}}\n*{{cite web\n |first       =\n |last        =\n |title       = U.S. Navy and Marine Corps Aces\n |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131229123921/http://www.history.navy.mil/branches/aces.html\n |archive-date = December 29, 2013\n |url         = http://www.history.navy.mil/branches/aces.html\n |work        =\n |date      = March 31, 1997\n |publisher   = Naval Historical Center\n |location    = Washington, D.C.\n |access-date  = May 27, 2019\n}}\n*{{cite book |last=Veronico |first= Nicholas A. |title=The Blue Angels: A Fly-By History: Sixty Years of Aerial Excellence |authorlink= |year=2005 |edition=Illustrated |publisher= Zenith Imprint |location=Minneapolis, Minnesota |isbn= 0-7603-2216-3  |url=}}\n*{{cite book |last= Wilcox |first= Robert K. |authorlink=  |author2=Lovell, James A. |title=First Blue: The Story of World War II Ace Butch Voris and the Creation of the Blue Angels |year=2006 |ed= |publisher= Macmillan |location=New York, New York |isbn= 0-312-32250-X  |url=}}\n*{{cite book |last=Wooldridge |first=E. T. |authorlink= |title=Carrier Warfare in the Pacific: An Oral History Collection |year=1993 |edition=Illustrated |publisher=Smithsonian Institution Press |location=Washington, D. C. |isbn=1-560-98264-0 |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781560982647 |ref=harv }}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscatinline}}\n*{{cite journal |last= |first= |authorlink= |date=June 17, 1944 |title=Air Group Officers Receive Awards |journal=The USS Bunker Hill Monument |volume=2 |issue=21 |page=1 |publisher=U.S. Navy/Bluejacket |location=Cantonment, Florida |url=http://bluejacket.com/usn/pdf/cv17_v2n21_440617.pdf |format= [[PDF]] |accessdate=August 22, 2015}}\n*{{cite web |last=Anft |first=Torsten |title=VF-11 Photo from 1956 |url=http://www.anft.net/vf-11/photos-1956-01.html |work=Red Rippers Unofficial Homepage |publisher=anft.com |location=Aachen, Germany |accessdate= October 30, 2011}}\n*{{cite web |last=Anft |first=Torsten |title=VF-11 Squadron |url=http://www.anft.net/vf-11/history.html#hist03 |work=Red Rippers Unofficial Homepage |publisher=anft.com |location=Aachen, Germany |accessdate= November 5, 2011}}\n*{{cite 