ry |year = 2005 |authorlink= |publisher=Naval Institute Press |location=Annapolis, Maryland |isbn=1-59114-465-5}}\n*{{cite book |last = Lundstrom |first=John B. |title=First Team And the Guadalcanal Campaign: Naval Fighter Combat from August to November 1942 |year = 2005 |authorlink= |publisher=Naval Institute Press |location=Annapolis, Maryland |isbn= 1-59114-472-8}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Lurie |editor1-first=Maxine N. |editor2-last= Mappen |editor2-first= Marc |title=Encyclopedia of New Jersey |authorlink= |year=2004 |publisher= Rutgers University Press |location=Piscataway, New Jersey |isbn= 0-8135-3325-2 |page=48 |url=}}\n*{{cite book |last = Mersky |first=Peter B. |title=Whitey: The Story of Rear Admiral E. L. Feightner |year = 2014 |authorlink= |publisher=Naval Institute Press |location=Annapolis, Maryland |url= |isbn=978-1-61251-791-9}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Powell |first=R. R. \"Boom\" |authorlink= |date=August 2008 |volume=13 |issue=4 |title=Cutlass Tales: Quirks of the Ensign Eater |journal=Flight Journal |publisher=Air Age Media |location=Wilton, Connecticut |url= |accessdate=}}\n*{{cite book |last = Stanaway |first= John |title=Nakajima Ki.43 \"Hayabusa\": Allied Code Name \"Oscar\" |year = 2006 |authorlink= |publisher=Merriam Press |location=Bennington, Vermont |edition=2nd |url= |isbn= 1-57638-141-2}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Tegler |first=Jan |authorlink= |date=April 2006 |title=34 Hours With Old Shakey |journal=Flight Journal |volume= |issue= |publisher=Air Age Media |location=Wilton, Connecticut |format= }}\n*{{cite book |last=Tillman |first= Barrett |title=Wildcat: The F4F in World War II  |authorlink=Barrett Tillman |year=1983 |edition=2nd |publisher= Naval Institute Press |location=Annapolis, Maryland |isbn=0-87021-789-5 |url=}}\n*{{cite book |last=Tillman |first= Barrett |title=Wildcat Aces of World War 2 (Aircraft of the Aces) |authorlink=Barrett Tillman |year=1995 |publisher= Osprey Publishing |location=Oxford, England |isbn=1-85532-486-5 |url=}}\n*{{cite book |last=Tillman |first= Barrett |title=Hellcat Aces of World War 2 |authorlink=Barrett Tillman |year=1996 |publisher= Osprey Publishing |location=Oxford, England |isbn=1-85532-596-9 |url=}}\n*{{cite book |last=Tillman |first= Barrett |title=Hellcat: The F6F in World War II |authorlink=Barrett Tillman |year=2000 |edition=2nd |publisher= Naval Institute Press |location=Annapolis, Maryland |isbn= 1-55750-991-3 |url=}}\n*{{cite book |last=Tillman |first= Barrett |title=Clash of The Carriers: The True Story of the Marianas Turkey Shoot of World War II |authorlink=Barrett Tillman |year=2005 |edition=Google eBook |publisher= NAL Caliber (Penguin Books) |location=New York City, New York |isbn=978-0-451-21956-5 |url=}}\n*{{cite web\n |first       =\n |last        =\n |title       = U.S. Navy and Marine Corps Aces\n |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131229123921/http://www.history.navy.mil/branches/aces.html\n |archive-date = December 29, 2013\n |url         = http://www.history.navy.mil/branches/aces.html\n |work        =\n |date      = March 31, 1997\n |publisher   = Naval Historical Center\n |location    = Washington, D.C.\n |access-date  = May 27, 2019\n}}\n*{{cite book |last=Veronico |first= Nicholas A. |title=The Blue Angels: A Fly-By History: Sixty Years of Aerial Excellence |authorlink= |year=2005 |edition=Illustrated |publisher= Zenith Imprint |location=Minneapolis, Minnesota |isbn= 0-7603-2216-3  |url=}}\n*{{cite book |last= Wilcox |first= Robert K. |authorlink=  |author2=Lovell, James A. |title=First Blue: The Story of World War II Ace Butch Voris and the Creation of the Blue Angels |year=2006 |ed= |publisher= Macmillan |location=New York, New York |isbn= 0-312-32250-X  |url=}}\n*{{cite book |last=Wooldridge |first=E. T. |authorlink= |title=Carrier Warfare in the Pacific: An Oral History Collection |year=1993 |edition=Illustrated |publisher=Smithsonian Institution Press |location=Washington, D. C. |isbn=1-560-98264-0 |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781560982647 |ref=harv }}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite journal |last= |first= |authorlink= |date=June 17, 1944 |title=Air Group Officers Receive Awards |journal=The USS Bunker Hill Monument |volume=2 |issue=21 |page=1 |publisher=U.S. Navy/Bluejacket |location=Cantonment, Florida |url=http://bluejacket.com/usn/pdf/cv17_v2n21_440617.pdf |format= [[PDF]] |accessdate=August 22, 2015}}\n*{{cite web |last=Anft |first=Torsten |title=VF-11 Photo from 1956 |url=http://www.anft.net/vf-11/photos-1956-01.html |work=Red Rippers Unofficial Homepage |publisher=anft.com |location=Aachen, Germany |accessdate= October 30, 2011}}\n*{{cite web |last=Anft |first=Torsten |title=VF-11 Squadron |url=http://www.anft.net/vf-11/history.html#hist03 |work=Red Rippers Unofficial Homepage |publisher=anft.com |location=Aachen, Germany |accessdate= November 5, 2011}}\n*{{cite web |last= |first= |title = 'Dash-1' Carrier Qualifications |url = http://www.midwaysailor.com/midway1950/midway-1143b.jpg |publisher = midwaysailor.com |location= |accessdate = August 16, 2015}}\n*{{cite web |title=Edward Feightner on IMDB |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm4560167/ |work = |publisher=Internet Movie Database |location= |accessdate= October 8, 2011}}\n*{{cite web |title = Edward  L.  Feightner |publisher = Veteran Tributes |location = Gulfport, Mississippi  |accessdate = August 27, 2015|url = http://www.veterantributes.org/TributeDetail.php?recordID=732}}\n*{{cite web |title=Edward L. Feightner, RADM, USN (Ret.) |url=http://www.epnaao.com/BIOS_files/EMERITUS/Feightner-%20Edward%20L.pdf |work = Golden Eagles |publisher=Early and Pioneer Naval Aviators Association |location=Cardiff, California |accessdate= August 22, 2015}}\n*{{cite web |last=Freeman |first=Paul |title=Abandoned & Little-Known Airfields: Pungo Naval Outer Landing Field, Virginia Beach VA |url = http://www.airfields-freeman.com/VA/Airfields_VA_VirginiaBeach.htm#pungo |publisher = |location = Sterling, Virginia |date= June 6, 2010  |accessdate = October 14, 2011}}\n*{{cite web |last=Hiroe |first=Takafumi | title = CVG-10 Deployments |url = http://www.gonavy.jp/CVG-CVG10f.html |date = September 9, 2009 |accessdate = November 11, 2011 |publisher=gonavy.jp |location = Japan}}\n*{{cite web |last=Lewis |first=Henry P. |title = Continuing History 1956&ndash;2008 |url = http://www.epnaao.com/Continuing%20History%201956-2008.pdf |year = 1980 | accessdate = November 5, 2011 |publisher=Early and Pioneer Naval Aviators' Association |location =Cardiff, California}}\n*{{cite web |last=Miller |first= Jerry |title = Sea Story - Rear Admiral \"Whitey\" Feightner |url =  https://www.usna.com/tributes-and-stories---stories-1942?#Feightner |publisher = U.S. Naval Academy Alumni Association and Foundation |location=Annapolis, Maryland |access-date = May 27, 2019}}\n*{{cite web |last=Prince |first=Thomas |title = USS Midway in the 1950s |url= http://www.midwaysailor.com/midway1950/1950flightops.html |publisher=midwaysailor.com |location=Saint Louis Park, Minnesota |accessdate  = July 31, 2011}}\n*{{cite web |last= Priolo |first=Gary P. | title = USS Chikaskia Photo Archive| url = http://www.navsource.org/archives/09/19/19054.htm |date = July 22, 2011 | accessdate = November 12, 2011 |publisher=navsource.org |location = Baytown, Texas}}\n*{{cite web |last=Rose |first=Scott |title = Cutlass Gallery - Taking Off |url = http://www.warbirdsresourcegroup.org/NARG/f7ucutlass_gallery_take_off_01_0001.html |publisher = Warbirds Resource Group |location=Boston, Massachusetts |accessdate = August 16, 2015}}\n*{{cite web |last=Sherman |first=Stephen |title = Lt. Edward L. \"Whitey\" Feightner |url = http://acepilots.com/usn_feightner.html |publisher = Ace Pilots |location = Scarsdale, New York |date = July 1, 2011 |accessdate = October 8, 2011}}\n*{{cite web |last=Shettle |first=M. L |title = Naval Air Facility Thermal |url = http://www.militarymuseum.org/ThermalAAF.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130127204242/http://www.militarymuseum.org/ThermalAAF.html |archivedate=January 27, 2013 |publisher = The California State Military Museum |location=Sacramento, California |accessdate = October 23, 2011}}\n*{{cite news |last= |first= |date= |title=Valor Awards for Edward Lewis Feightner |url=http://valor.militarytimes.com/recipient.php?recipientid=309252 |newspaper=Military Times |publisher=Sightline Media Group |location=Springfield, Virginia |access-date=August 27, 2015}}\n*{{cite web |last=Wagner |first=Ray  |title=Navy Fighters F2H, F9F |url = http://www.americancombatplanes.com/navy_fighters_2.html |publisher =  AmericanCombatPlanes.com |location=La Mesa, California |accessdate = October 28, 2011}}\n*{{cite web |last=Yarnall |first=Paul R. |title=USS Midway Aircraft Carrier Photo Archive |url=http://www.navsource.org/archives/02/41.htm |publisher=navsource.org |location=Baytown, Texas |work=NavSource Naval History |accessdate=July 31, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6b6GcKE9G?url=http://www.navsource.org/archives/02/41.htm |archivedate=August 27, 2015 }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Feightner, Edward L.}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American centenarians]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:American test pilots]]\n[[Category:Aviators from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Congressional Gold Medal recipients]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Ohio]]\n[[Category:People from Lima, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Air Medal]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Test Pilot School alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Navy rear admirals (upper half)]]\n[[Category:United States Navy pilots of World War II]]\n[[Category:University of Findlay alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Lotje", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo :-)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_L._Feightner"}
{"title_page": "Twenty-second Amendment to the United States Constitution", "text_new": "[[FHA-Secure]]{{Use American English|date = April 2019}}\n{{short description|Constitutional amendment limiting U.S. presidents to 2.5 terms}}\n{{Redirect|Twenty-second Amendment}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{US Constitution article series}}\nThe '''Twenty-second Amendment''' ('''Amendment XXII''') to the [[United States Constitution]] sets a limit on the number of times an individual is eligible for election to the office of [[President of the United States]], and also sets additional eligibility conditions for presidents who succeed to the unexpired terms of their predecessors.<ref name=TermsTenure>{{cite web| last=Neale| first=Thomas H.| title=Presidential Terms and Tenure: Perspectives and Proposals for Change| date=October 19, 2009| url=http://www.whitehousetransitionproject.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/Terms-Tenure_101909-1.pdf| publisher=Congressional Research Service, The Library of Congress| location=Washington, D.C.| accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref> \n\nto the ratification of the amendment, the president had not been subject to [[term limit]]s,  [[George Washington]] had established a two-term tradition that many other presidents had followed. In the [[1940 United States presidential election|1940 presidential election]] and the [[1944 United States presidential election|1944 presidential election]], [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] became the first president to win a third term and then later a fourth term, giving rise to concerns about the potential issues involved with a president serving an unlimited number of terms. [[United States Congress|Congress]] approved the Twenty-second Amendment on March 24, 1947, afhaljhfhnd submitted it to the [[State legislature (United States)|state legislatures]] for [[Article Five of the United States Constitution#Ratification|ratification]]. That process was completed on February 27, 1951, after the amendment had been ratified by the requisite 36 of the then-48 [[U.S. state|states]] (as neither [[Alaska]] nor [[Hawaii]] had been [[Admission to the Union|admitted as states]]), and its provisions [[Coming into force|came into force]] on that date.\n\nThe amendment prohibits any individual who has been elected president twice from being elected again. Under the amendment, an individual who fills an unexpired presidential term lasting greater than two years is also prohibited from winning election as president more than once. Scholars debate whether the amendment prohibits affected individuals from succeeding to the presidency under any circumstances or whether it only applies to presidential elections.\n\n==Text==\n<!-- Do not edit the words Article or President, they are capitalized as per the citation-->\n{{quote|'''Section 1.'''  No person shall be elected to the office of the President more than twice, and no person who has held the office of President, or acted as President, for more than two years of a term to which some other person was elected President shall be elected to the office of the President more than once. But this Article shall not apply to any person holding the office of President when this Article was proposed by the Congress, and shall not prevent any person who may be holding the office of President, or acting as President, during the term within which this Article becomes operative from holding the office of President or acting as President during the remainder of such term.}}\n\n{{quote|'''Section 2.''' This Article shall be inoperative unless it shall have been ratified as an amendment to the Constitution by the legislatures of three-fourths of the several states within seven years from the date of its submission to the states by the Congress.<ref name=CUSA:AA>{{cite web| title=Constitution of the United States of America: Analysis and Interpretation| url=https://www.congress.gov/content/conan/pdf/GPO-CONAN-2017.pdf| date=August 26, 2017| publisher=Library of Congress| location=Washington, D.C.| pages=39\u201340| accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref>}}\n\n==Background==\nNotwithstanding that the Twenty-second Amendment was clearly a reaction to [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]'s election to an unprecedented four terms as president, the notion of presidential [[term limit]]s has long been debated in American politics. Delegates to the [[Constitutional Convention (United States)|Constitutional Convention of 1787]] considered the issue extensively (alongside broader questions, such as who would elect the president, and the president's role). Many\u2014including [[Alexander Hamilton]] and [[James Madison]]\u2014supported a lifetime appointment for presidents, while others favored fixed terms appointments. Virginia's [[George Mason]] denounced the life-tenure proposal as tantamount to establishment of an [[elective monarchy]].<ref name=BuckleyMetzger>{{cite web| title=Twenty-second Amendment| last1=Buckley| first1=F. H.| last2=Metzger| first2=Gillian| url=https://constitutioncenter.org/interactive-constitution/amendments/amendment-xxii| work=The Interactive Constitution| publisher=The National Constitution Center| location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania| accessdate=March 19, 2018}}</ref>  An early draft of the United States Constitution provided that the President was restricted to a single seven-year term.<ref>First draft U.S.CONST., art. X, section 1.</ref>  Ultimately, the Framers approved four-year terms with no restriction on the amount of time a person could serve as president.\n\nThough dismissed by the Constitutional Convention, the concept of term limits for U.S. presidents took hold during the presidencies of [[George Washington]] and [[Thomas Jefferson]]. As his second term entered its final year in 1796, George Washington was exhausted from years of public service, and his health had begun to decline. He was also bothered by the unrelenting attacks from his political opponents, which had escalated after the signing of the [[Jay Treaty]], and believed that he had accomplished his major goals as president. For these reasons, he decided not to stand for reelection to a third term, a decision he announced to the nation through a ''[[George Washington's Farewell Address|Farewell Address]]'' in September 1796.<ref>{{cite book| last=Ferling| first=John| authorlink=John E. Ferling| title=The Ascent of George Washington: The Hidden Political Genius of an American Icon| date=2009| publisher=Bloomsbury Press| location=New York| pages=[https://archive.org/details/ascentofgeorgewa00ferl/page/347 347\u2013348]| isbn=978-1-59691-465-0| url=https://archive.org/details/ascentofgeorgewa00ferl/page/347}}</ref> Eleven years later, as Thomas Jefferson neared the half-way point of his second term, he wrote, {{quote|If some termination to the services of the chief magistrate be not fixed by the Constitution, or supplied by practice, his office, nominally for years, will in fact, become for life; and history shows how easily that degenerates into an inheritance.<ref>{{cite web |last=Jefferson |first=Thomas |date=December 10, 1807|title=Letter to the Legislature of Vermont |url=http://teachingamericanhistory.org/library/document/letter-to-the-legislature-of-vermont/ |accessdate=March 19, 2018 |publisher=TeachingAmericanHistory.org |location=Ashland, Ohio}}</ref>}}\n\nSince Washington made his historic announcement, numerous academics and public figures have looked at his decision to retire after two terms, and have, according to [[Political science|political scientist]] Bruce Peabody, \"argued he had established a ''two-term tradition'' that served as a vital check against any one person, or the presidency as a whole, accumulating too much power\".<ref name=Peabody22A>{{cite web| last=Peabody |first=Bruce| url=http://www.heritage.org/constitution/#!/amendments/22/essays/184/presidential-term-limit|title=Presidential Term Limit| publisher=The Heritage Foundation| accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref> Numerous amendments aimed toward changing informal precedent into constitutional law were proposed in Congress during the early to mid-19th century, but none passed.<ref name=BuckleyMetzger/><ref name=PeabodyGant>{{cite journal |last1=Peabody |first1=Bruce G. |last2=Gant |first2=Scott E. |date=February 1999 |title=The Twice and Future President: Constitutional Interstices and the Twenty-Second Amendment |url=http://alpha.fdu.edu/~peabody/Twice_and_Future_President.html |journal=Minnesota Law Review |publisher=University of Minnesota Law School |location=Minneapolis |volume=83 |issue=3 |pages=565\u2013635 |access-date=June 12, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115121046/http://alpha.fdu.edu/~peabody/Twice_and_Future_President.html |archive-date=January 15, 2013}}</ref> Three of the next four presidents after Jefferson\u2014[[James Madison]], [[James Monroe]], and [[Andrew Jackson]]\u2014served two terms, and each one adhered to the two-term principle;<ref name=TermsTenure/> Martin Van Buren was the only president between Jackson and [[Abraham Lincoln]] to be nominated for a second term, although he lost the [[1840 United States presidential election|1840 election]], and so only served one term.<ref name=PeabodyGant/>  Before the Civil War the seceding States drafted the [[Constitution of the Confederate States of America]] which in most respects was similar to the United States Constitution, but one change was limiting the President to a single six-year term.\n\n[[File:The Appomattox of the third termers - unconditional surrender LCCN97515771.tif|alt=Cartoon showing Ulysses S. Grant handing a sword to James Garfield, who is holding a rolled-up paper.|thumb|left|upright=1.25|[[Ulysses S. Grant]] is shown surrendering to [[James A. Garfield]] after losing the 1880 Republican presidential nomination to him, in this [[Political satire|satirical]] ''[[Puck (magazine)|Puck]]'' cartoon.]]\n\nIn spite of the strong two-term tradition, a few presidents prior to Franklin Roosevelt did attempt to secure a third term. Following [[Ulysses S. Grant]]'s reelection victory in [[1872 United States presidential election|1872]], there were serious discussions within Republican political circles about the possibility of his running again in 1876. Interest in a third term for Grant evaporated however, in the light of negative public opinion and opposition from members of Congress, and Grant left the presidency in 1877, after two terms. Even so, as the 1880 election approached, he sought nomination for a (non-consecutive) third term at the [[1880 Republican National Convention]], but narrowly lost to [[James Garfield]], who would go on to win the [[1880 United States presidential election|1880 election]].<ref name=PeabodyGant/>\n\n[[Theodore Roosevelt]] succeeded to the presidency on September 14, 1901, following [[Assassination of William McKinley|William McKinley's assassination]] ({{age in days|Mar 4 1901|Sep 14 1901}} days into his second term), and was subsequently elected to a full term in [[1904 United States presidential election|1904]]. While he declined to seek a third (second full) term in 1908, Roosevelt did seek one four years later, in the [[1912 United States presidential election|election of 1912]], where he lost to [[Woodrow Wilson]]. Wilson himself, despite his ill health following a serious stroke, aspired to a third term. Many of Wilson's advisers tried to convince him that his health precluded another campaign, but Wilson nonetheless asked that his name be placed in nomination for the presidency at the [[1920 Democratic National Convention]].<ref>{{Cite book |title=The Year of the Six Presidents |last=Pietrusza |first=David |publisher=Carroll and Graf |location=New York |date=2007 |isbn=978-0-78671-622-7 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780786716227/page/187 187\u2013200] |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780786716227/page/187 }}</ref> Democratic Party leaders were unwilling to support Wilson, however, and the nomination eventually went to [[James M. Cox]], who lost to [[Warren G. Harding]]. Wilson again contemplated running for a (nonconsecutive) third term in 1924, devising a strategy for his comeback, but again lacked any support; he died in February of that year.<ref>{{Cite book |title=In Search of Woodrow Wilson: Beliefs and Behavior |url=https://books.google.com/?id=b2A8WtVeFc4C&pg=PA261#v=onepage&q&f=false |publisher=Greenwood Press |location=Westport, Connecticut |date=1998 |isbn= 9780313305207 |first=Robert M. |last=Saunders |pages=260\u2013262}}</ref>\n\n[[File:FDR 1944 Color Portrait.jpg|thumb|upright=.75|right|[[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], elected to four terms, was president from 1933 until his death in 1945.]]\n\nFranklin D. Roosevelt spent the months leading up to the [[1940 Democratic National Convention]] refusing to state whether he would seek a third term. His Vice President, [[John Nance Garner]], along with [[United States Postmaster General|Postmaster General]] [[James Farley]], announced their candidacies for the Democratic nomination. When the convention came, Roosevelt sent a message to the convention, saying he would run only if [[Draft (politics)|drafted]], saying delegates were free to vote for whomever they pleased. This message was interpreted to mean he was willing to be drafted, and he subsequently was renominated on the convention's first ballot.<ref name=PeabodyGant/><ref>{{cite book| last=Rosen| first=Elliot A.| editor-last=Walch| editor-first=Timothy| title=At the President's Side: The Vice Presidency in the Twentieth Century| chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PBYghyfZjOUC&pg=PA52#v=onepage&q&f=false| chapter='Not Worth a Pitcher of Warm Piss': John Nance Garner as Vice President| date=1997| publisher=University of Missouri Press| location=Columbia, Missouri| pages=[https://archive.org/details/atpresidentsside00walc/page/52 52\u201353]| isbn=0-8262-1133-X| accessdate=March 20, 2018| url=https://archive.org/details/atpresidentsside00walc/page/52}}</ref> Later, during the [[1940 United States presidential election|1940 presidential election]], Roosevelt won a decisive victory over Republican [[Wendell Willkie]], becoming the first, and to date only, president to exceed eight years in office. Roosevelt's decision to seek a third term dominated the election campaign.<ref name=\"NCC\">{{cite web| url=https://constitutioncenter.org/blog/fdrs-third-term-decision-and-the-22nd-amendment/| title=FDR's third-term decision and the 22nd amendment| work=Constitution Daily| publisher=The National Constitution Center| location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania| accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref> Willkie ran against the open-ended presidential tenure, while Democrats cited the [[World War II|war in Europe]] as a reason for breaking with precedent.<ref name=PeabodyGant/>\n\nFour years later, Roosevelt faced Republican [[Thomas E. Dewey]] in the [[1944 United States presidential election|1944 election]]. Near the end of the campaign, Thomas Dewey announced his support of a constitutional amendment that would limit future presidents to two terms. According to Dewey, \"four terms, or sixteen years (a direct reference to the president's tenure in office four years hence), is the most dangerous threat to our freedom ever proposed.\"<ref>{{cite book| title=FDR, Dewey, and the Election of 1944| last=Jordan| first=David M.| publisher=Indiana University Press| location=Bloomington, Indiana| date=2011| page=[https://archive.org/details/fdrdeweyelection0000jord/page/290 290]| isbn=978-0-253-35683-3| url=https://archive.org/details/fdrdeweyelection0000jord/page/290}}</ref> He also discreetly raised the issue of the president's age. Roosevelt, however, was able to exude enough energy and charisma to retain the confidence of the American public, who reelected him to a fourth term.<ref>{{cite web| last=Leuchtenburg| first=William E.| url=https://millercenter.org/president/fdroosevelt/campaigns-and-elections| title=Franklin D. Roosevelt: Campaigns and Elections| publisher=Miller Center of Public Affairs, University of Virginia| location=Charlottesville, Virginia| accessdate=March 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWhile he effectively quelled rumors of his poor health during the campaign, Roosevelt's health was in reality deteriorating. On April 12, 1945, only {{age in days|Jan 20, 1945|Apr 12, 1945}} days after his [[Fourth inauguration of Franklin D. Roosevelt|fourth inauguration]], he suffered a cerebral hemorrhage and [[List of Presidents of the United States who died in office#1945: Franklin D. Roosevelt|died]]. He was succeeded by Vice President [[Harry Truman]].<ref>{{cite web| last=Leuchtenburg| first=William E.| url=https://millercenter.org/president/fdroosevelt/death-of-the-president| title=Franklin D. Roosevelt: Death of the President| publisher=Miller Center of Public Affairs, University of Virginia| location=Charlottesville, Virginia| accessdate=March 20, 2018}}</ref> In the [[1946 United States elections|midterm elections]] {{age in months|1945|4|12|1946|11|5}} months later, Republicans took control of both the House and the Senate. As many of them had campaigned on the issue of presidential tenure, declaring their support for a constitutional amendment that would limit how long a person could serve as president, the issue was given top priority in the [[80th Congress]] when it convened in January 1947.<ref name=Peabody22A/>\n\n==Proposal and ratification==\n===Proposal in Congress===\n{{see also|Presidency of Harry S. Truman}}\n\nThe [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] took quick action, approving a proposed constitutional amendment (House [[Joint Resolution]]&nbsp;27) setting a limit of two four-year terms for future presidents. Introduced by [[Earl C. Michener]], the measure passed 285\u2013121, with support from 47 Democrats, on February 6, 1947. Meanwhile, the Senate developed its own proposed amendment, which initially differed from the House proposal by requiring that the amendment be submitted to [[state ratifying conventions]] for ratification, rather than to the state legislatures, and by prohibiting any person who had served more than 365 days in each of two terms from further presidential service. Both these provisions were removed when the full Senate took up the bill, but a new provision was, however, added. Put forward by [[Robert A. Taft]], it clarified procedures governing the number of times a vice president who succeeded to the presidency might be elected to office. The amended proposal was passed 59\u201323, with 16 Democrats in favor, on March 12.<ref name=TermsTenure/><ref name=tahlequahdailypress>{{Cite news| title=Presidential terms limited by 22nd Amendment| last=Rowley| first=Sean| date=July 26, 2014| url=http://www.tahlequahdailypress.com/news/features/presidential-terms-limited-by-nd-amendment/article_abfac7ef-c505-55f2-b171-08bc83b6914d.html| work=Tahlequah Daily Press| accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeveral days later, the House agreed to the Senate's revisions, and on March 24, 1947, the constitutional amendment imposing term limitations on future Presidents was submitted to the states for ratification.<ref name=CUSA:AA/> The ratification process for the 22nd Amendment was completed on February 27, 1951, {{age in years and days|1947|3|21|1951|2|27}} after it was sent to the states.<ref name=\"NCC\"/><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.usconstitution.net/constamrat.html| title=Ratification of Constitutional Amendments| accessdate=May 9, 2012| last=Mount| first=Steve| date=January 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Ratification by the states===\n[[File:The Ratification of the Twenty-Second Amendment.png|thumb|A map of how the states voted on the Twenty-second Amendment]]\n[[Image:22nd Amendment Pg1of1 AC.jpg|thumb|The Twenty-Second Amendment in the [[National Archives and Records Administration|National Archives]]]]\nOnce submitted to the states, the 22nd Amendment was ratified by:<ref name=CUSA:AA/>\n# [[Maine]] (March 31, 1947)\n# [[Michigan]] (March 31, 1947)\n# [[Iowa]] (April 1, 1947)\n# [[Kansas]] (April 1, 1947)\n# [[New Hampshire]] (April 1, 1947)\n# [[Delaware]] (April 2, 1947)\n# [[Illinois]] (April 3, 1947)\n# [[Oregon]] (April 3, 1947)\n# [[Colorado]] (April 12, 1947)\n# [[California]] (April 15, 1947)\n# [[New Jersey]] (April 15, 1947)\n# [[Vermont]] (April 15, 1947)\n# [[Ohio]] (April 16, 1947)\n# [[Wisconsin]] (April 16, 1947)\n# [[Pennsylvania]] (April 29, 1947)\n# [[Connecticut]] (May 21, 1947)\n# [[Missouri]] (May 22, 1947)\n# [[Nebraska]] (May 23, 1947)\n# [[Virginia]] (January 28, 1948)\n# [[Mississippi]] (February 12, 1948)\n# [[New York (state)|New York]] (March 9, 1948)\n# [[South Dakota]] (January 21, 1949)\n# [[North Dakota]] (February 25, 1949)\n# [[Louisiana]] (May 17, 1950)\n# [[Montana]] (January 25, 1951)\n# [[Indiana]] (January 29, 1951)\n# [[Idaho]] (January 30, 1951)\n# [[New Mexico]] (February 12, 1951)\n# [[Wyoming]] (February 12, 1951)\n# [[Arkansas]] (February 15, 1951)\n# [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] (February 17, 1951)\n# [[Tennessee]] (February 20, 1951)\n# [[Texas]] (February 22, 1951)\n# [[Utah]] (February 26, 1951)\n# [[Nevada]] (February 26, 1951)\n# [[Minnesota]] (February 27, 1951)<br>Ratification was completed when the [[Minnesota Legislature]] ratified the amendment. On March 1, 1951, the Administrator of [[General Services Administration|General Services]], [[Jess Larson]], issued a certificate [[Promulgation|proclaiming]] the 22nd Amendment duly ratified and part of the Constitution. The amendment was subsequently ratified by:<ref name=CUSA:AA/>\n# [[North Carolina]] (February 28, 1951)\n# [[South Carolina]] (March 13, 1951)\n# [[Maryland]] (March 14, 1951)\n# [[Florida]] (April 16, 1951)\n# [[Alabama]] (May 4, 1951)\nConversely, two states\u2014[[Oklahoma]] and [[Massachusetts]]\u2014rejected the amendment, while five ([[Arizona]], [[Kentucky]], [[Rhode Island]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], and [[West Virginia]]) took no action.<ref name=tahlequahdailypress/>\n\n==Affected individuals==\nThe 22nd Amendment's two-term limit did not apply (due to the [[grandfather clause]] in Section 1) to Harry S. Truman, because he was the [[incumbent]] president at the time it was proposed by Congress. Truman, who had served nearly all of Franklin D. Roosevelt's unexpired fourth term and who was elected to a full term in [[1948 United States presidential election|1948]], was thus eligible to seek re-election in 1952.<ref name=\"NCC\"/> However, with his job approval rating floundering at around 27%,<ref>{{cite web |title=The Public and the 22nd Amendment: Third Terms and Lame Ducks |last=Weldon |first=Kathleen |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/kathleen-weldon/the-public-and-the-22nd-a_b_7967538.html |newspaper=Huffington Post |date=August 11, 2015 |access-date=March 27, 2018 }}</ref><ref name=APPtrumanJA>{{cite web |last1=Peters |first1=Gerhard |last2=Woolley |first2=John T. |title=Presidential Job Approval: F. Roosevelt (1941) \u2013 Trump |publisher=The American Presidency Project |location=Santa Barbara, California |url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/data/popularity.php?pres=33 |others=Data adapted from the [[Gallup (company)#Gallup Poll|Gallup Poll]] and compiled by Gerhard Peters |access-date=March 27, 2018 }}</ref> and after a poor performance in the [[New Hampshire primary#Winners and runners-up|1952 New Hampshire primary]], Truman chose not to seek his party's nomination. He theoretically also would have been eligible in later elections.\n\nSince [[coming into force]] in 1951, the amendment has applied to six presidents who have been elected twice: [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]], [[Richard Nixon]], [[Ronald Reagan]], [[Bill Clinton]], [[George W. Bush]], and [[Barack Obama]]. \n\nIt could have impacted two who entered office intra-term due to their predecessor's death or resignation: [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] and [[Gerald Ford]].<ref name=TermsTenure/> Johnson became president in November 1963, following the [[assassination of John F. Kennedy]], served out the final {{age in years and days|1963|11|22|1965|1|20|sep=and}} of Kennedy's term, and was elected to a full four-year term in [[1964 United States presidential election|1964]]. Four years later, he briefly ran for a second full term, but withdrew from the race during the [[1968 Democratic Party presidential primaries|party primaries]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Historically, odds were stacked against any President seeking a third term |date=December 27, 2016 |url=https://constitutioncenter.org/blog/historically-odds-were-stacked-against-any-president-seeking-a-third-term |work=Constitution Daily |publisher=The National Constitution Center |location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania |access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Johnson Says He Won't Run \u00b7 Surprise Decision: President Steps Aside in Unity Bid\u2014Says 'House' Is Divided |last=Wicker |first=Tom |work=The New York Times |date=April 1, 1968 |via=The Learning Network |url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/big/0331.html#article |access-date=March 22, 2018 }}</ref> Had Johnson served a second full term&nbsp;\u2013 through January 20, 1973&nbsp;\u2013 the total length of his presidency would have been {{age in years and days|1963|11|22|1973|1|20|sep=and}}; as it happened, Johnson died two days after this date.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/about-the-white-house/presidents/lyndon-b-johnson/ |title=Lyndon B. Johnson Biography |access-date=June 28, 2018 |publisher=The White House |year=2006 |first1=Frank |last1=Freidel |first2=Hugh |last2=Sidey }}</ref> Gerald Ford, who became president in August 1974 following the [[resignation of Richard Nixon]], served the final {{age in years and days|1974|8|9|1977|1|20|sep=and}} of Nixon's term, and attempted to win a full four-year term in [[1976 United States presidential election|1976]], but was defeated by [[Jimmy Carter]]. Johnson was eligible to be elected to two full terms in his own right, as he had served less than two years of Kennedy's unexpired term, whereas Ford was eligible to be elected to only one full term, as he had served more than two years of Nixon's unexpired term.<ref name=TermsTenure/>\n\n==Interaction with the Twelfth Amendment==\n{{See also|Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution#Interaction with the Twenty-second Amendment}}\n\nAs worded, the primary focus of the 22nd Amendment is on limiting individuals twice elected to the presidency from being elected again. Due to this, several issues could be raised regarding the amendment's meaning and application, especially in relation to the [[Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution|12th Amendment]], ratified in 1804, which states, \"But no person constitutionally ineligible to the office of President shall be eligible to that of Vice-President of the United States\".<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.archives.gov/founding-docs/amendments-11-27| title=The Constitution: Amendments 11-27| work=America's Founding Documents| publisher=National Archives| location=Washington, D.C.| accessdate=March 11, 2018}}</ref> While it is clear that under the 12th Amendment the original constitutional qualifications of age, citizenship, and residency apply to both the president and vice president, it is unclear whether someone who is ineligible to be elected president could be elected vice president. Because of this apparent ambiguity, there may be a loophole in the 22nd Amendment whereby a two-term former president could be elected vice president and then succeed to the presidency as a result of the incumbent's death, resignation, or removal from office (or even succeed to the presidency from some other stated office in the [[United States presidential line of succession|presidential line of succession]]).<ref name=PeabodyGant/><ref>{{cite web| url=https://cornerstonelaw.us/22nd-amendment-doesnt-say-think-says/| title=The 22nd Amendment Doesn't Say What You Think It Says | publisher=Cornerstone Law Firm| location=Blandon, Pennsylvania| last=Ready| first=Joel A. |accessdate=November 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSome argue that the 22nd Amendment and 12th Amendment bar any two-term president from later serving as vice president as well as from succeeding to the presidency from any point in the presidential line of succession.<ref>{{cite web| title=Constitutional Sleight of Hand| last=Franck| first=Matthew J.| date=July 31, 2007| accessdate=June 12, 2008| work=[[National Review]]|url=http://bench.nationalreview.com/post/?q=NDgwODVmMzcwMTQwNDM3YjU0OGE5ZjQyOTIxNmUyYzY=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080613214946/http://bench.nationalreview.com/post/?q=NDgwODVmMzcwMTQwNDM3YjU0OGE5ZjQyOTIxNmUyYzY=|archivedate=June 13, 2008}}</ref> Others contend that the [[original intent]] of the 12th Amendment concerns qualification for ''service'' (age, residence, and citizenship), while the 22nd Amendment, concerns qualifications for ''election'', and thus ([[Strict constructionism|strictly applying the text]]) a former two-term president is still eligible to ''serve'' as vice president (neither amendment restricts the number of times an individual can be elected to the vice presidency), and then succeed to the presidency to serve out the balance of the term (though prohibited from running for election to an additional term).<ref>{{cite news |title=Why the Constitution permits a Gore-Clinton ticket |authorlink=Michael C. Dorf| last=Dorf| first=Michael C.| publisher=[[CNN]]| url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/LAW/08/columns/fl.dorf.goreclinton.08.01/ | date=August 2, 2000 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051001004410/http://archives.cnn.com/2000/LAW/08/columns/fl.dorf.goreclinton.08.01/ |archive-date=October 1, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=How to bring back Bill: A Clinton-Clinton 2008 ticket is constitutionally possible| last1=Gant| first1=Scott E.| last2=Peabody| first2=Bruce G.| url=https://www.csmonitor.com/2006/0613/p09s02-coop.html| work=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]| date=June 13, 2006| accessdate=June 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe practical applicability of this distinction has not been tested, as no former president has ever sought the vice presidency. In 1980, former president Gerald Ford was mentioned as a possible vice presidential running mate for Republican presidential nominee Ronald Reagan, and there were some negotiations between the two camps, but nothing ever came of the idea.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/politics/2017/04/07/joe-louis-gop-convention/100197186/ |title=1980 convention launched 'Reagan Revolution' |first=Richard |last=Burr |date=April 7, 2017 |newspaper=The Detroit News |access-date=May 26, 2017 }}</ref> During [[Hillary Clinton 2016 presidential campaign|Hillary Clinton's 2016 presidential campaign]], she jokingly said that she had considered naming her husband Bill Clinton as her vice presidential running mate, but had been advised it would be unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite web| last=LoBianco| first=Tom| date=September 15, 2015 |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/09/14/politics/hillary-clinton-bill-clinton-vice-president/index.html |title=Hillary Clinton: Bill as VP has 'crossed her mind'| publisher=[[CNN]]| accessdate=October 29, 2015}}</ref> Most likely, the constitutional question raised will remain unanswered unless the situation actually occurs.<ref name=TermsTenure/>\n\n==Attempts at repeal==\nOver the years, several presidents have voiced their antipathy toward the amendment. After leaving office, Harry Truman variously described it as: \"bad\", \"stupid\", and \"one of the worst that has been put into the Constitution, except for the [[Eighteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Prohibition Amendment]]\".<ref>{{cite journal| title=Opposition to the 22nd Amendment: The National Committee Against Limiting the Presidency and its Activities, 1949-1951| last=Lemelin| first=Bernard Lemelin| journal=Canadian Review of American Studies| publisher=University of Toronto Press on behalf of the Canadian Association for American Studies with the support of Carleton University| volume=29| issue=3| date=Winter 1999| pages=133\u2013148| doi=10.3138/CRAS-029-03-06}}</ref> In January 1989, during an interview with [[Tom Brokaw]] a few days prior to leaving office, Ronald Reagan stated his intention to push for a repeal of the 22nd Amendment, calling it \"an infringement on the democratic rights of the people\".<ref>{{cite interview |last=Reagan |first=Ronald |subjectlink=Ronald Reagan |interviewer=[[Tom Brokaw]] |title=President Reagan Says He Will Fight to Repeal 22nd Amendment |work=[[NBC Nightly News]] |publisher=[[NBC]] |location=New York |date=January 18, 1989}} Retrieved June 14, 2015.</ref> In a November 2000 interview with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', out-going President Bill Clinton suggested that, given longer [[life expectancy]], perhaps the 22nd Amendment should be altered so as to limit presidents to two consecutive terms.<ref>{{cite web| title=Clinton: I Would've Won Third Term| publisher=[[ABC News]]| date=December 7, 2000| url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/story?id=122302&page=1| accessdate=March 26, 2018}}</ref> On multiple occasions since taking office in 2017, President [[Donald Trump]] has questioned presidential term limits and in public remarks has talked about serving beyond the limits of the 22nd Amendment. For instance, during an April 2019 White House event for the [[Wounded Warrior Project]], he joked that he would remain president \"at least for 10 or 14 years\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Einbinder |first=Nicole |title=Trump suggested his supporters want him to serve more than 2 terms as president |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-suggests-supporters-serve-more-two-terms-president-2019-6 |website=Business Insider |accessdate=September 14, 2019 |date=June 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Croucher |first=Shane |title=Donald Trump Posts Image on Twitter, Instagram Joking That He'll Stand in 2024 |url=https://www.newsweek.com/trump-twitter-instagram-joke-third-term-2024-1458686 |website=Newsweek |accessdate=September 14, 2019 |date=September 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first efforts in Congress to repeal the 22nd Amendment were undertaken in 1956, only five years after the amendment's ratification. According to the [[Congressional Research Service]], over the ensuing half-century (through 2008) 54 [[joint resolution]]s seeking to repeal the two-term presidential election limit were introduced (primarily in the House); none were given serious consideration.<ref name=TermsTenure/> Between 1997 and 2013, [[Jos\u00e9 E. Serrano]], Democratic representative for New York, introduced nine resolutions (one per Congress, all unsuccessful) to repeal the amendment.<ref>{{cite web| title=H.J.Res. 15 (113th): Proposing an amendment to the Constitution of the United States to repeal the twenty-second article of amendment, thereby removing the limitation on the number of terms an individual may serve as President| url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hjres15| date=2013| publisher=[[GovTrack]], a project of Civic Impulse, LLC| location=Washington, D.C.| accessdate=March 23, 2018}}</ref> Repeal has also been supported by senior congressmen such as [[Barney Frank]] and [[David Dreier]] and Senators [[Mitch McConnell]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/term-limits/|title=FACT CHECK: Bill to Repeal the 22nd Amendment}}</ref> and [[Harry Reid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://potus-geeks.livejournal.com/200091.html|title=The 22nd Amendment|last=potus_geeks|date=February 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Term limits in the United States]]\n* [[List of political term limits]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.annenbergclassroom.org/page/twenty-second-amendment The Annenberg Guide to the United States Constitution: Twenty-second Amendment]\n* [https://www.law.cornell.edu/anncon/html/amdt22toc_user.html CRS Annotated Constitution: Twenty-second Amendment]\n\n{{US Constitution}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:22}}\n[[Category:1951 in American law]]\n[[Category:1951 in American politics]]\n[[Category:Amendments to the United States Constitution]]\n[[Category:History of the United States (1945\u20131964)]]\n[[Category:Presidency of the United States]]\n[[Category:Term limits]]\n[[Category:80th United States Congress]]\n[[Category:1947 in American politics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = April 2019}}\n{{short description|Constitutional amendment limiting U.S. presidents to 2.5 terms}}\n{{Redirect|Twenty-second Amendment}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{US Constitution article series}}\nThe '''Twenty-second Amendment''' ('''Amendment XXII''') to the [[United States Constitution]] sets a limit on the number of times an individual is eligible for election to the office of [[President of the United States]], and also sets additional eligibility conditions for presidents who succeed to the unexpired terms of their predecessors.<ref name=TermsTenure>{{cite web| last=Neale| first=Thomas H.| title=Presidential Terms and Tenure: Perspectives and Proposals for Change| date=October 19, 2009| url=http://www.whitehousetransitionproject.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/Terms-Tenure_101909-1.pdf| publisher=Congressional Research Service, The Library of Congress| location=Washington, D.C.| accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref> \n\nto the ratification of the amendment, the president had not been subject to [[term limit]]s,  [[George Washington]] had established a two-term tradition that many other presidents had followed. In the [[1940 United States presidential election|1940 presidential election]] and the [[1944 United States presidential election|1944 presidential election]], [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] became the first president to win a third term and then later a fourth term, giving rise to concerns about the potential issues involved with a president serving an unlimited number of terms. [[United States Congress|Congress]] approved the Twenty-second Amendment on March 24, 1947, and submitted it to the [[State legislature (United States)|state legislatures]] for [[Article Five of the United States Constitution#Ratification|ratification]]. That process was completed on February 27, 1951, after the amendment had been ratified by the requisite 36 of the then-48 [[U.S. state|states]] (as neither [[Alaska]] nor [[Hawaii]] had been [[Admission to the Union|admitted as states]]), and its provisions [[Coming into force|came into force]] on that date.\n\nThe amendment prohibits any individual who has been elected president twice from being elected again. Under the amendment, an individual who fills an unexpired presidential term lasting greater than two years is also prohibited from winning election as president more than once. Scholars debate whether the amendment prohibits affected individuals from succeeding to the presidency under any circumstances or whether it only applies to presidential elections.\n\n==Text==\n<!-- Do not edit the words Article or President, they are capitalized as per the citation-->\n{{quote|'''Section 1.'''  No person shall be elected to the office of the President more than twice, and no person who has held the office of President, or acted as President, for more than two years of a term to which some other person was elected President shall be elected to the office of the President more than once. But this Article shall not apply to any person holding the office of President when this Article was proposed by the Congress, and shall not prevent any person who may be holding the office of President, or acting as President, during the term within which this Article becomes operative from holding the office of President or acting as President during the remainder of such term.}}\n\n{{quote|'''Section 2.''' This Article shall be inoperative unless it shall have been ratified as an amendment to the Constitution by the legislatures of three-fourths of the several states within seven years from the date of its submission to the states by the Congress.<ref name=CUSA:AA>{{cite web| title=Constitution of the United States of America: Analysis and Interpretation| url=https://www.congress.gov/content/conan/pdf/GPO-CONAN-2017.pdf| date=August 26, 2017| publisher=Library of Congress| location=Washington, D.C.| pages=39\u201340| accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref>}}\n\n==Background==\nNotwithstanding that the Twenty-second Amendment was clearly a reaction to [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]'s election to an unprecedented four terms as president, the notion of presidential [[term limit]]s has long been debated in American politics. Delegates to the [[Constitutional Convention (United States)|Constitutional Convention of 1787]] considered the issue extensively (alongside broader questions, such as who would elect the president, and the president's role). Many\u2014including [[Alexander Hamilton]] and [[James Madison]]\u2014supported a lifetime appointment for presidents, while others favored fixed terms appointments. Virginia's [[George Mason]] denounced the life-tenure proposal as tantamount to establishment of an [[elective monarchy]].<ref name=BuckleyMetzger>{{cite web| title=Twenty-second Amendment| last1=Buckley| first1=F. H.| last2=Metzger| first2=Gillian| url=https://constitutioncenter.org/interactive-constitution/amendments/amendment-xxii| work=The Interactive Constitution| publisher=The National Constitution Center| location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania| accessdate=March 19, 2018}}</ref>  An early draft of the United States Constitution provided that the President was restricted to a single seven-year term.<ref>First draft U.S.CONST., art. X, section 1.</ref>  Ultimately, the Framers approved four-year terms with no restriction on the amount of time a person could serve as president.\n\nThough dismissed by the Constitutional Convention, the concept of term limits for U.S. presidents took hold during the presidencies of [[George Washington]] and [[Thomas Jefferson]]. As his second term entered its final year in 1796, George Washington was exhausted from years of public service, and his health had begun to decline. He was also bothered by the unrelenting attacks from his political opponents, which had escalated after the signing of the [[Jay Treaty]], and believed that he had accomplished his major goals as president. For these reasons, he decided not to stand for reelection to a third term, a decision he announced to the nation through a ''[[George Washington's Farewell Address|Farewell Address]]'' in September 1796.<ref>{{cite book| last=Ferling| first=John| authorlink=John E. Ferling| title=The Ascent of George Washington: The Hidden Political Genius of an American Icon| date=2009| publisher=Bloomsbury Press| location=New York| pages=[https://archive.org/details/ascentofgeorgewa00ferl/page/347 347\u2013348]| isbn=978-1-59691-465-0| url=https://archive.org/details/ascentofgeorgewa00ferl/page/347}}</ref> Eleven years later, as Thomas Jefferson neared the half-way point of his second term, he wrote, {{quote|If some termination to the services of the chief magistrate be not fixed by the Constitution, or supplied by practice, his office, nominally for years, will in fact, become for life; and history shows how easily that degenerates into an inheritance.<ref>{{cite web |last=Jefferson |first=Thomas |date=December 10, 1807|title=Letter to the Legislature of Vermont |url=http://teachingamericanhistory.org/library/document/letter-to-the-legislature-of-vermont/ |accessdate=March 19, 2018 |publisher=TeachingAmericanHistory.org |location=Ashland, Ohio}}</ref>}}\n\nSince Washington made his historic announcement, numerous academics and public figures have looked at his decision to retire after two terms, and have, according to [[Political science|political scientist]] Bruce Peabody, \"argued he had established a ''two-term tradition'' that served as a vital check against any one person, or the presidency as a whole, accumulating too much power\".<ref name=Peabody22A>{{cite web| last=Peabody |first=Bruce| url=http://www.heritage.org/constitution/#!/amendments/22/essays/184/presidential-term-limit|title=Presidential Term Limit| publisher=The Heritage Foundation| accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref> Numerous amendments aimed toward changing informal precedent into constitutional law were proposed in Congress during the early to mid-19th century, but none passed.<ref name=BuckleyMetzger/><ref name=PeabodyGant>{{cite journal |last1=Peabody |first1=Bruce G. |last2=Gant |first2=Scott E. |date=February 1999 |title=The Twice and Future President: Constitutional Interstices and the Twenty-Second Amendment |url=http://alpha.fdu.edu/~peabody/Twice_and_Future_President.html |journal=Minnesota Law Review |publisher=University of Minnesota Law School |location=Minneapolis |volume=83 |issue=3 |pages=565\u2013635 |access-date=June 12, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115121046/http://alpha.fdu.edu/~peabody/Twice_and_Future_President.html |archive-date=January 15, 2013}}</ref> Three of the next four presidents after Jefferson\u2014[[James Madison]], [[James Monroe]], and [[Andrew Jackson]]\u2014served two terms, and each one adhered to the two-term principle;<ref name=TermsTenure/> Martin Van Buren was the only president between Jackson and [[Abraham Lincoln]] to be nominated for a second term, although he lost the [[1840 United States presidential election|1840 election]], and so only served one term.<ref name=PeabodyGant/>  Before the Civil War the seceding States drafted the [[Constitution of the Confederate States of America]] which in most respects was similar to the United States Constitution, but one change was limiting the President to a single six-year term.\n\n[[File:The Appomattox of the third termers - unconditional surrender LCCN97515771.tif|alt=Cartoon showing Ulysses S. Grant handing a sword to James Garfield, who is holding a rolled-up paper.|thumb|left|upright=1.25|[[Ulysses S. Grant]] is shown surrendering to [[James A. Garfield]] after losing the 1880 Republican presidential nomination to him, in this [[Political satire|satirical]] ''[[Puck (magazine)|Puck]]'' cartoon.]]\n\nIn spite of the strong two-term tradition, a few presidents prior to Franklin Roosevelt did attempt to secure a third term. Following [[Ulysses S. Grant]]'s reelection victory in [[1872 United States presidential election|1872]], there were serious discussions within Republican political circles about the possibility of his running again in 1876. Interest in a third term for Grant evaporated however, in the light of negative public opinion and opposition from members of Congress, and Grant left the presidency in 1877, after two terms. Even so, as the 1880 election approached, he sought nomination for a (non-consecutive) third term at the [[1880 Republican National Convention]], but narrowly lost to [[James Garfield]], who would go on to win the [[1880 United States presidential election|1880 election]].<ref name=PeabodyGant/>\n\n[[Theodore Roosevelt]] succeeded to the presidency on September 14, 1901, following [[Assassination of William McKinley|William McKinley's assassination]] ({{age in days|Mar 4 1901|Sep 14 1901}} days into his second term), and was subsequently elected to a full term in [[1904 United States presidential election|1904]]. While he declined to seek a third (second full) term in 1908, Roosevelt did seek one four years later, in the [[1912 United States presidential election|election of 1912]], where he lost to [[Woodrow Wilson]]. Wilson himself, despite his ill health following a serious stroke, aspired to a third term. Many of Wilson's advisers tried to convince him that his health precluded another campaign, but Wilson nonetheless asked that his name be placed in nomination for the presidency at the [[1920 Democratic National Convention]].<ref>{{Cite book |title=The Year of the Six Presidents |last=Pietrusza |first=David |publisher=Carroll and Graf |location=New York |date=2007 |isbn=978-0-78671-622-7 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780786716227/page/187 187\u2013200] |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780786716227/page/187 }}</ref> Democratic Party leaders were unwilling to support Wilson, however, and the nomination eventually went to [[James M. Cox]], who lost to [[Warren G. Harding]]. Wilson again contemplated running for a (nonconsecutive) third term in 1924, devising a strategy for his comeback, but again lacked any support; he died in February of that year.<ref>{{Cite book |title=In Search of Woodrow Wilson: Beliefs and Behavior |url=https://books.google.com/?id=b2A8WtVeFc4C&pg=PA261#v=onepage&q&f=false |publisher=Greenwood Press |location=Westport, Connecticut |date=1998 |isbn= 9780313305207 |first=Robert M. |last=Saunders |pages=260\u2013262}}</ref>\n\n[[File:FDR 1944 Color Portrait.jpg|thumb|upright=.75|right|[[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], elected to four terms, was president from 1933 until his death in 1945.]]\n\nFranklin D. Roosevelt spent the months leading up to the [[1940 Democratic National Convention]] refusing to state whether he would seek a third term. His Vice President, [[John Nance Garner]], along with [[United States Postmaster General|Postmaster General]] [[James Farley]], announced their candidacies for the Democratic nomination. When the convention came, Roosevelt sent a message to the convention, saying he would run only if [[Draft (politics)|drafted]], saying delegates were free to vote for whomever they pleased. This message was interpreted to mean he was willing to be drafted, and he subsequently was renominated on the convention's first ballot.<ref name=PeabodyGant/><ref>{{cite book| last=Rosen| first=Elliot A.| editor-last=Walch| editor-first=Timothy| title=At the President's Side: The Vice Presidency in the Twentieth Century| chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PBYghyfZjOUC&pg=PA52#v=onepage&q&f=false| chapter='Not Worth a Pitcher of Warm Piss': John Nance Garner as Vice President| date=1997| publisher=University of Missouri Press| location=Columbia, Missouri| pages=[https://archive.org/details/atpresidentsside00walc/page/52 52\u201353]| isbn=0-8262-1133-X| accessdate=March 20, 2018| url=https://archive.org/details/atpresidentsside00walc/page/52}}</ref> Later, during the [[1940 United States presidential election|1940 presidential election]], Roosevelt won a decisive victory over Republican [[Wendell Willkie]], becoming the first, and to date only, president to exceed eight years in office. Roosevelt's decision to seek a third term dominated the election campaign.<ref name=\"NCC\">{{cite web| url=https://constitutioncenter.org/blog/fdrs-third-term-decision-and-the-22nd-amendment/| title=FDR's third-term decision and the 22nd amendment| work=Constitution Daily| publisher=The National Constitution Center| location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania| accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref> Willkie ran against the open-ended presidential tenure, while Democrats cited the [[World War II|war in Europe]] as a reason for breaking with precedent.<ref name=PeabodyGant/>\n\nFour years later, Roosevelt faced Republican [[Thomas E. Dewey]] in the [[1944 United States presidential election|1944 election]]. Near the end of the campaign, Thomas Dewey announced his support of a constitutional amendment that would limit future presidents to two terms. According to Dewey, \"four terms, or sixteen years (a direct reference to the president's tenure in office four years hence), is the most dangerous threat to our freedom ever proposed.\"<ref>{{cite book| title=FDR, Dewey, and the Election of 1944| last=Jordan| first=David M.| publisher=Indiana University Press| location=Bloomington, Indiana| date=2011| page=[https://archive.org/details/fdrdeweyelection0000jord/page/290 290]| isbn=978-0-253-35683-3| url=https://archive.org/details/fdrdeweyelection0000jord/page/290}}</ref> He also discreetly raised the issue of the president's age. Roosevelt, however, was able to exude enough energy and charisma to retain the confidence of the American public, who reelected him to a fourth term.<ref>{{cite web| last=Leuchtenburg| first=William E.| url=https://millercenter.org/president/fdroosevelt/campaigns-and-elections| title=Franklin D. Roosevelt: Campaigns and Elections| publisher=Miller Center of Public Affairs, University of Virginia| location=Charlottesville, Virginia| accessdate=March 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWhile he effectively quelled rumors of his poor health during the campaign, Roosevelt's health was in reality deteriorating. On April 12, 1945, only {{age in days|Jan 20, 1945|Apr 12, 1945}} days after his [[Fourth inauguration of Franklin D. Roosevelt|fourth inauguration]], he suffered a cerebral hemorrhage and [[List of Presidents of the United States who died in office#1945: Franklin D. Roosevelt|died]]. He was succeeded by Vice President [[Harry Truman]].<ref>{{cite web| last=Leuchtenburg| first=William E.| url=https://millercenter.org/president/fdroosevelt/death-of-the-president| title=Franklin D. Roosevelt: Death of the President| publisher=Miller Center of Public Affairs, University of Virginia| location=Charlottesville, Virginia| accessdate=March 20, 2018}}</ref> In the [[1946 United States elections|midterm elections]] {{age in months|1945|4|12|1946|11|5}} months later, Republicans took control of both the House and the Senate. As many of them had campaigned on the issue of presidential tenure, declaring their support for a constitutional amendment that would limit how long a person could serve as president, the issue was given top priority in the [[80th Congress]] when it convened in January 1947.<ref name=Peabody22A/>\n\n==Proposal and ratification==\n===Proposal in Congress===\n{{see also|Presidency of Harry S. Truman}}\n\nThe [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] took quick action, approving a proposed constitutional amendment (House [[Joint Resolution]]&nbsp;27) setting a limit of two four-year terms for future presidents. Introduced by [[Earl C. Michener]], the measure passed 285\u2013121, with support from 47 Democrats, on February 6, 1947. Meanwhile, the Senate developed its own proposed amendment, which initially differed from the House proposal by requiring that the amendment be submitted to [[state ratifying conventions]] for ratification, rather than to the state legislatures, and by prohibiting any person who had served more than 365 days in each of two terms from further presidential service. Both these provisions were removed when the full Senate took up the bill, but a new provision was, however, added. Put forward by [[Robert A. Taft]], it clarified procedures governing the number of times a vice president who succeeded to the presidency might be elected to office. The amended proposal was passed 59\u201323, with 16 Democrats in favor, on March 12.<ref name=TermsTenure/><ref name=tahlequahdailypress>{{Cite news| title=Presidential terms limited by 22nd Amendment| last=Rowley| first=Sean| date=July 26, 2014| url=http://www.tahlequahdailypress.com/news/features/presidential-terms-limited-by-nd-amendment/article_abfac7ef-c505-55f2-b171-08bc83b6914d.html| work=Tahlequah Daily Press| accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeveral days later, the House agreed to the Senate's revisions, and on March 24, 1947, the constitutional amendment imposing term limitations on future Presidents was submitted to the states for ratification.<ref name=CUSA:AA/> The ratification process for the 22nd Amendment was completed on February 27, 1951, {{age in years and days|1947|3|21|1951|2|27}} after it was sent to the states.<ref name=\"NCC\"/><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.usconstitution.net/constamrat.html| title=Ratification of Constitutional Amendments| accessdate=May 9, 2012| last=Mount| first=Steve| date=January 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Ratification by the states===\n[[File:The Ratification of the Twenty-Second Amendment.png|thumb|A map of how the states voted on the Twenty-second Amendment]]\n[[Image:22nd Amendment Pg1of1 AC.jpg|thumb|The Twenty-Second Amendment in the [[National Archives and Records Administration|National Archives]]]]\nOnce submitted to the states, the 22nd Amendment was ratified by:<ref name=CUSA:AA/>\n# [[Maine]] (March 31, 1947)\n# [[Michigan]] (March 31, 1947)\n# [[Iowa]] (April 1, 1947)\n# [[Kansas]] (April 1, 1947)\n# [[New Hampshire]] (April 1, 1947)\n# [[Delaware]] (April 2, 1947)\n# [[Illinois]] (April 3, 1947)\n# [[Oregon]] (April 3, 1947)\n# [[Colorado]] (April 12, 1947)\n# [[California]] (April 15, 1947)\n# [[New Jersey]] (April 15, 1947)\n# [[Vermont]] (April 15, 1947)\n# [[Ohio]] (April 16, 1947)\n# [[Wisconsin]] (April 16, 1947)\n# [[Pennsylvania]] (April 29, 1947)\n# [[Connecticut]] (May 21, 1947)\n# [[Missouri]] (May 22, 1947)\n# [[Nebraska]] (May 23, 1947)\n# [[Virginia]] (January 28, 1948)\n# [[Mississippi]] (February 12, 1948)\n# [[New York (state)|New York]] (March 9, 1948)\n# [[South Dakota]] (January 21, 1949)\n# [[North Dakota]] (February 25, 1949)\n# [[Louisiana]] (May 17, 1950)\n# [[Montana]] (January 25, 1951)\n# [[Indiana]] (January 29, 1951)\n# [[Idaho]] (January 30, 1951)\n# [[New Mexico]] (February 12, 1951)\n# [[Wyoming]] (February 12, 1951)\n# [[Arkansas]] (February 15, 1951)\n# [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] (February 17, 1951)\n# [[Tennessee]] (February 20, 1951)\n# [[Texas]] (February 22, 1951)\n# [[Utah]] (February 26, 1951)\n# [[Nevada]] (February 26, 1951)\n# [[Minnesota]] (February 27, 1951)<br>Ratification was completed when the [[Minnesota Legislature]] ratified the amendment. On March 1, 1951, the Administrator of [[General Services Administration|General Services]], [[Jess Larson]], issued a certificate [[Promulgation|proclaiming]] the 22nd Amendment duly ratified and part of the Constitution. The amendment was subsequently ratified by:<ref name=CUSA:AA/>\n# [[North Carolina]] (February 28, 1951)\n# [[South Carolina]] (March 13, 1951)\n# [[Maryland]] (March 14, 1951)\n# [[Florida]] (April 16, 1951)\n# [[Alabama]] (May 4, 1951)\nConversely, two states\u2014[[Oklahoma]] and [[Massachusetts]]\u2014rejected the amendment, while five ([[Arizona]], [[Kentucky]], [[Rhode Island]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], and [[West Virginia]]) took no action.<ref name=tahlequahdailypress/>\n\n==Affected individuals==\nThe 22nd Amendment's two-term limit did not apply (due to the [[grandfather clause]] in Section 1) to Harry S. Truman, because he was the [[incumbent]] president at the time it was proposed by Congress. Truman, who had served nearly all of Franklin D. Roosevelt's unexpired fourth term and who was elected to a full term in [[1948 United States presidential election|1948]], was thus eligible to seek re-election in 1952.<ref name=\"NCC\"/> However, with his job approval rating floundering at around 27%,<ref>{{cite web |title=The Public and the 22nd Amendment: Third Terms and Lame Ducks |last=Weldon |first=Kathleen |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/kathleen-weldon/the-public-and-the-22nd-a_b_7967538.html |newspaper=Huffington Post |date=August 11, 2015 |access-date=March 27, 2018 }}</ref><ref name=APPtrumanJA>{{cite web |last1=Peters |first1=Gerhard |last2=Woolley |first2=John T. |title=Presidential Job Approval: F. Roosevelt (1941) \u2013 Trump |publisher=The American Presidency Project |location=Santa Barbara, California |url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/data/popularity.php?pres=33 |others=Data adapted from the [[Gallup (company)#Gallup Poll|Gallup Poll]] and compiled by Gerhard Peters |access-date=March 27, 2018 }}</ref> and after a poor performance in the [[New Hampshire primary#Winners and runners-up|1952 New Hampshire primary]], Truman chose not to seek his party's nomination. He theoretically also would have been eligible in later elections.\n\nSince [[coming into force]] in 1951, the amendment has applied to six presidents who have been elected twice: [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]], [[Richard Nixon]], [[Ronald Reagan]], [[Bill Clinton]], [[George W. Bush]], and [[Barack Obama]]. \n\nIt could have impacted two who entered office intra-term due to their predecessor's death or resignation: [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] and [[Gerald Ford]].<ref name=TermsTenure/> Johnson became president in November 1963, following the [[assassination of John F. Kennedy]], served out the final {{age in years and days|1963|11|22|1965|1|20|sep=and}} of Kennedy's term, and was elected to a full four-year term in [[1964 United States presidential election|1964]]. Four years later, he briefly ran for a second full term, but withdrew from the race during the [[1968 Democratic Party presidential primaries|party primaries]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Historically, odds were stacked against any President seeking a third term |date=December 27, 2016 |url=https://constitutioncenter.org/blog/historically-odds-were-stacked-against-any-president-seeking-a-third-term |work=Constitution Daily |publisher=The National Constitution Center |location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania |access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Johnson Says He Won't Run \u00b7 Surprise Decision: President Steps Aside in Unity Bid\u2014Says 'House' Is Divided |last=Wicker |first=Tom |work=The New York Times |date=April 1, 1968 |via=The Learning Network |url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/big/0331.html#article |access-date=March 22, 2018 }}</ref> Had Johnson served a second full term&nbsp;\u2013 through January 20, 1973&nbsp;\u2013 the total length of his presidency would have been {{age in years and days|1963|11|22|1973|1|20|sep=and}}; as it happened, Johnson died two days after this date.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/about-the-white-house/presidents/lyndon-b-johnson/ |title=Lyndon B. Johnson Biography |access-date=June 28, 2018 |publisher=The White House |year=2006 |first1=Frank |last1=Freidel |first2=Hugh |last2=Sidey }}</ref> Gerald Ford, who became president in August 1974 following the [[resignation of Richard Nixon]], served the final {{age in years and days|1974|8|9|1977|1|20|sep=and}} of Nixon's term, and attempted to win a full four-year term in [[1976 United States presidential election|1976]], but was defeated by [[Jimmy Carter]]. Johnson was eligible to be elected to two full terms in his own right, as he had served less than two years of Kennedy's unexpired term, whereas Ford was eligible to be elected to only one full term, as he had served more than two years of Nixon's unexpired term.<ref name=TermsTenure/>\n\n==Interaction with the Twelfth Amendment==\n{{See also|Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution#Interaction with the Twenty-second Amendment}}\n\nAs worded, the primary focus of the 22nd Amendment is on limiting individuals twice elected to the presidency from being elected again. Due to this, several issues could be raised regarding the amendment's meaning and application, especially in relation to the [[Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution|12th Amendment]], ratified in 1804, which states, \"But no person constitutionally ineligible to the office of President shall be eligible to that of Vice-President of the United States\".<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.archives.gov/founding-docs/amendments-11-27| title=The Constitution: Amendments 11-27| work=America's Founding Documents| publisher=National Archives| location=Washington, D.C.| accessdate=March 11, 2018}}</ref> While it is clear that under the 12th Amendment the original constitutional qualifications of age, citizenship, and residency apply to both the president and vice president, it is unclear whether someone who is ineligible to be elected president could be elected vice president. Because of this apparent ambiguity, there may be a loophole in the 22nd Amendment whereby a two-term former president could be elected vice president and then succeed to the presidency as a result of the incumbent's death, resignation, or removal from office (or even succeed to the presidency from some other stated office in the [[United States presidential line of succession|presidential line of succession]]).<ref name=PeabodyGant/><ref>{{cite web| url=https://cornerstonelaw.us/22nd-amendment-doesnt-say-think-says/| title=The 22nd Amendment Doesn't Say What You Think It Says | publisher=Cornerstone Law Firm| location=Blandon, Pennsylvania| last=Ready| first=Joel A. |accessdate=November 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSome argue that the 22nd Amendment and 12th Amendment bar any two-term president from later serving as vice president as well as from succeeding to the presidency from any point in the presidential line of succession.<ref>{{cite web| title=Constitutional Sleight of Hand| last=Franck| first=Matthew J.| date=July 31, 2007| accessdate=June 12, 2008| work=[[National Review]]|url=http://bench.nationalreview.com/post/?q=NDgwODVmMzcwMTQwNDM3YjU0OGE5ZjQyOTIxNmUyYzY=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080613214946/http://bench.nationalreview.com/post/?q=NDgwODVmMzcwMTQwNDM3YjU0OGE5ZjQyOTIxNmUyYzY=|archivedate=June 13, 2008}}</ref> Others contend that the [[original intent]] of the 12th Amendment concerns qualification for ''service'' (age, residence, and citizenship), while the 22nd Amendment, concerns qualifications for ''election'', and thus ([[Strict constructionism|strictly applying the text]]) a former two-term president is still eligible to ''serve'' as vice president (neither amendment restricts the number of times an individual can be elected to the vice presidency), and then succeed to the presidency to serve out the balance of the term (though prohibited from running for election to an additional term).<ref>{{cite news |title=Why the Constitution permits a Gore-Clinton ticket |authorlink=Michael C. Dorf| last=Dorf| first=Michael C.| publisher=[[CNN]]| url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/LAW/08/columns/fl.dorf.goreclinton.08.01/ | date=August 2, 2000 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051001004410/http://archives.cnn.com/2000/LAW/08/columns/fl.dorf.goreclinton.08.01/ |archive-date=October 1, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=How to bring back Bill: A Clinton-Clinton 2008 ticket is constitutionally possible| last1=Gant| first1=Scott E.| last2=Peabody| first2=Bruce G.| url=https://www.csmonitor.com/2006/0613/p09s02-coop.html| work=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]| date=June 13, 2006| accessdate=June 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe practical applicability of this distinction has not been tested, as no former president has ever sought the vice presidency. In 1980, former president Gerald Ford was mentioned as a possible vice presidential running mate for Republican presidential nominee Ronald Reagan, and there were some negotiations between the two camps, but nothing ever came of the idea.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/politics/2017/04/07/joe-louis-gop-convention/100197186/ |title=1980 convention launched 'Reagan Revolution' |first=Richard |last=Burr |date=April 7, 2017 |newspaper=The Detroit News |access-date=May 26, 2017 }}</ref> During [[Hillary Clinton 2016 presidential campaign|Hillary Clinton's 2016 presidential campaign]], she jokingly said that she had considered naming her husband Bill Clinton as her vice presidential running mate, but had been advised it would be unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite web| last=LoBianco| first=Tom| date=September 15, 2015 |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/09/14/politics/hillary-clinton-bill-clinton-vice-president/index.html |title=Hillary Clinton: Bill as VP has 'crossed her mind'| publisher=[[CNN]]| accessdate=October 29, 2015}}</ref> Most likely, the constitutional question raised will remain unanswered unless the situation actually occurs.<ref name=TermsTenure/>\n\n==Attempts at repeal==\nOver the years, several presidents have voiced their antipathy toward the amendment. After leaving office, Harry Truman variously described it as: \"bad\", \"stupid\", and \"one of the worst that has been put into the Constitution, except for the [[Eighteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Prohibition Amendment]]\".<ref>{{cite journal| title=Opposition to the 22nd Amendment: The National Committee Against Limiting the Presidency and its Activities, 1949-1951| last=Lemelin| first=Bernard Lemelin| journal=Canadian Review of American Studies| publisher=University of Toronto Press on behalf of the Canadian Association for American Studies with the support of Carleton University| volume=29| issue=3| date=Winter 1999| pages=133\u2013148| doi=10.3138/CRAS-029-03-06}}</ref> In January 1989, during an interview with [[Tom Brokaw]] a few days prior to leaving office, Ronald Reagan stated his intention to push for a repeal of the 22nd Amendment, calling it \"an infringement on the democratic rights of the people\".<ref>{{cite interview |last=Reagan |first=Ronald |subjectlink=Ronald Reagan |interviewer=[[Tom Brokaw]] |title=President Reagan Says He Will Fight to Repeal 22nd Amendment |work=[[NBC Nightly News]] |publisher=[[NBC]] |location=New York |date=January 18, 1989}} Retrieved June 14, 2015.</ref> In a November 2000 interview with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', out-going President Bill Clinton suggested that, given longer [[life expectancy]], perhaps the 22nd Amendment should be altered so as to limit presidents to two consecutive terms.<ref>{{cite web| title=Clinton: I Would've Won Third Term| publisher=[[ABC News]]| date=December 7, 2000| url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/story?id=122302&page=1| accessdate=March 26, 2018}}</ref> On multiple occasions since taking office in 2017, President [[Donald Trump]] has questioned presidential term limits and in public remarks has talked about serving beyond the limits of the 22nd Amendment. For instance, during an April 2019 White House event for the [[Wounded Warrior Project]], he joked that he would remain president \"at least for 10 or 14 years\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Einbinder |first=Nicole |title=Trump suggested his supporters want him to serve more than 2 terms as president |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-suggests-supporters-serve-more-two-terms-president-2019-6 |website=Business Insider |accessdate=September 14, 2019 |date=June 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Croucher |first=Shane |title=Donald Trump Posts Image on Twitter, Instagram Joking That He'll Stand in 2024 |url=https://www.newsweek.com/trump-twitter-instagram-joke-third-term-2024-1458686 |website=Newsweek |accessdate=September 14, 2019 |date=September 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first efforts in Congress to repeal the 22nd Amendment were undertaken in 1956, only five years after the amendment's ratification. According to the [[Congressional Research Service]], over the ensuing half-century (through 2008) 54 [[joint resolution]]s seeking to repeal the two-term presidential election limit were introduced (primarily in the House); none were given serious consideration.<ref name=TermsTenure/> Between 1997 and 2013, [[Jos\u00e9 E. Serrano]], Democratic representative for New York, introduced nine resolutions (one per Congress, all unsuccessful) to repeal the amendment.<ref>{{cite web| title=H.J.Res. 15 (113th): Proposing an amendment to the Constitution of the United States to repeal the twenty-second article of amendment, thereby removing the limitation on the number of terms an individual may serve as President| url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hjres15| date=2013| publisher=[[GovTrack]], a project of Civic Impulse, LLC| location=Washington, D.C.| accessdate=March 23, 2018}}</ref> Repeal has also been supported by senior congressmen such as [[Barney Frank]] and [[David Dreier]] and Senators [[Mitch McConnell]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/term-limits/|title=FACT CHECK: Bill to Repeal the 22nd Amendment}}</ref> and [[Harry Reid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://potus-geeks.livejournal.com/200091.html|title=The 22nd Amendment|last=potus_geeks|date=February 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Term limits in the United States]]\n* [[List of political term limits]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.annenbergclassroom.org/page/twenty-second-amendment The Annenberg Guide to the United States Constitution: Twenty-second Amendment]\n* [https://www.law.cornell.edu/anncon/html/amdt22toc_user.html CRS Annotated Constitution: Twenty-second Amendment]\n\n{{US Constitution}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:22}}\n[[Category:1951 in American law]]\n[[Category:1951 in American politics]]\n[[Category:Amendments to the United States Constitution]]\n[[Category:History of the United States (1945\u20131964)]]\n[[Category:Presidency of the United States]]\n[[Category:Term limits]]\n[[Category:80th United States Congress]]\n[[Category:1947 in American politics]]\n", "name_user": "Helena Otto", "label": "safe", "comment": "did some things", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Twenty-second_Amendment_to_the_United_States_Constitution"}
{"title_page": "Smiljana Rendi\u0107", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Smiljana Rendi\u0107\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1926|08|27}}\n| birth_place   = [[Split, Croatia]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1994|05|26|1926|08|27}} \n| death_place   = [[Rijeka]], [[Croatia]]\n| nationality   = [[Croats|Croat]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[journalist]], [[translator]], [[vaticanist]], [[Judaism studies|judaist scholar]], [[poet]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Smiljana Rendi\u0107''' was a [[Croats|Croatian]] woman [[journalist]], [[translator]], [[vaticanist]], [[Judaism studies|judaist scholar]], [[poet]], notable for her reporting from [[Second Vatican Council]] and for [[censorship]] by rulling [[SFRJ|Communist authorities of Yugoslavia]] due to her [[Catholic]] and [[Croats|Croatian]] orientation.<ref> Jeli\u010di\u0107, A., 2019: [https://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=323560 Smiljana Rendi\u0107: katoli\u010dka novinarka i pratiteljica Drugoga vatikanskog sabora] ''Crkva u svijetu'' '''54''' (2), 299-302. </ref><ref name=bagdasarov> Bagdasarov, Artur: [http://www.matica.hr/vijenac/470/Jezik%20kojim%20nitko%20nikad%20nije%20govorio%20/ Jezik kojim nitko nikad nije govorio] [The language nobody has spoken] ''[[Vijenac]]'' '''470''' (8 March 2012). Access date 15 April 2020. </ref><ref name=ika/><ref> Burilovi\u0107-Crnov, S., 2019: ''Smiljana Rendi\u0107. Katoli\u010dka novinarka i pratiteljica Drugoga vatikanskog sabora'' [Smiljana Rendi\u0107: Catholic journalist and reporter from the Second Vatican Council] Doctoral dissertation. Review of the dissertation: Matkovi\u0107-Vla\u0161i\u0107, Lj., 2019: [https://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=324658 Ime koje valja pamtiti - Silvana BURILOVI\u0106 CRNOV, Smiljana Rendi\u0107. Katoli\u010dka novinarka i pratiteljica Drugoga vatikanskog sabora, Katoli\u010dki bogoslovni fakultet, Doktorska disertacija iz fundamentalne teologije, Split, 2019, 550 str.] ''Nova prisutnost : \u010dasopis za intelektualna i duhovna pitanja'' '''XVII''' (II), 411-412. </ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nRendi\u0107 was born in [[Split, Croatia]] in 1926, in the family of Marko and Ivana (ne\u00e9 Ruzinovi\u0107) Rendi\u0107, where she attended the gymnasium. Her family's property was confiscated by the Communist authorities due to her father's activity in [[Croatian Peasants' Party]]. Hence she was unable to finish her higher education, she was firstly employed in Jugovinil [[factory]]. Later she moved to [[Rijeka]], where thanks to her knowledge of [[Italian language]] Rendi\u0107 started working in the editorial committee of ''La Voce del Popolo'' newspaper. She also wrote for ''Pomorstvo'' (Seamanship) magazine until 1972, as well as reported for ''[[Glas Koncila]]''<ref> Vukovi\u0107, Tomislav: [https://www.glas-koncila.hr/sds-ov-dosje-o-nadbiskupu-viktoru-buricu-27-odbijen-prijedlog-da-se-diktatoru-krvavih-ruku-dodijeli-nobelova-nagrada/ SDS-ov DOSJE O (NAD)BISKUPU VIKTORU BURI\u0106U (27) Odbijen prijedlog da se diktatoru \u00bbkrvavih ruku\u00ab dodijeli Nobelova nagrada] ''[[Glas Koncila]]''. Published 27 February 2020. Access date 15 April 2020. </ref> and other Catholic periodicals under the guise of her [[pseudonym]]s Vjera Marini and Madam Berith.<ref name=ika> [https://ika.hkm.hr/novosti/umrla-smiljana-rendic/ Umrla Smiljana Rendi\u0107] [Smiljana Rendi\u0107 died] Informative Catholic Agency (IKA). Published 27 May 1994. Access date 15 April 2020. </ref> Rendi\u0107 also published her [[poem]]s (mostly [[sonnets]]<ref> Rendi\u0107, S., 1999: [https://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=113828 X. milost slova] ''Jezik: \u010dasopis za kulturu hrvatskoga knji\u017eevnog jezika'' '''47''' (4), 161-161. </ref>) in various periodicals.\n\nRendi\u0107 was sued by the Communist authorities for her article ''The genitive exit or the Second Croatian revival'' in ''Kritika'' magazine (no. 18) in 1971, in which she criticized Yugoslav integralism and \"linguistic colonisation\" of [[Croatian language]] (as partially stated in [[Declaration on the Name and Status of the Croatian Literary Language]]) and endorsed intellectual and academical requests of [[Croatian Spring]].<ref> [http://www.hkv.hr/vijesti/dokumenti/12768-smiljana-rendic-izlazak-iz-genitiva-ili-drugi-hrvatski-preporod.html Original text of the article] published by Croatian Culture Council on 13 May 2012. Access date 15 April 2020. </ref> Rendi\u0107's advocate was [[Milan Vukovi\u0107 (jurist)|Milan Vukovi\u0107]], who will later become president of the [[Supreme Court of Croatia]]. As a result of the [[show trial]] at the Supreme Court of SFRY in [[November]] [[1973]], Rendi\u0107 was forcibly retired and sentenced to one-year prison punishment, while ''Kritika'' magazine was censored.<ref name=bagdasarov/><ref name=ika/>\n\nShe was a member of the editorial committee of the ''Glas Koncila'' 1963-1994. For her's [[Bible study (Christianity)|biblistic]], [[Jewish studies|judaistic]] and journalist work, she was posthumously awarded by [[Croatian Bishops' Conference]] unique award ''Zlatno pero'' (\"Golden feather\") that wasn't given to anybody else except her.<ref name=ika/> \n\n== Works ==\n* [https://archive.org/details/Crni_sator-berithsmiljana_rendic/mode/2up ''Crni \u0161ator''] (Black tent), Glas Koncila, 1967.\n* [https://knjizara.glas-koncila.hr/katolicki-identitet-i-hrvatski-preporod.html ''Katoli\u010dki identitet i hrvatski preporod''] (Catholic identity and Croatian revival), Glas Koncila, Zagreb, 2012, ISBN 978-953-241-368-7.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rendi\u0107, Smiljana}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:1994 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Split, Croatia]]\n[[Category:Croatian journalists]]\n[[Category:Croatian translators]]\n[[Category:Croatian poets]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Smiljana Rendi\u0107\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1926|08|27}}\n| birth_place   = [[Split, Croatia]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1994|05|26|1926|08|27}} \n| death_place   = [[Rijeka]], [[Croatia]]\n| nationality   = [[Croats|Croat]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[journalist]], [[translator]], [[vaticanist]], [[Judaism studies|judaist scholar]], [[poet]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Smiljana Rendi\u0107''' was a [[Croats|Croatian]] woman [[journalist]], [[translator]], [[vaticanist]], [[Judaism studies|judaist scholar]], [[poet]], notable for her reporting from [[Second Vatican Council]] and for [[censorship]] by rulling [[SFRJ|Communist authorities of Yugoslavia]] due to her [[Catholic]] and [[Croats|Croatian]] orientation.<ref> Jeli\u010di\u0107, A., 2019: [https://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=323560 Smiljana Rendi\u0107: katoli\u010dka novinarka i pratiteljica Drugoga vatikanskog sabora] ''Crkva u svijetu'' '''54''' (2), 299-302. </ref><ref name=bagdasarov> Bagdasarov, Artur: [http://www.matica.hr/vijenac/470/Jezik%20kojim%20nitko%20nikad%20nije%20govorio%20/ Jezik kojim nitko nikad nije govorio] [The language nobody has spoken] ''[[Vijenac]]'' '''470''' (8 March 2012). Access date 15 April 2020. </ref><ref name=ika/><ref> Burilovi\u0107-Crnov, S., 2019: ''Smiljana Rendi\u0107. Katoli\u010dka novinarka i pratiteljica Drugoga vatikanskog sabora'' [Smiljana Rendi\u0107: Catholic journalist and reporter from the Second Vatican Council] Doctoral dissertation. Review of the dissertation: Matkovi\u0107-Vla\u0161i\u0107, Lj., 2019: [https://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=324658 Ime koje valja pamtiti - Silvana BURILOVI\u0106 CRNOV, Smiljana Rendi\u0107. Katoli\u010dka novinarka i pratiteljica Drugoga vatikanskog sabora, Katoli\u010dki bogoslovni fakultet, Doktorska disertacija iz fundamentalne teologije, Split, 2019, 550 str.] ''Nova prisutnost : \u010dasopis za intelektualna i duhovna pitanja'' '''XVII''' (II), 411-412. </ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nRendi\u0107 was born in [[Split, Croatia]] in 1926, in the family of Marko and Ivana (ne\u00e9 Ruzinovi\u0107) Rendi\u0107, where she attended the gymnasium. Her family's property was confiscated by the Communist authorities due to her father's activity in [[Croatian Peasants' Party]]. Hence she was unable to finish her higher education, she was firstly employed in Jugovinil [[factory]]. Later she moved to [[Rijeka]], where thanks to her knowledge of [[Italian language]] Rendi\u0107 started working in the editorial committee of ''La Voce del Popolo'' newspaper. She also wrote for ''Pomorstvo'' (Seamanship) magazine until 1972, as well as reported for ''[[Glas Koncila]]''<ref> Vukovi\u0107, Tomislav: [https://www.glas-koncila.hr/sds-ov-dosje-o-nadbiskupu-viktoru-buricu-27-odbijen-prijedlog-da-se-diktatoru-krvavih-ruku-dodijeli-nobelova-nagrada/ SDS-ov DOSJE O (NAD)BISKUPU VIKTORU BURI\u0106U (27) Odbijen prijedlog da se diktatoru \u00bbkrvavih ruku\u00ab dodijeli Nobelova nagrada] ''[[Glas Koncila]]''. Published 27 February 2020. Access date 15 April 2020. </ref> and other Catholic periodicals under the guise of her [[pseudonym]]s Vjera Marini and Madam Berith.<ref name=ika> [https://ika.hkm.hr/novosti/umrla-smiljana-rendic/ Umrla Smiljana Rendi\u0107] [Smiljana Rendi\u0107 died] Informative Catholic Agency (IKA). Published 27 May 1994. Access date 15 April 2020. </ref> Rendi\u0107 also published her [[poem]]s (mostly [[sonnets]]<ref> Rendi\u0107, S., 1999: [https://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=113828 X. milost slova] ''Jezik: \u010dasopis za kulturu hrvatskoga knji\u017eevnog jezika'' '''47''' (4), 161-161. </ref>) in various periodicals.\n\nRendi\u0107 was sued by the Communist authorities for her article ''The genitive exit or the Second Croatian revival'' in ''Kritika'' magazine (no. 18) in 1971, in which she criticized Yugoslav integralism and \"linguistic colonisation\" of [[Croatian language]] (as partially stated in [[Declaration on the Name and Status of the Croatian Literary Language]]) and endorsed intellectual and academical requests of [[Croatian Spring]].<ref> [http://www.hkv.hr/vijesti/dokumenti/12768-smiljana-rendic-izlazak-iz-genitiva-ili-drugi-hrvatski-preporod.html Original text of the article] published by Croatian Culture Council on 13 May 2012. Access date 15 April 2020. </ref> Rendi\u0107's advocate was [[Milan Vukovi\u0107 (jurist)|Milan Vukovi\u0107]], who will later become president of the [[Supreme Court of Croatia]]. As a result of the [[show trial]] at the Supreme Court of SFRY in [[November]] [[1973]], Rendi\u0107 was forcibly retired and sentenced to one-year prison punishment, while ''Kritika'' magazine was censored.<ref name=bagdasarov/><ref name=ika/>\n\nShe was a member of the editorial committee of the ''Glas Koncila'' 1963-1994. For her's [[Bible study (Christianity)|biblistic]], [[Jewish studies|judaistic]] and journalist work, she was posthumously awarded by [[Croatian Bishops' Conference]] unique award ''Zlatno pero'' (\"Golden feather\") that wasn't given to anybody else except her.<ref name=ika/> \n\n== Works ==\n* [https://knjizara.glas-koncila.hr/katolicki-identitet-i-hrvatski-preporod.html ''Katoli\u010dki identitet i hrvatski preporod''] (Catholic identity and Croatian revival), Glas Koncila, Zagreb, 2012, ISBN 978-953-241-368-7.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rendi\u0107, Smiljana}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:1994 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Split, Croatia]]\n[[Category:Croatian journalists]]\n[[Category:Croatian translators]]\n[[Category:Croatian poets]]\n", "name_user": "Mudroslov", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWorks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smiljana_Rendi%C4%87"}
{"title_page": "Sambhaji", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Other uses|Sambhaji (disambiguation)}}{{weasel|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n|name        = Sambhaji\n|title       = [[Chhatrapati]] of the [[Maratha Empire]]\n|image       = Sambhaji painting late 17th century.png\n|caption     = A painting of Sambhaji, late 17th century\n|succession  = [[File:Flag of the Maratha Empire.svg|33x30px]] 2nd [[Chhatrapati]] of the [[Maratha Empire]]\n|reign       = 16 January 1681 \u2013 11 March 1689\n|coronation  = 20 July 1680, [[Panhala]]<br />or 16 January 1681, [[Raigad fort]]\n|predecessor = [[Shivaji|Shivaji I]]\n|successor   = [[Rajaram I]]\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=yes|1657|5|14}}\n|birth_place = [[Purandar Fort]], near [[Pune]], [[India]]\n|death_date  = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1689|3|11|1657|5|14}}\n|death_place = [[Tulapur]]-Vadhu Dist. [[Pune]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n|spouse      = Yesubai\n|issue       = Bhavani Bai <br /> [[Shahu I]]\n|father      = [[Shivaji|Shivaji I]]\n|mother      = [[Sai Bhosale|Saibai]]\n|religion    = [[Hinduism]]\n|royal house =[[Bhonsle]]\n}}\n\n'''Sambhaji Bhosale''' (14 May 1657 \u2013 11 March 1689) was the second ruler of the [[Maratha Empire|Maratha kingdom]]. He was the eldest son of [[Shivaji]], the founder of the Maratha Empire and his first wife [[Sai Bhosale|Saibai]]. He was successor of the realm after his father's death, and ruled it for nine years. Sambhaji's rule was largely shaped by the ongoing wars between the Maratha kingdom and [[Mughal Empire]] as well as other neighbouring powers such as the [[Siddi]]s, [[Mysore]] and the Portuguese in [[Goa]]. In 1689, Sambhaji was captured, tortured and executed by the Mughals, and succeeded by his brother [[Rajaram I]].<ref name=\"sen2\">{{Cite book |last=Sen |first=Sailendra |title=A Textbook of Medieval Indian History |publisher=Primus Books |year=2013 |isbn=978-9-38060-734-4 |pages=199\u2013200}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSambhaji was born at [[Purandar fort]] to [[Sai Bhosale|Saibai]], Shivaji's first wife. His mother died when he was two years old and he was raised by his paternal grandmother [[Jijabai]].<ref name=\"Joshi1980\" /> At the age of nine, Sambhaji was sent to live with Raja [[Jai Singh I]] of [[Aamer]] as a [[Hostage#Historical hostage practices|political hostage]] to ensure compliance of the [[Treaty of Purandar (1665)|Treaty of Purandar]] that Shivaji had signed with the Mughals on 11 June 1665.{{Citation needed|reason=|date=March 2018}} As a result of the treaty, Sambhaji became a Mughal [[mansabdar]].<ref name=\"books.google.com\">{{cite book|last1=Rana|first1=Bhawan Singh|title=Chhatrapati Shivaji|date=2004|publisher=Diamond Pocket Books|location=New Delhi|isbn=8128808265|page=64|edition= 1st|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=HsBPTc3hcekC&oi=fnd&pg=PA}}</ref> He and his father Shivaji presented themselves at Mughal emperor, [[Aurangzeb]]'s court at Agra on 12 May 1666. Aurangzeb put both of them under house arrest but they escaped on 22 July 1666.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gordon|first1=Stewart|title=The Marathas 1600\u20131818|date=1993|publisher=Cambridge University|location=New York|isbn=978-0-521-26883-7|pages=74\u201378|edition= 1st publ.|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=iHK-BhVXOU4C&oi=fnd&pg=PR9&dq=sambhaji+purandar+jaisingh+shivaji+treaty&ots=S0STQ4MCke&sig=GdCbVniN6jL1mZARbVJ_SYW_t0M#v=onepage&q=%20shivaji%20aurangzeb%20escape&f=false|accessdate=5 June 2016}}</ref> However, the two sides reconciled and had cordial relations during the period 1666\u20131670. In this period Shivaji and Sambhaji fought alongside the Mughals against the [[Sultanate of Bijapur]].<ref name=\"books.google.com\"/>\n\n===Marriage===\nSambhaji was married to Jivubai in a marriage of political alliance; per Maratha custom she took the name [[Yesubai]]. Jivubai was the daughter of Pilajirao Shirke, who had entered Shivaji's service following the defeat of a powerful [[deshmukh]] Rao Rana Suryajirao Surve who was his previous patron. This marriage thus gave Shivaji access to the [[Konkan]] coastal belt.<ref name=\"Mehta2005\">{{cite book|author=J. L. Mehta|title=Advanced Study in the History of Modern India: Volume One: 1707 \u2013 1813|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d1wUgKKzawoC&pg=PA47|page=47|accessdate=7 April 2016|date=1 January 2005|publisher=Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd|isbn=978-1-932705-54-6}}</ref>{{rp|4}}<ref name=\"Mehta2005\"/><ref name=\"Chhatrapati Shivaji\">{{cite book|last1=Rana|first1=Bhawan Singh|title=Chhatrapati Shivaji|date=2004|publisher=Diamond Pocket Books|location=New Delhi|isbn=81-288-0826-5|pages=96\u201399|edition= 1st|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=HsBPTc3hcekC&oi=fnd&pg=PA7&dq=sambhaji+shivaji+diler+khan&ots=A_SAEyx1_s&sig=Xx-HkByQ2fVpBjyMlrP8CRBGRxQ#v=snippet&q=sambhaji%20%20diler%20khan&f=false|accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref> Yesubai gave birth to a daughter named Bhavani Bai and then to a son named [[Shahu I|Shahu]].\n\n===House arrest and defection to the Mughals===\nSambhaji's behaviour, including alleged irresponsibility and addiction to sensual pleasures led Shivaji to imprison his son at Panhala fort in 1678 to curb his behaviour.<ref name=\"Mehta2005\"/><ref name=\"Sardesai1946\">{{cite book|author=Govind Sakharam Sardesai|title=New History of the Marathas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lTVuAAAAMAAJ|year=1946|publisher=Phoenix Publications|page=230}}</ref> Sambhaji escaped from the fort with his wife and defected to the Mughals in December 1678 for a year, but then returned home when he learnt of a plan by [[Dilir Khan]], the Mughal viceroy of Deccan to arrest him and send him to Delhi.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bhave|first1=Y.G.|title=From the death of Shivaji to the death of Aurangzeb : the critical years|date=2000|publisher=Northern Book Centre|location=New Delhi|isbn=81-7211100-2|page=35|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=Q5kVk6msxUcC&oi=fnd&pg=PR7&dq=shivaji+sambhaji+panhala+&ots=lLqy86rM34&sig=u7SAV_MadAvMeefJcQ-LXS4uqoM#v=onepage&q=sambhaji%20khan&f=false}}</ref> Upon returning home, Sambhaji was unrepentant and was put under surveillance at [[Panhala]].<ref name=\"Mehta2005\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Gordon|first1=Stewart|title=The Marathas 1600\u20131818|date=1993|publisher=Cambridge University|location=New York|isbn=978-0-521-26883-7|page=80|edition= 1. publ.|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=iHK-BhVXOU4C&oi=fnd&pg=PR9&dq=sambhaji+purandar+jaisingh+shivaji+treaty&ots=S0STQ4MCke&sig=GdCbVniN6jL1mZARbVJ_SYW_t0M#v=onepage&q=%20shivaji%20aurangzeb%20escape&f=false|accessdate=5 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Accession==\n[[File:Sambhaji &amp; Kubkullus.jpg|thumb|Sambhaji &amp; Kubkullus]]\nWhen Shivaji died on the 3rd April 1680, Sambhaji was still managing the surrounding region from the Panhala fort<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Sawant|first=Shivaji|title=Chhava|publisher=Continental Publishers|year=|isbn=|location=Pune|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Jadhav|first=Namdevrao|title=Khara Sambhaji|publisher=Rajamata Prakashan|year=2014|isbn=978-8191098037|location=Pune|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Sawant|first=Indrajit|title=Marathyanche Swatantrayuddha Bhag 1- Chhatrapati Sambhaji Maharaj|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>. Some of the influential sardars including ministers [[Annaji Datto Sachiv|Annaji Datto]] and other ministers conspired against Sambhaji, supported by Soyarabai, to prevent Sambhaji from succeeding the throne.<ref name=\"Mehta2005\"/>{{rp|48}} Shivaji's widow and Sambhaji's stepmother, [[Soyrabai]] after her husband's death installed the couple's son, Rajaram, a lad of 10, on the throne on 21 April 1680.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gordon|first1=Stewart|title=The Marathas 1600\u20131818|date=1993|publisher=Cambridge University|location=New York|isbn=978-0-521-26883-7|pages=91|edition= 1st publ.|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=iHK-BhVXOU4C&oi=fnd&pg=PR9&dq=sambhaji+purandar+jaisingh+shivaji+treaty&ots=S0STQ4MCke&sig=GdCbVniN6jL1mZARbVJ_SYW_t0M#v=onepage&q=%20shivaji%20aurangzeb%20escape&f=false|accessdate=5 June 2016}}</ref> News of Shivaji's death was purposefully hidden from Sambhaji by the conspirators. Upon hearing this news, Sambhaji started his preparations and took possession of the Panhala fort. He arrested the fort commander Vitthal Tryambak and senior minister Janardanpant Hanumante who were involved in the conspiracy. He also asked his father-in-law of Pilajirao Shirke to be ready with his forces at Shringarpur. Both sides were vying for the crucial support of [[Hambirrao Mohite]] the commander-in-chief of Maratha army. He was the brother of [[Soyarabai]] and the maternal uncle of \ufffc[[Rajaram I|Rajaram]]\ufffc\ufffc.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Soyarabai issued orders to [[Annaji Datto Sachiv|Anaji Datto]] and [[Moropant Trimbak Pingle|Moropant]] to leave Raigad with a force of 5,000 to arrest Sambhaji at Panhala. Hambirrao was near [[Karad]] with his army of 20,000. Anaji and Moropant came to meet Hambirrao and asked for his support to arrest Sambhaji. Hambirrao refused and arrested both these ministers. On the next day Hambirrao along with his senior generals Rupaji Bhosle and Anandrao Makaji met Sambhaji at Panhala. Sambhaji was delighted at the arrival of Hambirrao on his side<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|last=Patil|first=Vishwas|title=Sambhaji|publisher=Mehta Publishing House|year=2016|isbn=9788177666519|location=Pune|pages=196-208}}</ref> . Sambhaji held a ceremony at Panhala to acknowledge Hambirrao's support. He stayed at Panhala for some time as condolence letters were coming to him from British, Portuguese, Dutch, French, Adilshahi, Qutbshahi and other neighbouring powers after Shivaji's death. Meanwhile he asked Pilajirao to secure Raigad with a force of 10,000. He was confronted by sardar Malsawant of Soyarabai's side but Pilajirao defeated and arrested him and secured the control of Raigad [[Raigad Fort|fort]]. Sambhaji formally ascended the throne on 20 July 1680. Rajaram, his wife mother [[Soyarabai]], all the senior ministers involved in the conspiracy were put under house arrest. Malsawant still kept on insulting Sambhaji and he was executed by throwing him off the cliff.(Takmak Tok cliff). Sambhaji's coronation took place of 16th January 1681. Sambhaji pardoned and restored all the ministers such as [[Janardanpant]], [[Hiroji Farzand]], Rahuji Somnath in their previously held positions. Peshwa Moropant had died meanwhile, his position was given to his son Nilopant Pingale. [[Annaji Datto Sachiv|Anaji Datto]] was also pardoned but he was transferred to Mujumdar and his former post of Suranvis was given to [[Abaji Sondev]] <ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" />. In 1681 Aurangzeb's rebel son Akbar along with Rajput chieftain Durgadas Rathore had arrived in Maharashtra to seek help against his father. Sambhaji had appointed Hiroji Farzand to negotiate with Akbar and Durgadas Rathore. The conspirators tried lure Akbar to their side to dethrone Sambhaji. They offered him half of the Maratha kingdom in return for his support to dethrone Sambhaji. The conspirators also tried to poison Sambhaji but the attempt failed. Akbar did not pay heed to their offer and instead informed Sambhaji about this conspiracy. Sambhaji quickly marched to [[Ballaleshwar Pali|Pali]] and arrested the conspirators near Sudhagad fort at Pali. Senior ministers Anaji Datto, Hiroji Farzand, Balaji Awji, Somaji Datto, Awji Balaji and others were arrested. Sambhaji had pardoned them before and they still conspired to poison him. Sambhaji gave the order to execute the traitors by trampling them under elephant. Some of Shivaji's ministers such as Annaji Datto, Hiroji Farzand and other conspirators were executed on charges of conspiracy and treason.<ref name=\"Mehta2005\"/>{{rp|48}}<ref name=\"SharmaL\u0101\u02bcibrer\u012b2004\">{{cite book|author1=Sunita Sharma|author2=K\u0332h\u0332ud\u0101 Bak\u0332h\u0332sh Oriyan\u1e6dal Pablik L\u0101\u02bcibrer\u012b|title=Veil, sceptre, and quill: profiles of eminent women, 16th- 18th centuries|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q2kaAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=30 September 2012|year=2004|publisher=Khuda Bakhsh Oriental Public Library|page=139}} \u2013 ''By June 1680 three months after Shivaji's death Rajaram was made a prisoner in the fort of [[Raigad Fort|Raigad]].\"</ref> Sambhaji arrived at Raigad and put Soyarabai and Rajaram under house arrest. Soyarabai was guilty for her actions and commited suicide by poisoning herself. Sambhaji was very sad at the demise of Soyarabai which is evident from the letter sent by him to Bakre Shastri of Kudal wherein he mentions that 'Soyarabai had a pure heart'. Sambhaji also felt very sad for the death of Balaji Awji Chitnis in the process and built a temple in the memory of [[Balaji Awji Chitnis]] at Pali. <ref name=\":3\" /> <ref name=\":2\" /> <ref name=\":1\" /> <ref name=\":4\" />. \n\n==Military expeditions and conflicts==\nShortly following Sambhaji's accession, he began his military campaigns against neighboring states. Historians have been quick to note the distinction between the more tolerant and chivalrous practices of his father Shivaji, and the more pragmatic and brutal practices of Sambhaji. \n\n===Attack on Burhanpur===\nThe fort of Burhanpur was first in the charge of Bahadur khan who later gave it to Kakar Khan. Kakar was at the duty of collecting [[Jizya]] tax from the citizens. In order to accomplish the task, Kakar Khan destroyed more than 100 temples surrounding Burhanpur and conducting torture, plunder, killing, cutting of women's ears and men's eyes for the wealth. The Jizya was collected and stored captive at the Burhanpur fort.<ref>{|url=  http://informatonaboutsambhajiraje.blogspot.com/2016/10/maratha-yodhha-early-life-sambhaji-was.html?m=1}</ref>.Sambhaji plundered and ravaged [[Burhanpur]] in 1680. His forces completely routed the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] garrison and punitively executed captives. The Marathas then looted the city and set its ports ablaze. Sambhaji then withdrew into [[Baglana]], evading the forces of Mughal commander Khan Jahan Bahadur Kokaltash.<ref>{{cite book|first=John F. |last=Richard |authorlink=John F. Richards |title=The Mughal Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HHyVh29gy4QC|accessdate=1 October 2012|date=26 January 1996|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-56603-2|page=218}}</ref> During the attack on Burhanpur, among his 20,000 troops, many of them perpetrated atrocities against Muslims, including plunder, killing, and torture.<ref name=\"richards\">{{cite book|title=The Mughal Empire|author=[[John F. Richards]]|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year=1995|pages=217\u2013223}}</ref>\n\n===Mughal Empire===\nIn 1681, Aurangzeb's fourth son [[Sultan Muhammad Akbar|Akbar]] left the Mughal court along with a few Muslim Mansabdar supporters and joined Muslim rebels in the Deccan. He was accompanied by rajput chieftain [[Durgadas Rathore]] of Marwar.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Patil|first=Vishwas|title=Sambhaji|publisher=Mehta Publishing house|year=2016|isbn=|location=Pune|pages=}}</ref> Aurangzeb in response moved his court south to [[Aurangabad, Maharashtra|Aurangabad]] and took over command of the Deccan campaign.The rebels were defeated and Akbar fled south to seek refuge with Sambhaji. Sambhaji's ministers including Annaji Datto, and other ministers took this opportunity and conspired again to enthrone Rajaram again. They signed a treasonable letter against Sambhaji in which they promised to join Akbar, to whom the letter was sent.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Eh1BAAAAMAAJ&q=annaji+datto+conspire+sambhaji&dq=annaji+datto+conspire+sambhaji&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiFl57A8KnaAhWIM48KHYM1C9sQ6AEIPTAF|title=Maharani Tarabai of Kolhapur, c. 1675-1761 A.D.|last=P\u0101\u1e6d\u012bla|first=\u015a\u0101lin\u012b|date=1987|publisher=S. Chand & Co.|isbn=9788121902694|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=43gBAAAAMAAJ&q=annaji+datto+conspire+sambhaji&dq=annaji+datto+conspire+sambhaji&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiFl57A8KnaAhWIM48KHYM1C9sQ6AEIJzAA|title=Chhatrapati Sambhaji|last=Gokhale|first=Kamal Shrikrishna|date=1978|publisher=Navakamal Publications|language=en}}</ref> Akbar gave this letter to Sambhaji.<ref name=\":0\" /> Enraged Sambhaji executed conspirators on charges of treason.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=43gBAAAAMAAJ&q=sambhaji+conspirators+execute&dq=sambhaji+conspirators+execute&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiZ3oS_9qnaAhVCwI8KHavMDjkQ6AEIKzAB|title=Chhatrapati Sambhaji|last=Gokhale|first=Kamal Shrikrishna|date=1978|publisher=Navakamal Publications|language=en}}</ref>\n\nFor fully five years, Akbar stayed with Sambhaji, hoping that the latter would lend him men and money to strike and seize the Mughal throne for himself. Unfortunately for Sambhaji, giving asylum to Akbar did not bear fruit. Eventually, Sambhaji helped Akbar flee to [[Persia]]. On the other hand, Aurangzeb after coming to Deccan never returned to his capital in the north.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Great Moghuls |first1=Bamber |last1=Gascoigne |first2=Christina |last2=Gascoigne |authorlink1=Bamber Gascoigne |publisher=Cape |year=1971 |pages=228\u2013229 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-ryFAAAAIAAJ}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Kulkarni|first1=A.R.|title=The Marathas|date=2008|publisher=Diamond Publications|location=Pune|isbn=9788184830736|edition= 1st|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N45LDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\nIn 1682, the Mughals laid siege to the Maratha fort of [[Ramsej]], but after five months of failed attempts, including planting explosive mines and building wooden towers to gain the walls, the Mughal siege failed.<ref>{{cite book|title=Itihas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MApDAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=3 August 2013|year=1976|publisher=Director of State Archives, Government of Andhra Pradesh.|pages=100\u2013103}}</ref>\n\n===Siddis of Janjira===\nThe Marathas under Shivaji came into conflict with the [[Siddi]]s, Muslims of [[Abyssinian people|Abyssinian]] descent settled in India, over the control of the Konkan coast. Shivaji was able to reduce their presence to the fortified island of [[Janjira State|Janjira]]. Sambhaji continued the Maratha campaign against them, while at that time the Siddis formed an alliance with the Mughals.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kumar|first1=Amarendra|title=KEIGWIN'S BOMBAY (1683-84) AND THE MARATHA-SIDDI NAVAL CONFLICT|journal=Proceedings of the Indian History Congress|date=2014|volume=75|pages=320\u2013324|jstor=44158397}}</ref> At the start of 1682, a Maratha army later joined by Sambhaji personally, attacked the island for thirty days, doing heavy damage but failing to breach its defenses. Sambhaji then attempted a ruse, sending a party of his people to the Siddis, claiming to be defectors. They were allowed into the fort and planned to detonate the [[gunpowder magazine]] during a coming Maratha attack. However, one of the female defectors became involved with a Siddi man and he uncovered the plot, and the infiltrators were executed. The Maratha then attempted to build a stone [[causeway]] from the shore to the island, but were interrupted halfway through when the Mughal army moved to menace Raigad. Sambhaji returned to counter them and his remaining troops were unable to overcome the Janjira garrison and the Siddi fleet protecting it.<ref name=\"Ali1996\">{{cite book|author=Shanti Sadiq Ali|title=The African Dispersal in the Deccan: From Medieval to Modern Times|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-3CPc22nMqIC&pg=PA171|accessdate=1 October 2012|date=1 January 1996|publisher=Orient Blackswan|isbn=978-81-250-0485-1|pages=171\u2013}}</ref>\n\n===Portuguese and English===\n[[Image:Chh. Sambhaji's WatanPatra.jpg|thumb|WatanPatra, grant document, by Chh. Sambhaji]]\nHaving failed to take Janjira in 1682, Sambhaji sent a commander to seize the Portuguese coastal fort of [[Anjediva Island|Anjadiva]] instead. The Marathas seized the fort, seeking to turn it into a naval base, but in April 1682 were ejected from the fort by a detachment of 200 Portuguese. This incident led to a larger conflict between the two regional powers.<ref name=\"Ali1996\"/>{{rp|171}}\n\nThe [[History of Goa#Portuguese conquest and colonisation|Portuguese colony of Goa]] at that time provided supplies to the Mughals, allowed them to use the Portuguese ports in India and pass through their territory. In order to deny this support to the Mughals, Sambhaji undertook a campaign against Portuguese Goa in late 1683, storming the colony and taking its forts.<ref name=\"Ames2000\">{{cite book|author=Glenn Joseph Ames|title=Renascent Empire?: The House of Braganza and the Quest for Stability in Portuguese Monsoon Asia c. 1640\u20131683|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MfMNfsOMUHwC&pg=PA155|year=2000|publisher=Amsterdam University Press|isbn=978-90-5356-382-3|pages=155\u2013}}</ref> The situation for the colonists became so dire that the Portuguese viceroy, [[Francisco de T\u00e1vora, conde de Alvor]] went with his remaining supporters to the cathedral where the crypt of [[Francis Xavier|Saint Francis Xavier]] was kept, where they prayed for deliverance. The viceroy had the casket opened and gave the saint's body his baton, royal credentials and a letter asking the saint's support. Sambhaji's Goa campaign was checked by the arrival of the Mughal army and navy in January 1684, forcing him to withdraw.<ref name=\"Alden1996\">{{cite book|author=Dauril Alden|title=The Making of an Enterprise: The Society of Jesus in Portugal, Its Empire, and Beyond, 1540\u20131750|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7nVIBhrRb9AC&pg=PA202|accessdate=2 October 2012|date=1 September 1996|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-2271-1|pages=202\u2013}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, in 1684 Sambhaji signed a defensive treaty with the English at Bombay, realising his need for English arms and gunpowder, particularly as their lack of artillery and explosives impeded the Maratha's ability to lay siege to fortifications. Thus reinforced, Sambhaji proceeded to take [[Pratapgad]] and a series of forts along the [[Ghats]].<ref name=\"Gordon1993\">{{cite book|author=Stewart Gordon|title=The Marathas 1600\u20131818|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iHK-BhVXOU4C&pg=PA91|accessdate=2 October 2012|date=16 September 1993|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-26883-7|pages=91\u2013}}</ref>{{rp|91}}\n\n===Mysore===\nMuch like his father Shivaji's Karnataka campaign, Sambhaji attempted in 1681 to invade [[Mysore]], then a southern principality ruled by [[Wodeyar]] [[Chikkadevaraja]]. Sambhaji's large army was repelled,<ref name=\"Gordon1993\"/>{{rp|91}} as had happened to Shivaji in 1675.<ref name=\"Chopra1992\">{{cite book|author=Pran Nath Chopra|title=Encyclopaedia of India: Karnataka|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PfNtAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2 October 2012|year=1992|publisher=Rima Pub. House}}</ref> The Chikkadevraja later made treaties and rendered tribute to the Maratha kingdom during the conflicts of 1682\u20131686. The Chikkadevraja however began to draw close to the Mughal empire and ceased to follow his treaties with the Marathas. In response, Sambhaji invaded Mysore in 1686, accompanied by his Brahmin friend and poet [[Kavi Kalash]].<ref name=\"Muddhachari1969\">{{cite book|author=B. Muddhachari|title=The Mysore-Maratha relations in the 17th century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w1PRAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2 October 2012|year=1969|publisher=Pras\u0101r\u0101nga, University of Mysore|page=106}}</ref><ref name=\"SatyanarayanaMuseums1996\">{{cite book|author1=A. Satyanarayana|author2=Karnataka (India). Directorate of Archaeology & Museums|title=History of the Wodeyars of Mysore, 1610\u20131748|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3jduAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2 October 2012|year=1996|publisher=Directorate of Archaeology and Museums|page=94}}</ref>\n\n==Capture and execution==\n[[Image:Tulapur arch.jpg|thumb|Stone arch at [[Tulapur]] confluence where Sambhaji was executed]]\n[[File:Vadhu Tulapur - Statue of Sambhaji Maharaja.JPG|thumb|upright|Statue of Sambhaji at Tulapur]]\nThe 1687 [[Battle of Wai]] saw the Maratha forces badly weakened by the Mughals. The key Maratha commander [[Hambirao Mohite]] was killed and troops began to desert the Maratha armies. Sambhaji's positions were spied upon by his own relations, the Shirke family, who had defected to the Mughals. Sambhaji and 25 of his advisors were captured by the Mughal forces of [[Muqarrab Khan]] in a skirmish at [[Sangameshwar]] in February 1689.<ref name=\"Mehta2005\"/>{{rp|47}}\n\nAccounts of Sambhaji's confrontation with the Mughal ruler and following torture, execution and disposal of his body, vary widely depending on the source, though generally all agree that he was tortured and executed on the emperor's orders.<ref name=\"Mehta2005\"/>{{rp|50}}\n\nThe captured Sambhaji and [[Kavi Kalash]] were taken to [[Pedgaon, Ahmednagar|Bahadurgad]] in present-day Ahmednagar district, where Aurangzeb humiliated them by parading them wearing clown's clothes and they were subjected to insults by Mughal soldiers. Accounts vary as to the reasons for what came next: Mughal accounts state that Sambhaji was asked to surrender his forts, treasures and names of Mughal collaborators with the Marathas and that he sealed his fate by insulting both the emperor and the Islamic prophet Muhammad during interrogation and was executed for having killed Muslims.<ref>{{cite book|first=John F. |last=Richards |authorlink=John F. Richards|title=The Mughal Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HHyVh29gy4QC|accessdate=29 September 2012|date=26 January 1996|publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-56603-2 |page=223}}</ref> The [[ulema]] of the Mughal Empire sentenced Sambhaji to death for the atrocities his troops perpetrated against Muslims in Burhanpur, including plunder, killing, rape, and torture.<ref name=\"richards\"/>\n\nMaratha accounts instead state that he was ordered to bow before Aurangzeb and convert to Islam and it was his refusal to do so, by saying that he would accept Islam on the day the emperor presented him his daughter's hand, that led to his death.<ref name=\"SBBhattacherje2009\">{{cite book | author=S. B. Bhattacherje | title=Encyclopaedia of Indian Events & Dates | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oGVSvXuCsyUC&pg=SL1-PA81 | accessdate=6 March 2012 | date=1 May 2009 | publisher=Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd | isbn=978-81-207-4074-7 | pages = A80-A81 }}</ref> By doing so he earned the title of ''Dharmaveer'' (\"protector of [[dharma]]\").<ref name=\"Bhave2000\">{{cite book|author=Y. G. Bhave|title=From the Death of Shivaji to the Death of Aurangzeb: The Critical Years|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q5kVk6msxUcC&pg=PA60|accessdate=2 October 2012|date=1 January 2000|publisher=Northern Book Centre|isbn=978-81-7211-100-7|pages=60\u2013}}</ref> Aurangzeb ordered Sambhaji and Kavi Kalash to be tortured to death; the process took over a fortnight and included plucking out their eyes and tongue, pulling out their nails and removing their skin. Sambhaji was finally killed on 11 March 1689,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/in.ernet.dli.2015.48871/2015.48871.Maasir---I---Alamgiri#page/n205/mode/2up/search/quli|title=Maasir \u2013 I \u2013 Alamgiri|website=archive.org|access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref> reportedly by tearing him apart from the front and back with [[wagh nakhe]] (metal \"tiger claws\") and beheading with an axe at [[Tulapur]] on the banks of the [[Bhima river]] near Pune.<ref name=\"Mehta2005\"/>{{rp|50}}\n\nOther accounts state that Sambhaji challenged Aurangzeb in open court and refused to convert to Islam. Dennis Kincaid writes, \"He (Sambhaji) was ordered by the Emperor to embrace Islam. He refused and was made to run the gauntlet of the whole Imperial army. Tattered and bleeding he was brought before the Emperor and repeated his refusal. His tongue was torn and again the question was put. He called for writing material and wrote 'Not even if the emperor bribed me with his daughter!' So then he was put to death by torture\".<ref name=\"Bhave2000\"/>\n\nSome accounts state that Sambhaji's body was cut into pieces and thrown into the river or that the body or portions were recaptured and cremated at the confluence of rivers at Tulapur.<ref name=\"Gokhale1978\">{{cite book|author=Kamal Shrikrishna Gokhale|title=Chhatrapati Sambhaji|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=43gBAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2 October 2012|year=1978|publisher=Navakamal Publications|page=365}}</ref><ref name=\"Organiser\">{{cite book|title=Organiser|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dk8_AQAAIAAJ|accessdate=2 October 2012|date=January 1973|publisher=Bharat Prakashan.|page=280}} \u2013 ''When they were finally thrown away, the Marathas brought Sambhaji's head to Tulapur and consigned if to fire at the confluence of the Bheema and Indrayani rivers.''</ref> Other accounts state that Sambhaji's remains were fed to the dogs.<ref>{{cite book|author=J. L. Mehta|title=Advanced Study in the History of Modern India: Volume One: 1707 \u2013 1813|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d1wUgKKzawoC&pg=PA50|accessdate=7 April 2016|date=1 January 2005|publisher=Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd|isbn=978-1-932705-54-6|page=50}}</ref>\n\n== Literary contributions ==\nSambhaji was sophisticated, educated and well-versed in a few languages other than Marathi. [[Keshav Pandit]] was employed for Sambhaji's education. Keshav Pandit, alias Keshav Bhatta of Shringarpur, was an erudite scholar in the Nitishastra and Sanskrit language and literature. He seems to have deeper knowledge of the different forms of Sanskrit literature; Hindu jurisprudence and the Puranas. He also seems to have made Sambhaji familiar with the famous works of different sciences and music written by ancient scholars in the Sanskrit language.<ref name=\"Joshi1980\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9ngBAAAAMAAJ&q=Keshav+Pandit+Sambhaji&dq=Keshav+Pandit+Sambhaji&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4nJWctqfaAhXMPo8KHa3gDC8Q6AEIJzAA|title=Chhatrapati Sambhaji, 1657\u20131689 A.D.|last=Joshi|first=Pandit Shankar|date=1980|publisher=S. Chand|language=en |pages=4\u20135}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/BudhabhushanamOfShambhurajaHDVelankarBORI1926/Budhabhushanam%20of%20Shambhuraja%20-%20HD%20Velankar%20-%20BORI%201926#page/n11/mode/2up|title=Budhabhushanam Of Shambhuraja HD Velankar BORI 1926|website=archive.org|access-date=7 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nThere are several books by Sambhaji. The most notable is ''Budhbhushanam''  which is in Sanskrit and three other known books ''Nayikabhed'', ''Saatsatak'', ''Nakhshikha'' are in Hindi language.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/BudhabhushanamOfShambhurajaHDVelankarBORI1926/Budhabhushanam%20of%20Shambhuraja%20-%20HD%20Velankar%20-%20BORI%201926#page/n13/mode/2up|title=Budhabhushanam Of Shambhuraja HD Velankar BORI 1926|website=archive.org|access-date=7 April 2018}}</ref> In ''Budhbhushanam'', Sambhaji wrote poetry on politics. In the book Sambhaji writes about dos and don'ts for a king and discusses military tactics. The first few ''[[sloka meter|slokas]]'' are praises for Shahaji (his grandfather) and his father Shivaji. In ''Budhbhushan'' Sambhaji considers Shivaji to be the incarnation that saved the earth and restored righteousness.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/BudhabhushanamOfShambhurajaHDVelankarBORI1926/Budhabhushanam%20of%20Shambhuraja%20-%20HD%20Velankar%20-%20BORI%201926#page/n15/mode/2up|title=Budhabhushanam Of Shambhuraja HD Velankar BORI 1926|website=archive.org|access-date=7 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Succession==\nThe Maratha Kingdom was put into disarray by Sambhaji's death and his younger [[half-brother]] [[Rajaram Chhatrapati]] assumed the throne. Rajaram shifted the Maratha capital far south to [[Gingee|Jinji]], while Maratha guerrilla fighters under [[Santaji Ghorpade]] and [[Dhanaji Jadhav]] continued to harass the Mughal army. A few days after Sambhaji's death, the capital [[Raigad Fort]] fell to the Mughals. Sambhaji's widow, Yesubai, son, [[Chhattrapati Shahu|Shahu]] and Shivaji's widow, [[Sakvarbai]]  were captured; Sakvarbai died in Mughal captivity.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Mehta|first1=J. L.|title=Advanced study in the history of modern India, 1707\u20131813|date=2005|publisher=New Dawn Press, Inc.|location=Slough|isbn=9781932705546|page=47}}</ref> Shahu, who was seven years of age when captured, remained prisoner of the Mughals for 18 years from February 1689 until Mughal Emperor [[Aurangzeb]]'s death in 1707. Shahu was then set free by Emperor [[Muhammad Azam Shah]], son of Aurangzeb. After his release Shahu had to fight a brief war with his aunt [[Tarabai]], Rajaram's widow who claimed the throne for her own son, Shivaji II.<ref>{{citation | first = Malgonkar |last = Manohar | title = The Sea Hawk: Life and Battles of Kanoji Angrey | year = 1959 | page = 63}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=A. Vijaya Kumari |author2=Sepuri Bhaskar |title=Social change among Balijas: majority community of Andhra Pradesh|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r-ffeWmj2JUC&pg=PA6 |publisher=MD |accessdate=24 June 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"sen4\">{{Cite book |last=Sen |first=Sailendra |title=A Textbook of Medieval Indian History |publisher=Primus Books |year=2013 |isbn=978-93-80607-34-4 |pages=201\u2013202}}</ref> The Mughals kept Yesubai captive to ensure that Shahu adhered to the terms of his release. She was released in 1719 when Marathas became strong enough under Shahu and Peshwa [[Balaji Vishwanath]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Quarterly Review of Historical Studies|url=https://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13121|year=1971|publisher=Institute of Historical Studies.}}</ref>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{Succession box|\n before=[[Shivaji]] |\n title=[[Chhatrapati]] of the<br /> [[Maratha Empire]] |\n years=1680\u20131689 |\n after=[[Rajaram Chhatrapati|Rajaram]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bhosale|Bhosale family ancestry]]\n*[[Maratha clan system]]\n*[[Marathi people]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n<nowiki/>{{Commons category}}\n\n{{MarathaEmpire}}\n{{Shivaji}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1657 births]]\n[[Category:1689 deaths]]\n[[Category:17th-century Indian monarchs]]\n[[Category:Executed Indian people]]\n[[Category:Hindu martyrs]]\n[[Category:Hindu monarchs]]\n[[Category:Marathi people]]\n[[Category:People executed by India by decapitation]]\n[[Category:People executed by the Mughal Empire]]\n[[Category:People from Maharashtra]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Other uses|Sambhaji (disambiguation)}}{{weasel|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n|name        = Sambhaji\n|title       = [[Chhatrapati]] of the [[Maratha Empire]]\n|image       = Sambhaji painting late 17th century.png\n|caption     = A painting of Sambhaji, late 17th century\n|succession  = [[File:Flag of the Maratha Empire.svg|33x30px]] 2nd [[Chhatrapati]] of the [[Maratha Empire]]\n|reign       = 16 January 1681 \u2013 11 March 1689\n|coronation  = 20 July 1680, [[Panhala]]<br />or 16 January 1681, [[Raigad fort]]\n|predecessor = [[Shivaji|Shivaji I]]\n|successor   = [[Rajaram I]]\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=yes|1657|5|14}}\n|birth_place = [[Purandar Fort]], near [[Pune]], [[India]]\n|death_date  = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1689|3|11|1657|5|14}}\n|death_place = [[Tulapur]]-Vadhu Dist. [[Pune]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n|spouse      = Yesubai\n|issue       = Bhavani Bai <br /> [[Shahu I]]\n|father      = [[Shivaji|Shivaji I]]\n|mother      = [[Sai Bhosale|Saibai]]\n|religion    = [[Hinduism]]\n|royal house =[[Bhonsle]]\n}}\n\n'''Sambhaji Bhosale''' (14 May 1657 \u2013 11 March 1689) was the second ruler of the [[Maratha Empire|Maratha kingdom]]. He was the eldest son of [[Shivaji]], the founder of the Maratha Empire and his first wife [[Sai Bhosale|Saibai]]. He was successor of the realm after his father's death, and ruled it for nine years. Sambhaji's rule was largely shaped by the ongoing wars between the Maratha kingdom and [[Mughal Empire]] as well as other neighbouring powers such as the [[Siddi]]s, [[Mysore]] and the Portuguese in [[Goa]]. In 1689, Sambhaji was captured, tortured and executed by the Mughals, and succeeded by his brother [[Rajaram I]].<ref name=\"sen2\">{{Cite book |last=Sen |first=Sailendra |title=A Textbook of Medieval Indian History |publisher=Primus Books |year=2013 |isbn=978-9-38060-734-4 |pages=199\u2013200}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSambhaji was born at [[Purandar fort]] to [[Sai Bhosale|Saibai]], Shivaji's first wife. His mother died when he was two years old and he was raised by his paternal grandmother [[Jijabai]].<ref name=\"Joshi1980\" /> At the age of nine, Sambhaji was sent to live with Raja [[Jai Singh I]] of [[Aamer]] as a [[Hostage#Historical hostage practices|political hostage]] to ensure compliance of the [[Treaty of Purandar (1665)|Treaty of Purandar]] that Shivaji had signed with the Mughals on 11 June 1665.{{Citation needed|reason=|date=March 2018}} As a result of the treaty, Sambhaji became a Mughal [[mansabdar]].<ref name=\"books.google.com\">{{cite book|last1=Rana|first1=Bhawan Singh|title=Chhatrapati Shivaji|date=2004|publisher=Diamond Pocket Books|location=New Delhi|isbn=8128808265|page=64|edition= 1st|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=HsBPTc3hcekC&oi=fnd&pg=PA}}</ref> He and his father Shivaji presented themselves at Mughal emperor, [[Aurangzeb]]'s court at Agra on 12 May 1666. Aurangzeb put both of them under house arrest but they escaped on 22 July 1666.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gordon|first1=Stewart|title=The Marathas 1600\u20131818|date=1993|publisher=Cambridge University|location=New York|isbn=978-0-521-26883-7|pages=74\u201378|edition= 1st publ.|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=iHK-BhVXOU4C&oi=fnd&pg=PR9&dq=sambhaji+purandar+jaisingh+shivaji+treaty&ots=S0STQ4MCke&sig=GdCbVniN6jL1mZARbVJ_SYW_t0M#v=onepage&q=%20shivaji%20aurangzeb%20escape&f=false|accessdate=5 June 2016}}</ref> However, the two sides reconciled and had cordial relations during the period 1666\u20131670. In this period Shivaji and Sambhaji fought alongside the Mughals against the [[Sultanate of Bijapur]].<ref name=\"books.google.com\"/>\n\n===Marriage===\nSambhaji was married to Jivubai in a marriage of political alliance; per Maratha custom she took the name [[Yesubai]]. Jivubai was the daughter of Pilajirao Shirke, who had entered Shivaji's service following the defeat of a powerful [[deshmukh]] Rao Rana Suryajirao Surve who was his previous patron. This marriage thus gave Shivaji access to the [[Konkan]] coastal belt.<ref name=\"Mehta2005\">{{cite book|author=J. L. Mehta|title=Advanced Study in the History of Modern India: Volume One: 1707 \u2013 1813|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d1wUgKKzawoC&pg=PA47|page=47|accessdate=7 April 2016|date=1 January 2005|publisher=Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd|isbn=978-1-932705-54-6}}</ref>{{rp|4}}<ref name=\"Mehta2005\"/><ref name=\"Chhatrapati Shivaji\">{{cite book|last1=Rana|first1=Bhawan Singh|title=Chhatrapati Shivaji|date=2004|publisher=Diamond Pocket Books|location=New Delhi|isbn=81-288-0826-5|pages=96\u201399|edition= 1st|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=HsBPTc3hcekC&oi=fnd&pg=PA7&dq=sambhaji+shivaji+diler+khan&ots=A_SAEyx1_s&sig=Xx-HkByQ2fVpBjyMlrP8CRBGRxQ#v=snippet&q=sambhaji%20%20diler%20khan&f=false|accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref> Yesubai gave birth to a daughter named Bhavani Bai and then to a son named [[Shahu I|Shahu]].\n\n===House arrest and defection to the Mughals===\nSambhaji's behaviour, including alleged irresponsibility and addiction to sensual pleasures led Shivaji to imprison his son at Panhala fort in 1678 to curb his behaviour.<ref name=\"Mehta2005\"/><ref name=\"Sardesai1946\">{{cite book|author=Govind Sakharam Sardesai|title=New History of the Marathas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lTVuAAAAMAAJ|year=1946|publisher=Phoenix Publications|page=230}}</ref> Sambhaji escaped from the fort with his wife and defected to the Mughals in December 1678 for a year, but then returned home when he learnt of a plan by [[Dilir Khan]], the Mughal viceroy of Deccan to arrest him and send him to Delhi.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bhave|first1=Y.G.|title=From the death of Shivaji to the death of Aurangzeb : the critical years|date=2000|publisher=Northern Book Centre|location=New Delhi|isbn=81-7211100-2|page=35|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=Q5kVk6msxUcC&oi=fnd&pg=PR7&dq=shivaji+sambhaji+panhala+&ots=lLqy86rM34&sig=u7SAV_MadAvMeefJcQ-LXS4uqoM#v=onepage&q=sambhaji%20khan&f=false}}</ref> Upon returning home, Sambhaji was unrepentant and was put under surveillance at [[Panhala]].<ref name=\"Mehta2005\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Gordon|first1=Stewart|title=The Marathas 1600\u20131818|date=1993|publisher=Cambridge University|location=New York|isbn=978-0-521-26883-7|page=80|edition= 1. publ.|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=iHK-BhVXOU4C&oi=fnd&pg=PR9&dq=sambhaji+purandar+jaisingh+shivaji+treaty&ots=S0STQ4MCke&sig=GdCbVniN6jL1mZARbVJ_SYW_t0M#v=onepage&q=%20shivaji%20aurangzeb%20escape&f=false|accessdate=5 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Accession==\n[[File:Sambhaji &amp; Kubkullus.jpg|thumb|Sambhaji &amp; Kubkullus]]\nWhen Shivaji died on the 3rd April 1680, Sambhaji was still managing the surrounding region from the Panhala fort<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Sawant|first=Shivaji|title=Chhava|publisher=Continental Publishers|year=|isbn=|location=Pune|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Jadhav|first=Namdevrao|title=Khara Sambhaji|publisher=Rajamata Prakashan|year=2014|isbn=978-8191098037|location=Pune|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Sawant|first=Indrajit|title=Marathyanche Swatantrayuddha Bhag 1- Chhatrapati Sambhaji Maharaj|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>. Some of the influential sardars including ministers [[Annaji Datto Sachiv|Annaji Datto]] and other ministers conspired against Sambhaji, supported by Soyarabai, to prevent Sambhaji from succeeding the throne.<ref name=\"Mehta2005\"/>{{rp|48}} Shivaji's widow and Sambhaji's stepmother, [[Soyrabai]] after her husband's death installed the couple's son, Rajaram, a lad of 10, on the throne on 21 April 1680.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gordon|first1=Stewart|title=The Marathas 1600\u20131818|date=1993|publisher=Cambridge University|location=New York|isbn=978-0-521-26883-7|pages=91|edition= 1st publ.|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=iHK-BhVXOU4C&oi=fnd&pg=PR9&dq=sambhaji+purandar+jaisingh+shivaji+treaty&ots=S0STQ4MCke&sig=GdCbVniN6jL1mZARbVJ_SYW_t0M#v=onepage&q=%20shivaji%20aurangzeb%20escape&f=false|accessdate=5 June 2016}}</ref> News of Shivaji's death was purposefully hidden from Sambhaji by the conspirators. Upon hearing this news, Sambhaji started his preparations and took possession of the Panhala fort. He arrested the fort commander Vitthal Tryambak and senior minister Janardanpant Hanumante who were involved in the conspiracy. He also asked his father-in-law of Pilajirao Shirke to be ready with his forces at Shringarpur. Both sides were vying for the crucial support of [[Hambirrao Mohite]] the commander-in-chief of Maratha army. He was the brother of [[Soyarabai]] and maternal uncle of \ufffc[[Rajaram I|Rajaram]]\ufffc\ufffc.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Soyarabai issued orders to [[Annaji Datto Sachiv|Anaji Datto]] and [[Moropant Trimbak Pingle|Moropant]] to leave Raigad with a force of 5,000 to arrest Sambhaji at Panhala. Hambirrao was near [[Karad]] with his army of 20,000. Anaji and Moropant came to meet Hambirrao and asked for his support to arrest Sambhaji. Hambirrao refused and arrested both these ministers. On the next day Hambirrao along with his senior generals Rupaji Bhosle and Anandrao Makaji met Sambhaji at Panhala. Sambhaji was delighted at the arrival of Hambirrao on his side<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|last=Patil|first=Vishwas|title=Sambhaji|publisher=Mehta Publishing House|year=2016|isbn=9788177666519|location=Pune|pages=196-208}}</ref> . Sambhaji held a ceremony at Panhala to acknowledge Hambirrao's support. He stayed at Panhala for some time as condolence letters were coming to him from British, Portuguese, Dutch, French, Adilshahi, Qutbshahi and other neighbouring powers after Shivaji's death. Meanwhile he asked Pilajirao to secure Raigad with a force of 10,000. He was confronted by sardar Malsawant of Soyarabai's side but Pilajirao defeated and arrested him and secured the control of Raigad [[Raigad Fort|fort]]. Sambhaji formally ascended the throne on 20 July 1680. Rajaram, his wife mother [[Soyarabai]], all the senior ministers involved in the conspiracy were put under house arrest. Malsawant still kept on insulting Sambhaji and he was executed by throwing him off the cliff.(Takmak Tok cliff). Sambhaji's coronation took place of 16th January 1681. Sambhaji pardoned and restored all the ministers such as [[Janardanpant]], [[Hiroji Farzand]], Rahuji Somnath in their previously held positions. Peshwa Moropant had died meanwhile, his position was given to his son Nilopant Pingale. [[Annaji Datto Sachiv|Anaji Datto]] was also pardoned but he was transferred to Mujumdar and his former post of Suranvis was given to [[Abaji Sondev]] <ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" />. In 1681 Aurangzeb's rebel son Akbar along with Rajput chieftain Durgadas Rathore had arrived in Maharashtra to seek help against his father. Sambhaji had appointed Hiroji Farzand to negotiate with Akbar and Durgadas Rathore. The conspirators tried lure Akbar to their side to dethrone Sambhaji. They offered him half of the Maratha kingdom in return for his support to dethrone Sambhaji. The conspirators also tried to poison Sambhaji but the attempt failed. Akbar did not pay heed to their offer and instead informed Sambhaji about this conspiracy. Sambhaji quickly marched to [[Ballaleshwar Pali|Pali]] and arrested the conspirators near Sudhagad fort at Pali. Senior ministers Anaji Datto, Hiroji Farzand, Balaji Awji, Somaji Datto, Awji Balaji and others were arrested. Sambhaji had pardoned them before and they still conspired to poison him. Sambhaji gave the order to execute the traitors by trampling them under elephant. Some of Shivaji's ministers such as Annaji Datto, Hiroji Farzand and other conspirators were executed on charges of conspiracy and treason.<ref name=\"Mehta2005\"/>{{rp|48}}<ref name=\"SharmaL\u0101\u02bcibrer\u012b2004\">{{cite book|author1=Sunita Sharma|author2=K\u0332h\u0332ud\u0101 Bak\u0332h\u0332sh Oriyan\u1e6dal Pablik L\u0101\u02bcibrer\u012b|title=Veil, sceptre, and quill: profiles of eminent women, 16th- 18th centuries|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q2kaAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=30 September 2012|year=2004|publisher=Khuda Bakhsh Oriental Public Library|page=139}} \u2013 ''By June 1680 three months after Shivaji's death Rajaram was made a prisoner in the fort of [[Raigad Fort|Raigad]].\"</ref> Sambhaji arrived at Raigad and put Soyarabai and Rajaram under house arrest. Soyarabai was guilty for her actions and commited suicide by poisoning herself. Sambhaji was very sad at the demise of Soyarabai which is evident from the letter sent by him to Bakre Shastri of Kudal wherein he mentions that 'Soyarabai had a pure heart'. Sambhaji also felt very sad for the death of Balaji Awji Chitnis in the process and built a temple in the memory of [[Balaji Awji Chitnis]] at Pali. <ref name=\":3\" /> <ref name=\":2\" /> <ref name=\":1\" /> <ref name=\":4\" />. \n\n==Military expeditions and conflicts==\nShortly following Sambhaji's accession, he began his military campaigns against neighboring states. Historians have been quick to note the distinction between the more tolerant and chivalrous practices of his father Shivaji, and the more pragmatic and brutal practices of Sambhaji. \n\n===Attack on Burhanpur===\nThe fort of Burhanpur was first in the charge of Bahadur khan who later gave it to Kakar Khan. Kakar was at the duty of collecting [[Jizya]] tax from the citizens. In order to accomplish the task, Kakar Khan destroyed more than 100 temples surrounding Burhanpur and conducting torture, plunder, killing, cutting of women's ears and men's eyes for the wealth. The Jizya was collected and stored captive at the Burhanpur fort.<ref>{|url=  http://informatonaboutsambhajiraje.blogspot.com/2016/10/maratha-yodhha-early-life-sambhaji-was.html?m=1}</ref>.Sambhaji plundered and ravaged [[Burhanpur]] in 1680. His forces completely routed the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] garrison and punitively executed captives. The Marathas then looted the city and set its ports ablaze. Sambhaji then withdrew into [[Baglana]], evading the forces of Mughal commander Khan Jahan Bahadur Kokaltash.<ref>{{cite book|first=John F. |last=Richard |authorlink=John F. Richards |title=The Mughal Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HHyVh29gy4QC|accessdate=1 October 2012|date=26 January 1996|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-56603-2|page=218}}</ref> During the attack on Burhanpur, among his 20,000 troops, many of them perpetrated atrocities against Muslims, including plunder, killing, and torture.<ref name=\"richards\">{{cite book|title=The Mughal Empire|author=[[John F. Richards]]|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year=1995|pages=217\u2013223}}</ref>\n\n===Mughal Empire===\nIn 1681, Aurangzeb's fourth son [[Sultan Muhammad Akbar|Akbar]] left the Mughal court along with a few Muslim Mansabdar supporters and joined Muslim rebels in the Deccan. He was accompanied by rajput chieftain [[Durgadas Rathore]] of Marwar.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Patil|first=Vishwas|title=Sambhaji|publisher=Mehta Publishing house|year=2016|isbn=|location=Pune|pages=}}</ref> Aurangzeb in response moved his court south to [[Aurangabad, Maharashtra|Aurangabad]] and took over command of the Deccan campaign.The rebels were defeated and Akbar fled south to seek refuge with Sambhaji. Sambhaji's ministers including Annaji Datto, and other ministers took this opportunity and conspired again to enthrone Rajaram again. They signed a treasonable letter against Sambhaji in which they promised to join Akbar, to whom the letter was sent.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Eh1BAAAAMAAJ&q=annaji+datto+conspire+sambhaji&dq=annaji+datto+conspire+sambhaji&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiFl57A8KnaAhWIM48KHYM1C9sQ6AEIPTAF|title=Maharani Tarabai of Kolhapur, c. 1675-1761 A.D.|last=P\u0101\u1e6d\u012bla|first=\u015a\u0101lin\u012b|date=1987|publisher=S. Chand & Co.|isbn=9788121902694|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=43gBAAAAMAAJ&q=annaji+datto+conspire+sambhaji&dq=annaji+datto+conspire+sambhaji&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiFl57A8KnaAhWIM48KHYM1C9sQ6AEIJzAA|title=Chhatrapati Sambhaji|last=Gokhale|first=Kamal Shrikrishna|date=1978|publisher=Navakamal Publications|language=en}}</ref> Akbar gave this letter to Sambhaji.<ref name=\":0\" /> Enraged Sambhaji executed conspirators on charges of treason.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=43gBAAAAMAAJ&q=sambhaji+conspirators+execute&dq=sambhaji+conspirators+execute&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiZ3oS_9qnaAhVCwI8KHavMDjkQ6AEIKzAB|title=Chhatrapati Sambhaji|last=Gokhale|first=Kamal Shrikrishna|date=1978|publisher=Navakamal Publications|language=en}}</ref>\n\nFor fully five years, Akbar stayed with Sambhaji, hoping that the latter would lend him men and money to strike and seize the Mughal throne for himself. Unfortunately for Sambhaji, giving asylum to Akbar did not bear fruit. Eventually, Sambhaji helped Akbar flee to [[Persia]]. On the other hand, Aurangzeb after coming to Deccan never returned to his capital in the north.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Great Moghuls |first1=Bamber |last1=Gascoigne |first2=Christina |last2=Gascoigne |authorlink1=Bamber Gascoigne |publisher=Cape |year=1971 |pages=228\u2013229 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-ryFAAAAIAAJ}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Kulkarni|first1=A.R.|title=The Marathas|date=2008|publisher=Diamond Publications|location=Pune|isbn=9788184830736|edition= 1st|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N45LDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\nIn 1682, the Mughals laid siege to the Maratha fort of [[Ramsej]], but after five months of failed attempts, including planting explosive mines and building wooden towers to gain the walls, the Mughal siege failed.<ref>{{cite book|title=Itihas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MApDAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=3 August 2013|year=1976|publisher=Director of State Archives, Government of Andhra Pradesh.|pages=100\u2013103}}</ref>\n\n===Siddis of Janjira===\nThe Marathas under Shivaji came into conflict with the [[Siddi]]s, Muslims of [[Abyssinian people|Abyssinian]] descent settled in India, over the control of the Konkan coast. Shivaji was able to reduce their presence to the fortified island of [[Janjira State|Janjira]]. Sambhaji continued the Maratha campaign against them, while at that time the Siddis formed an alliance with the Mughals.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kumar|first1=Amarendra|title=KEIGWIN'S BOMBAY (1683-84) AND THE MARATHA-SIDDI NAVAL CONFLICT|journal=Proceedings of the Indian History Congress|date=2014|volume=75|pages=320\u2013324|jstor=44158397}}</ref> At the start of 1682, a Maratha army later joined by Sambhaji personally, attacked the island for thirty days, doing heavy damage but failing to breach its defenses. Sambhaji then attempted a ruse, sending a party of his people to the Siddis, claiming to be defectors. They were allowed into the fort and planned to detonate the [[gunpowder magazine]] during a coming Maratha attack. However, one of the female defectors became involved with a Siddi man and he uncovered the plot, and the infiltrators were executed. The Maratha then attempted to build a stone [[causeway]] from the shore to the island, but were interrupted halfway through when the Mughal army moved to menace Raigad. Sambhaji returned to counter them and his remaining troops were unable to overcome the Janjira garrison and the Siddi fleet protecting it.<ref name=\"Ali1996\">{{cite book|author=Shanti Sadiq Ali|title=The African Dispersal in the Deccan: From Medieval to Modern Times|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-3CPc22nMqIC&pg=PA171|accessdate=1 October 2012|date=1 January 1996|publisher=Orient Blackswan|isbn=978-81-250-0485-1|pages=171\u2013}}</ref>\n\n===Portuguese and English===\n[[Image:Chh. Sambhaji's WatanPatra.jpg|thumb|WatanPatra, grant document, by Chh. Sambhaji]]\nHaving failed to take Janjira in 1682, Sambhaji sent a commander to seize the Portuguese coastal fort of [[Anjediva Island|Anjadiva]] instead. The Marathas seized the fort, seeking to turn it into a naval base, but in April 1682 were ejected from the fort by a detachment of 200 Portuguese. This incident led to a larger conflict between the two regional powers.<ref name=\"Ali1996\"/>{{rp|171}}\n\nThe [[History of Goa#Portuguese conquest and colonisation|Portuguese colony of Goa]] at that time provided supplies to the Mughals, allowed them to use the Portuguese ports in India and pass through their territory. In order to deny this support to the Mughals, Sambhaji undertook a campaign against Portuguese Goa in late 1683, storming the colony and taking its forts.<ref name=\"Ames2000\">{{cite book|author=Glenn Joseph Ames|title=Renascent Empire?: The House of Braganza and the Quest for Stability in Portuguese Monsoon Asia c. 1640\u20131683|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MfMNfsOMUHwC&pg=PA155|year=2000|publisher=Amsterdam University Press|isbn=978-90-5356-382-3|pages=155\u2013}}</ref> The situation for the colonists became so dire that the Portuguese viceroy, [[Francisco de T\u00e1vora, conde de Alvor]] went with his remaining supporters to the cathedral where the crypt of [[Francis Xavier|Saint Francis Xavier]] was kept, where they prayed for deliverance. The viceroy had the casket opened and gave the saint's body his baton, royal credentials and a letter asking the saint's support. Sambhaji's Goa campaign was checked by the arrival of the Mughal army and navy in January 1684, forcing him to withdraw.<ref name=\"Alden1996\">{{cite book|author=Dauril Alden|title=The Making of an Enterprise: The Society of Jesus in Portugal, Its Empire, and Beyond, 1540\u20131750|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7nVIBhrRb9AC&pg=PA202|accessdate=2 October 2012|date=1 September 1996|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-2271-1|pages=202\u2013}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, in 1684 Sambhaji signed a defensive treaty with the English at Bombay, realising his need for English arms and gunpowder, particularly as their lack of artillery and explosives impeded the Maratha's ability to lay siege to fortifications. Thus reinforced, Sambhaji proceeded to take [[Pratapgad]] and a series of forts along the [[Ghats]].<ref name=\"Gordon1993\">{{cite book|author=Stewart Gordon|title=The Marathas 1600\u20131818|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iHK-BhVXOU4C&pg=PA91|accessdate=2 October 2012|date=16 September 1993|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-26883-7|pages=91\u2013}}</ref>{{rp|91}}\n\n===Mysore===\nMuch like his father Shivaji's Karnataka campaign, Sambhaji attempted in 1681 to invade [[Mysore]], then a southern principality ruled by [[Wodeyar]] [[Chikkadevaraja]]. Sambhaji's large army was repelled,<ref name=\"Gordon1993\"/>{{rp|91}} as had happened to Shivaji in 1675.<ref name=\"Chopra1992\">{{cite book|author=Pran Nath Chopra|title=Encyclopaedia of India: Karnataka|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PfNtAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2 October 2012|year=1992|publisher=Rima Pub. House}}</ref> The Chikkadevraja later made treaties and rendered tribute to the Maratha kingdom during the conflicts of 1682\u20131686. The Chikkadevraja however began to draw close to the Mughal empire and ceased to follow his treaties with the Marathas. In response, Sambhaji invaded Mysore in 1686, accompanied by his Brahmin friend and poet [[Kavi Kalash]].<ref name=\"Muddhachari1969\">{{cite book|author=B. Muddhachari|title=The Mysore-Maratha relations in the 17th century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w1PRAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2 October 2012|year=1969|publisher=Pras\u0101r\u0101nga, University of Mysore|page=106}}</ref><ref name=\"SatyanarayanaMuseums1996\">{{cite book|author1=A. Satyanarayana|author2=Karnataka (India). Directorate of Archaeology & Museums|title=History of the Wodeyars of Mysore, 1610\u20131748|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3jduAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2 October 2012|year=1996|publisher=Directorate of Archaeology and Museums|page=94}}</ref>\n\n==Capture and execution==\n[[Image:Tulapur arch.jpg|thumb|Stone arch at [[Tulapur]] confluence where Sambhaji was executed]]\n[[File:Vadhu Tulapur - Statue of Sambhaji Maharaja.JPG|thumb|upright|Statue of Sambhaji at Tulapur]]\nThe 1687 [[Battle of Wai]] saw the Maratha forces badly weakened by the Mughals. The key Maratha commander [[Hambirao Mohite]] was killed and troops began to desert the Maratha armies. Sambhaji's positions were spied upon by his own relations, the Shirke family, who had defected to the Mughals. Sambhaji and 25 of his advisors were captured by the Mughal forces of [[Muqarrab Khan]] in a skirmish at [[Sangameshwar]] in February 1689.<ref name=\"Mehta2005\"/>{{rp|47}}\n\nAccounts of Sambhaji's confrontation with the Mughal ruler and following torture, execution and disposal of his body, vary widely depending on the source, though generally all agree that he was tortured and executed on the emperor's orders.<ref name=\"Mehta2005\"/>{{rp|50}}\n\nThe captured Sambhaji and [[Kavi Kalash]] were taken to [[Pedgaon, Ahmednagar|Bahadurgad]] in present-day Ahmednagar district, where Aurangzeb humiliated them by parading them wearing clown's clothes and they were subjected to insults by Mughal soldiers. Accounts vary as to the reasons for what came next: Mughal accounts state that Sambhaji was asked to surrender his forts, treasures and names of Mughal collaborators with the Marathas and that he sealed his fate by insulting both the emperor and the Islamic prophet Muhammad during interrogation and was executed for having killed Muslims.<ref>{{cite book|first=John F. |last=Richards |authorlink=John F. Richards|title=The Mughal Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HHyVh29gy4QC|accessdate=29 September 2012|date=26 January 1996|publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-56603-2 |page=223}}</ref> The [[ulema]] of the Mughal Empire sentenced Sambhaji to death for the atrocities his troops perpetrated against Muslims in Burhanpur, including plunder, killing, rape, and torture.<ref name=\"richards\"/>\n\nMaratha accounts instead state that he was ordered to bow before Aurangzeb and convert to Islam and it was his refusal to do so, by saying that he would accept Islam on the day the emperor presented him his daughter's hand, that led to his death.<ref name=\"SBBhattacherje2009\">{{cite book | author=S. B. Bhattacherje | title=Encyclopaedia of Indian Events & Dates | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oGVSvXuCsyUC&pg=SL1-PA81 | accessdate=6 March 2012 | date=1 May 2009 | publisher=Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd | isbn=978-81-207-4074-7 | pages = A80-A81 }}</ref> By doing so he earned the title of ''Dharmaveer'' (\"protector of [[dharma]]\").<ref name=\"Bhave2000\">{{cite book|author=Y. G. Bhave|title=From the Death of Shivaji to the Death of Aurangzeb: The Critical Years|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q5kVk6msxUcC&pg=PA60|accessdate=2 October 2012|date=1 January 2000|publisher=Northern Book Centre|isbn=978-81-7211-100-7|pages=60\u2013}}</ref> Aurangzeb ordered Sambhaji and Kavi Kalash to be tortured to death; the process took over a fortnight and included plucking out their eyes and tongue, pulling out their nails and removing their skin. Sambhaji was finally killed on 11 March 1689,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/in.ernet.dli.2015.48871/2015.48871.Maasir---I---Alamgiri#page/n205/mode/2up/search/quli|title=Maasir \u2013 I \u2013 Alamgiri|website=archive.org|access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref> reportedly by tearing him apart from the front and back with [[wagh nakhe]] (metal \"tiger claws\") and beheading with an axe at [[Tulapur]] on the banks of the [[Bhima river]] near Pune.<ref name=\"Mehta2005\"/>{{rp|50}}\n\nOther accounts state that Sambhaji challenged Aurangzeb in open court and refused to convert to Islam. Dennis Kincaid writes, \"He (Sambhaji) was ordered by the Emperor to embrace Islam. He refused and was made to run the gauntlet of the whole Imperial army. Tattered and bleeding he was brought before the Emperor and repeated his refusal. His tongue was torn and again the question was put. He called for writing material and wrote 'Not even if the emperor bribed me with his daughter!' So then he was put to death by torture\".<ref name=\"Bhave2000\"/>\n\nSome accounts state that Sambhaji's body was cut into pieces and thrown into the river or that the body or portions were recaptured and cremated at the confluence of rivers at Tulapur.<ref name=\"Gokhale1978\">{{cite book|author=Kamal Shrikrishna Gokhale|title=Chhatrapati Sambhaji|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=43gBAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2 October 2012|year=1978|publisher=Navakamal Publications|page=365}}</ref><ref name=\"Organiser\">{{cite book|title=Organiser|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dk8_AQAAIAAJ|accessdate=2 October 2012|date=January 1973|publisher=Bharat Prakashan.|page=280}} \u2013 ''When they were finally thrown away, the Marathas brought Sambhaji's head to Tulapur and consigned if to fire at the confluence of the Bheema and Indrayani rivers.''</ref> Other accounts state that Sambhaji's remains were fed to the dogs.<ref>{{cite book|author=J. L. Mehta|title=Advanced Study in the History of Modern India: Volume One: 1707 \u2013 1813|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d1wUgKKzawoC&pg=PA50|accessdate=7 April 2016|date=1 January 2005|publisher=Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd|isbn=978-1-932705-54-6|page=50}}</ref>\n\n== Literary contributions ==\nSambhaji was sophisticated, educated and well-versed in a few languages other than Marathi. [[Keshav Pandit]] was employed for Sambhaji's education. Keshav Pandit, alias Keshav Bhatta of Shringarpur, was an erudite scholar in the Nitishastra and Sanskrit language and literature. He seems to have deeper knowledge of the different forms of Sanskrit literature; Hindu jurisprudence and the Puranas. He also seems to have made Sambhaji familiar with the famous works of different sciences and music written by ancient scholars in the Sanskrit language.<ref name=\"Joshi1980\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9ngBAAAAMAAJ&q=Keshav+Pandit+Sambhaji&dq=Keshav+Pandit+Sambhaji&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4nJWctqfaAhXMPo8KHa3gDC8Q6AEIJzAA|title=Chhatrapati Sambhaji, 1657\u20131689 A.D.|last=Joshi|first=Pandit Shankar|date=1980|publisher=S. Chand|language=en |pages=4\u20135}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/BudhabhushanamOfShambhurajaHDVelankarBORI1926/Budhabhushanam%20of%20Shambhuraja%20-%20HD%20Velankar%20-%20BORI%201926#page/n11/mode/2up|title=Budhabhushanam Of Shambhuraja HD Velankar BORI 1926|website=archive.org|access-date=7 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nThere are several books by Sambhaji. The most notable is ''Budhbhushanam''  which is in Sanskrit and three other known books ''Nayikabhed'', ''Saatsatak'', ''Nakhshikha'' are in Hindi language.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/BudhabhushanamOfShambhurajaHDVelankarBORI1926/Budhabhushanam%20of%20Shambhuraja%20-%20HD%20Velankar%20-%20BORI%201926#page/n13/mode/2up|title=Budhabhushanam Of Shambhuraja HD Velankar BORI 1926|website=archive.org|access-date=7 April 2018}}</ref> In ''Budhbhushanam'', Sambhaji wrote poetry on politics. In the book Sambhaji writes about dos and don'ts for a king and discusses military tactics. The first few ''[[sloka meter|slokas]]'' are praises for Shahaji (his grandfather) and his father Shivaji. In ''Budhbhushan'' Sambhaji considers Shivaji to be the incarnation that saved the earth and restored righteousness.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/BudhabhushanamOfShambhurajaHDVelankarBORI1926/Budhabhushanam%20of%20Shambhuraja%20-%20HD%20Velankar%20-%20BORI%201926#page/n15/mode/2up|title=Budhabhushanam Of Shambhuraja HD Velankar BORI 1926|website=archive.org|access-date=7 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Succession==\nThe Maratha Kingdom was put into disarray by Sambhaji's death and his younger [[half-brother]] [[Rajaram Chhatrapati]] assumed the throne. Rajaram shifted the Maratha capital far south to [[Gingee|Jinji]], while Maratha guerrilla fighters under [[Santaji Ghorpade]] and [[Dhanaji Jadhav]] continued to harass the Mughal army. A few days after Sambhaji's death, the capital [[Raigad Fort]] fell to the Mughals. Sambhaji's widow, Yesubai, son, [[Chhattrapati Shahu|Shahu]] and Shivaji's widow, [[Sakvarbai]]  were captured; Sakvarbai died in Mughal captivity.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Mehta|first1=J. L.|title=Advanced study in the history of modern India, 1707\u20131813|date=2005|publisher=New Dawn Press, Inc.|location=Slough|isbn=9781932705546|page=47}}</ref> Shahu, who was seven years of age when captured, remained prisoner of the Mughals for 18 years from February 1689 until Mughal Emperor [[Aurangzeb]]'s death in 1707. Shahu was then set free by Emperor [[Muhammad Azam Shah]], son of Aurangzeb. After his release Shahu had to fight a brief war with his aunt [[Tarabai]], Rajaram's widow who claimed the throne for her own son, Shivaji II.<ref>{{citation | first = Malgonkar |last = Manohar | title = The Sea Hawk: Life and Battles of Kanoji Angrey | year = 1959 | page = 63}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=A. Vijaya Kumari |author2=Sepuri Bhaskar |title=Social change among Balijas: majority community of Andhra Pradesh|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r-ffeWmj2JUC&pg=PA6 |publisher=MD |accessdate=24 June 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"sen4\">{{Cite book |last=Sen |first=Sailendra |title=A Textbook of Medieval Indian History |publisher=Primus Books |year=2013 |isbn=978-93-80607-34-4 |pages=201\u2013202}}</ref> The Mughals kept Yesubai captive to ensure that Shahu adhered to the terms of his release. She was released in 1719 when Marathas became strong enough under Shahu and Peshwa [[Balaji Vishwanath]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Quarterly Review of Historical Studies|url=https://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13121|year=1971|publisher=Institute of Historical Studies.}}</ref>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{Succession box|\n before=[[Shivaji]] |\n title=[[Chhatrapati]] of the<br /> [[Maratha Empire]] |\n years=1680\u20131689 |\n after=[[Rajaram Chhatrapati|Rajaram]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bhosale|Bhosale family ancestry]]\n*[[Maratha clan system]]\n*[[Marathi people]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n<nowiki/>{{Commons category}}\n\n{{MarathaEmpire}}\n{{Shivaji}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1657 births]]\n[[Category:1689 deaths]]\n[[Category:17th-century Indian monarchs]]\n[[Category:Executed Indian people]]\n[[Category:Hindu martyrs]]\n[[Category:Hindu monarchs]]\n[[Category:Marathi people]]\n[[Category:People executed by India by decapitation]]\n[[Category:People executed by the Mughal Empire]]\n[[Category:People from Maharashtra]]\n", "name_user": "Charvak157", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sambhaji"}
{"title_page": "Alberto M\u00e1rcico", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Alberto M\u00e1rcico\n| image = Marcico ferro c oeste.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| caption = M\u00e1rcico with [[Ferro Carril Oeste]] in 1982\n| fullname = Alberto Jos\u00e9 M\u00e1rcico\n| height = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1960|5|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Corrientes]], Argentina\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1980\u20131985\n| clubs1 = [[Ferro Carril Oeste]]\n| caps1 = 210\n| goals1 = 44\n| years2 = 1986\u20131992\n| clubs2 = [[Toulouse FC|Toulouse]]\n| caps2 = 227\n| goals2 = 64\n| years3 = 1992\u20131995\n| clubs3 = [[Boca Juniors]]\n| caps3 = 126\n| goals3 = 13\n| years4 = 1996\u20131998\n| clubs4 = [[Club de Gimnasia y Esgrima La Plata|Gimnasia y Esgrima (LP)]]\n| caps4 = 31\n| goals4 = 10\n| nationalyears1 = 1983\u20131992\n| nationalteam1 = [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 15\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n}}\n'''Alberto Jos\u00e9 M\u00e1rcico''' (born 13 May 1960) is an Argentine former professional [[Association football|football]] [[midfielder]]. He played club football in Argentina]] and France as well as representing the [[Argentina national football team]] on 15 occasions between 1983 and 1992, including at the [[1983 Copa Am\u00e9rica]].\n\n==Career==\nM\u00e1rcico made his professional debut in 1980 with [[Ferro Carril Oeste]] under manager [[Carlos Timoteo Griguol]]. In 1982, he was part of the team that won the Nacional championship without losing a single game. In 1984, he helped Ferro to win their second Nacional and was awarded the 1984 [[Player of the Year of Argentina|Player of the Year]] title.\n\nM\u00e1rcico was sold to French club [[Toulouse FC]] where he played for six years before returning to Argentina in 1992 to play for [[Boca Juniors]] where he won three titles with the club, but his career was interrupted several times with injuries. One of the highlights of his time with Boca came on 18 June 1995, when he scored a goal in a 4\u20132 win against fierce rivals [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]] in the [[Supercl\u00e1sico|supercl\u00e1sico derby]] at [[River Plate Stadium|Estadio Monumental]].\n\nIn 1996, he was offered a chance to return to Ferro, but he chose instead to rejoin former manager Griguol, who was then in charge of [[Club de Gimnasia y Esgrima La Plata|Gimnasia de La Plata]]. M\u00e1rcico started his time at Gimnasia in fine form scoring 10 goals in 14 games, but then the injuries returned, eventually forcing him to quit the game in 1998.\n\nAfter retirement M\u00e1rcico went into coaching, he returned to Boca in 2002 as field assistant to [[Oscar Tab\u00e1rez]]. He was also head coach of [[Club Atl\u00e9tico Nueva Chicago|Nueva Chicago]] for a short spell. He now runs a football school in the French city of [[Auch]].\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''Ferro Carril Oeste'''\n*[[Primera Divisi\u00f3n Argentina]] [[Nacional championship]]: 1982, 1984\n\n'''Boca Juniors'''\n*[[Primera Divisi\u00f3n Argentina]] Apertura: 1992\n*[[Supercopa Masters]]: 1992\n*[[Copa de Oro]]: 1992\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Footballer of the Year of Argentina]]: 1984\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commonscatinline}}\n*{{in lang|es}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20120726142528/http://www.futbolxxi.com/Futbolista.aspx?ID=6853&SEOFutbolista=Marcico+Alberto+Jose Argentine Primera statistics]\n\n{{Argentina Squad 1983 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Argentine Footballer of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marcico, Alberto}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Corrientes Province]]\n[[Category:Argentine footballers]]\n[[Category:Argentina international footballers]]\n[[Category:1983 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Ferro Carril Oeste footballers]]\n[[Category:Toulouse FC players]]\n[[Category:Boca Juniors footballers]]\n[[Category:Gimnasia y Esgrima de La Plata footballers]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:Argentine football managers]]\n[[Category:Nueva Chicago managers]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Alberto M\u00e1rcico\n| image = Marcico ferro c oeste.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| caption = M\u00e1rcico with [[Ferro Carril Oeste]] in 1982\n| fullname = Alberto Jos\u00e9 M\u00e1rcico\n| height = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1960|5|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Corrientes]], Argentina\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1980\u20131985\n| clubs1 = [[Ferro Carril Oeste]]\n| caps1 = 210\n| goals1 = 44\n| years2 = 1986\u20131992\n| clubs2 = [[Toulouse FC|Toulouse]]\n| caps2 = 227\n| goals2 = 64\n| years3 = 1992\u20131995\n| clubs3 = [[Boca Juniors]]\n| caps3 = 126\n| goals3 = 13\n| years4 = 1996\u20131998\n| clubs4 = [[Club de Gimnasia y Esgrima La Plata|Gimnasia y Esgrima (LP)]]\n| caps4 = 31\n| goals4 = 10\n| nationalyears1 = 1983\u20131992\n| nationalteam1 = [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 15\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n}}\n'''Alberto Jos\u00e9 M\u00e1rcico''' (born 13 May 1960) is an Argentine former professional [[Association football|football]] [[midfielder]]. He played club football in Argentina]] and France as well as representing the [[Argentina national football team]] on 15 occasions between 1983 and 1992, including at the [[1983 Copa Am\u00e9rica]].\n\nM\u00e1rcico made his professional debut in 1980 with [[Ferro Carril Oeste]] under manager [[Carlos Timoteo Griguol]]. In 1982, he was part of the team that won the Nacional championship without losing a single game. In 1984, he helped Ferro to win their second Nacional and was awarded the 1984 [[Player of the Year of Argentina|Player of the Year]] title.\n\nM\u00e1rcico was sold to French club [[Toulouse FC]] where he played for six years before returning to Argentina in 1992 to play for [[Boca Juniors]] where he won three titles with the club, but his career was interrupted several times with injuries. One of the highlights of his time with Boca came on 18 June 1995, when he scored a goal in a 4\u20132 win against fierce rivals [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]] in the [[Supercl\u00e1sico|supercl\u00e1sico derby]] at [[River Plate Stadium|Estadio Monumental]].\n\nIn 1996, he was offered a chance to return to Ferro, but he chose instead to rejoin former manager Griguol, who was then in charge of [[Club de Gimnasia y Esgrima La Plata|Gimnasia de La Plata]]. M\u00e1rcico started his time at Gimnasia in fine form scoring 10 goals in 14 games, but then the injuries returned, eventually forcing him to quit the game in 1998.\n\nAfter retirement M\u00e1rcico went into coaching, he returned to Boca in 2002 as field assistant to [[Oscar Tab\u00e1rez]]. He was also head coach of [[Club Atl\u00e9tico Nueva Chicago|Nueva Chicago]] for a short spell. He now runs a football school in the [[France|French]] city of [[Auch]].\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''Ferro Carril Oeste'''\n*[[Primera Divisi\u00f3n Argentina]] [[Nacional championship]]: 1982, 1984\n\n'''Boca Juniors'''\n*[[Primera Divisi\u00f3n Argentina]] Apertura: 1992\n*[[Supercopa Masters]]: 1992\n*[[Copa de Oro]]: 1992\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Footballer of the Year of Argentina]]: 1984\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commonscatinline}}\n*{{in lang|es}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20120726142528/http://www.futbolxxi.com/Futbolista.aspx?ID=6853&SEOFutbolista=Marcico+Alberto+Jose Argentine Primera statistics]\n\n{{Argentina Squad 1983 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Argentine Footballer of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marcico, Alberto}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Corrientes Province]]\n[[Category:Argentine footballers]]\n[[Category:Argentina international footballers]]\n[[Category:1983 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Ferro Carril Oeste footballers]]\n[[Category:Toulouse FC players]]\n[[Category:Boca Juniors footballers]]\n[[Category:Gimnasia y Esgrima de La Plata footballers]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:Argentine football managers]]\n[[Category:Nueva Chicago managers]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add \"Career\" heading.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alberto_M%C3%A1rcico"}
{"title_page": "Kirriereoch Hill", "text_new": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Kirriereoch Hill\n| photo = Along The Track - geograph.org.uk - 1540312.jpg\n| photo_caption =  A forestry road in Kirriereoch Forest towards Kirriereoch Hill behind.\n| elevation_m = 786\n| elevation_ref = \n| prominence = 150.2m \n| prominence_ref = <ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1691|title = Kirriereoch Hill|publisher = hillbagging.co.uk|accessdate = 22 October 2019}}</ref>\n| listing = [[Marilyn (hill)|Marilyn]], [[List of Donald mountains in Scotland|Donald]]\n| translation = Striped [[Cirque|Corrie]] (Coire Riabhach)\n| language = [[Scottish Gaelic]]\n| location = [[South Ayrshire]], [[Dumfries and Galloway]], [[Scotland]]\n| range = [[Galloway Hills]]\n| grid_ref_UK = NX420870\n| map               = Scotland\n| topo = [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Landranger'' 77\n}}\n\n'''Kirriereoch Hill''' is a hill in the [[Range of the Awful Hand]] in the [[Galloway Hills]], part of the [[Southern Uplands]] of  [[Scotland]]. It lies on the border of the old counties of [[Ayrshire]] and [[Kirkcudbrightshire]], or the modern regions of [[Dumfries and Galloway]] and [[South Ayrshire]]. Kirriereoch Hill was classified as a [[Hill lists in the British Isles#Corbetts|Corbett]] and Marilyn but then deleted from these lists in 1984 due to not being thought to achieve the respective prominence criteria.  \n\nIn August 2015 the hill was re-listed as a Marilyn<ref>http://www.rhb.org.uk/</ref> after having been surveyed to have a 150.2m prominence.  However, since this is less than the 152.4m required, the hill will not be re-listed as a Corbett.<ref>http://www.hills-database.co.uk/news.html</ref>\n\n==Walking==\nThe traverse of the Range of the Awful Hand is a classic long hillwalk, taking in Kirriereoch Hill. \n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080807124741/http://www.needlesports.com/galloway/walking.htm Information on Hill Walking in the Galloway Hills]\n* [http://www.ayrshirescotland.com/kirriereoch-hike.html Photo Tour of hiking Kirriereoch and Tarfessock from Kirriereoch Car Park]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|55.15204|-4.48108|type:landmark_region:GB_source:enwiki-osgb36(NX420870)|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Marilyns of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Donalds]]\n[[Category:Mountains and hills of Dumfries and Galloway]]\n[[Category:Highest points of historic Scottish counties]]\n\n\n{{DumfriesGalloway-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Kirriereoch Hill\n| photo = Along The Track - geograph.org.uk - 1540312.jpg\n| photo_caption =  A forestry road in Kirriereoch Forest towards Kirriereoch Hill behind.\n| elevation_m = 786\n| elevation_ref = \n| prominence = 150.2m \n| prominence_ref = <ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1691|title = Kirriereoch Hill|publisher = hillbagging.co.uk|accessdate = 22 October 2019}}</ref>\n| listing = [[Marilyn (hill)|Marilyn]], [[List of Donald mountains in Scotland|Donald]]\n| translation = Striped [[Cirque|Corrie]] (Coire Riabhach)\n| language = [[Scottish Gaelic]]\n| location = [[South Ayrshire]], [[Dumfries and Galloway]], [[Scotland]]\n| range = [[Galloway Hills]]\n| grid_ref_UK = NX420870\n| map               = Scotland\n| topo = [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Landranger'' 77\n}}\n\n'''Kirriereoch Hill''' is a hill in the [[Range of the Awful Hand]] in the [[Southern Uplands]] of southern [[Scotland]]. It lies on the border of the old counties of [[Ayrshire]] and [[Kirkcudbrightshire]], or the modern regions of [[Dumfries and Galloway]] and [[South Ayrshire]]. Kirriereoch Hill was classified as a [[Hill lists in the British Isles#Corbetts|Corbett]] and Marilyn but then deleted from these lists in 1984 due to not being thought to achieve the respective prominence criteria.  \n\nIn August 2015 the hill was re-listed as a Marilyn<ref>http://www.rhb.org.uk/</ref> after having been surveyed to have a 150.2m prominence.  However, since this is less than the 152.4m required, the hill will not be re-listed as a Corbett.<ref>http://www.hills-database.co.uk/news.html</ref>\n\n==Walking==\nThe traverse of the Range of the Awful Hand is a classic long hillwalk, taking in Kirriereoch Hill. \n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080807124741/http://www.needlesports.com/galloway/walking.htm Information on Hill Walking in the Galloway Hills]\n* [http://www.ayrshirescotland.com/kirriereoch-hike.html Photo Tour of hiking Kirriereoch and Tarfessock from Kirriereoch Car Park]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|55.15204|-4.48108|type:landmark_region:GB_source:enwiki-osgb36(NX420870)|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Marilyns of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Donalds]]\n[[Category:Mountains and hills of Dumfries and Galloway]]\n[[Category:Highest points of historic Scottish counties]]\n\n\n{{DumfriesGalloway-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iangpark", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kirriereoch_Hill"}
